<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru a0689 03-17 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Lawmaker Accuses Pan Am and US Gov't; Bits Of Suspect Suitcase
Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with report officials analyzing
bits of suitcase that held explosives. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Politicians of...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of those killed by the bomb that
destroyed Pan Am Flight 103 should direct their anger at the airline
and the U.S. government, not Britain, a legislator of the governing
party said Friday.
   Pan Am confirmed it had been warned by the West German government
Nov. 10 about the kind of radio-cassette player bomb involved.
   In Washington, Bush administration officials said investigators
believe they found bits of the suitcase that contained the plastic
explosive that destroyed the Pan Am jumbo jet in December, the New
York Times reported Saturday.
   The officials, who spoke anonymously, said experts are analyzing
the chemical makeup of the shards to determine the suitcase brand
and trace the owner, the Times reported.
   Politicians of the opposition Labor Party charged Transport
Secretary Paul Channon with bungling a warning dated two days before
the disaster but not mailed until several days later.
   John Prescott, the Labor transportation spokesman, accused the
government of planting stories in several London newspapers Friday
that said the bomber was identified or even arrested.
   Scottish and West German authorities denied the reports of an
arrest.
   Investigators have said a bomb in a radio-cassette player brought
the Boeing 747 down Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard and 11
residents of the market town of Lockerbie, Scotland.
   David Wilshire of the Conservative Party, who specializes in
transportation issues, said some relatives of victims have been
``blaming the British government, blaming Heathrow, blaming anybody
except the people I think they ought to be complaining about, namely
the American government and Pan Am.''
   West Germany had warned Pan Am, which also received a warning
from the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration on Nov. 18, Wilshire
said, ``so what has it got to do with the British government? Are
Pan Am deaf or not?''
   In New York, Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon confirmed Friday
that the West German government's warning was received Nov. 10.
   Responding to Wilshire's charge that the airline ``forgot to tell
anybody'' about earlier warnings, she said: ``Frankly, I don't think
it's for the company to disclose that.''
   Ms. Hanlon said Pan Am tightened security after receiving the
warning and those precautions remained in effect.
   The West German warning followed the arrest Oct. 26 of 13 alleged
members of a radical Palestinian group, the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command. Authorities reported
seizing a radio-cassette player bomb with a detonator rigged to go
off at high altitude.
   West German officials briefed representatives of the United
States, Britain and other nations in November about the discovery,
Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for West Germany's chief prosecutor,
said Friday in Karlsruhe.
   ``There were pictures and an explanation of how the bomb
functioned,'' he said. ``This was about three weeks after it was
found because it took time to analyze the device.''
   Prechtel said the West Germans told their colleagues such a
device could blow up a jetliner, but did not name a specific threat.
   The FAA notified U.S. flag carriers, including Pan Am, on Nov.
18, and Britain notified its national carriers Nov. 22.
   Criticism of Channon arose this week with the disclosure that the
Transport Department prepared a warning dated Dec. 19, two days
before the disaster, that included photographs of a mock
radio-cassette bomb and sent it by mail.
   Channon told The Times of London the warning was not mailed until
after the disaster, but he insisted it contained no information not
already gven to Pan Am.
   At issue are two warnings: the November alert from West Germany
and an anonymous telephone call received Dec. 5 by the U.S. Embassy
in Helsinki, Finland, claiming a Palestinian group would attack a
U.S.-bound Pan Am flight originating in Frankfurt within two weeks.
   Elizabeth Delude-Dix, an American whose Irish husband was killed
on Flight 103, said Thursday she was ``bewildered and also very
angry.''
   ``Now we know that the government had information which told them
the carrier that would be affected _ Pan American; the origin of the
flight _ Frankfurt; that the threatened period was during the month
of December, and now we've learned that they also had information
about the exact kind of bomb that was used.''
   Lord Fraser, Scotland's senior law enforcement officer, said
Friday the Helsinki warning was bogus.
   ``Police officers went to Helsinki and made inquiries into that
particular warning _ which was made anonymously _ and the conclusion
reached now is that that phone call has not got any relevance to the
Lockerbie disaster or the subsequent inquiry,'' he said.
   Finnish authorities said in December they knew the man who made
the threat, and several previous ones, and the man who allegedly was
to plant the bomb. fe They concluded the caller was pursuing a
grudge and the man he accused was harmless.
</TEXT>
