<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-TruceVillage     03-17 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Truce Village,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Koreans Still Assail US At Truce Village</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With U.S. soldiers watching from guard
towers on the other side of the border, Maj. Kang Sung Nam of the
North Korean army launched a verbal assault on the Americans,
blaming them for dividing the Korean people.
   ``Panmunjom is just a military demarcation line which the
imperialist Americans drew to divide the Korean people,'' Kang told
tourists from Hong Kong during a visit to the snow-dusted truce
village on the border of North and South Korea.
   ``We hope you can go back and tell your people that we Koreans
are longing for reunification.''
   Kang then presented each tourist with a lapel pin depicting two
hands shaking across the Korean peninsula set on a background of the
North Korean flag.
   Although hundreds of thousands of troops from North and South man
the tense 155-mile-long demilitarized zone, Panmunjom is a tourist
attraction for both sides.
   The official North Korean tour of Panmunjom includes the use of a
large-scale model to explain the demilitarized zone that was set up
after the Korean War. It also includes as a visit to one of the
large huts that straddle the demarcation line, where the two sides
have negotiated since the armistice in 1953.
   The North Koreans offer a version of the 1950-53 Korean War
markedly different from that of the South Koreans and Americans, who
fought under the banner of the United Nations Command.
   Visitors are shown a 20-minute documentary accusing the United
States of invading the Communist North, using chemical weapons and
bearing sole responsibility for the peninsula's division. The film
features close-ups of wounded Korean civilians and surrendering U.S.
soldiers.
   The documentary does not mention, however, that it was North
Korea's invasion of the South on June 25, 1950 that set off the war,
nor does it refer to the Chinese who entered the conflict to help
North Korea recover from severe military setbacks.
   Kang repeatedly maintained that at the 1953 truce signing in
Panmunjom, the South Korean representative was unable to speak for
his people because, he said, the negotiations were dominated by the
United States.
   The North and South remain technically at war, with each
government claiming to be the legitimate ruler of all Korea.
   But in recent months, the two sides have been exchanging
proposals on ending the confrontation and Panmunjom, the site of the
latest round of political talks, once again has been the focus of
attention.
   Panmunjom became neutral after the war but has been a symbol of
the division and tension on the peninsula to both North and South.
   The heavily militarized Korean peninsula includes an estimated
850,000 military regulars in North Korean and 650,000 soldiers in
South Korea, supported by a 42,000-member U.S. military contingent.
   But North Korean officials talk as though any hostilities would
come from the South.
   ``The People's Army is here to protect you,'' tour guide Yoon Mu
Ho reassured the tourists as eight North Korean soldiers stood
stiffly at attention at the truce village huts.
</TEXT>
