<FIRST>r a PM-PackerCelebration     03-17 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Packer Celebration,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Hopes To Cash In On Well-Known Cannibal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists are digging up the century-old
remains of five prospectors caught in a snowstorm and eaten by one
of their companions, and residents hope to cash in on the notoriety
surrounding the case.
   Not everyone is pleased with the fuss being made over Alferd
Packer's cannibalism during the winter of 1874.
   ``I run into some people who wonder if we ought to give so much
attention to Alferd Packer,'' said Grant Houston, president of the
Hinsdale County Historical Society.
   ``There are a lot more worthy people who have passed through
here, but they didn't commit cannibalism. So they're boring,
compared with Packer and his hold on the popular imagination.''
   Packer was the sole survivor in a party of six prospectors who
got caught in snows near Slumgullion Pass, and he later admitted
eating the flesh of his five companions.
   He insisted he killed only one, in self-defense, and told
conflicting tales about the other deaths.
   While scientists this summer begin exhuming the victims' bones to
determine how they died, residents of the tourism-dependent county
plan a number of special events celebrating Packer's notoriety.
   The county museum, which will open in June, will display Packer
relics, including shackles that held him and a model gallows
intended to hang him. In April 1883 Packer was convicted of
manslaughter, served a brief sentence and was pardoned in 1901. He
died a free man.
   In July, a drama based on the Packer trial will be performed in
the second-floor courtroom where Packer was tried. Members of the
audience will site as jury at each performance.
   A full line of Packer souvenirs for tourists is expected as well.
   The lead researcher of the exhumation is not amused.
   ``If this all gets out of hand, we'll just pack up and leave,''
said James E. Starrs, professor of law and forensic science at
George Washington University in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
