<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0840EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d e BC-Opera     03-17 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Presents Emotional `Rigoletto'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Verdi's ``Rigoletto,'' when played and sung well,
can reach inside a listener and stir up the emotions.
   The Metropolitan Opera, in its first performance of ``Rigoletto''
this season, did just that.
   Leo Nucci, who's singing in four operas at the Met this season,
sang the title role beautifully. When Nucci was singing, before
entering his house in Act 1, we feared he was just walking through
the part. But when events became emotional for Rigoletto, Nucci
became emotional. He greeted his daughter with love. Later, after
she has been raped, he is moving in his distress and tenderness for
her feelings. Rigoletto has been a callous man before, but Nucci
melts a listener's heart when singing a father's anguish.
   Hei-Kyung Hong sang Gilda, the daughter. Her voice is honey sweet
and so clear that it conveys purity and even a spiritual quality.
She sang ``Caro nome'' slowly instead of making a dazzling display
of fast coloratura. That such a girl is in love, then harmed, then
decides to die to save the unworthy man she loves makes her story
more moving than usual.
   Taro Ichihara sang the Duke. In Act 1, his voice sounded grainy,
tense on top and too mellow for a tenor in the low register.
However, after he warmed up his voice sounded more unified and made
a strongly favorable impression.
   Timothy Noble was good as Monterone, who puts a curse on
Rigoletto. When he does that, the lighting is dramatic. Nucci takes
his jester's cap off, making Rigoletto look like a person, not a
clown. The only strong light is on his horrified face. Monterone is
dimly seen. Otherwise, only lighted candles, held by chorus members,
are seen.
   Bass Jan-Hendrik Rootering also was vocally strong as the
assassin, Sparafucile.
   The orchestra and chorus were secure under conducting by Nello
Santi. He has conducted the opera at the Met before. Only four
singers of the 13 principals had sung their roles in the house
before.
   This production, which has a revolving round center structure
looking like a big wedding cake, was new in 1977. We haven't liked
it but it does provide a round balcony one flight up where
characters can sing and observe. Next season, the Met will have a
new ``Rigoletto'' production, with Nucci again in the title role and
Luciano Pavarotti as the Duke.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PolicyReview     03-17 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Policy Review,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Administration Analysts Toil Away on Policy Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pace is picking up. The analysts are
marshaling their arguments. The specialists are checking their
figures. The prognosticators are peering into their crystal balls.
   This is the chance for defense and foreign affairs experts to
make their mark in the nearly brand new Bush administration. It is
their chance to influence policy.
   Some of them have come out of the ``think tanks'' for just this
purpose. Others are grizzled veterans of the Pentagon, the State
Department and the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
   What they are busily working on is a four-part policy report, due
April 21, that is bound to have a heavy impact on how the United
States deals with the Soviet Union, not to mention other adversaries
and allies.
   For instance, President Bush will not set a date for a resumption
of strategic weapons reduction negotiations with the Soviets until
the report is in and digested.
   The four parts are: an overall review of existing U.S. defense
forces; policy needs for the 1990s; whether changes are needed in
conventional and nuclear forces; arms control policy.
   The four parts are to be completed in sequence. At this stage,
the first is going through revisions, the second is about to be put
down in draft form. The third and fourth parts depend on the results
of the first two studies.
   With the final deadline more than a month away, the Bush
administration is likely to feel continuing heat from critics who
complain of foot-dragging.
   U.S. policy is taking shape at a very slow pace.
   Congress is demanding an early answer to what kind of mobile
missile the United States will add to its nuclear arsenal. The
choices are a single-warhead Midgetman on trucks, or the huge,
10-warhead MX launched from railroad cars.
   Then there is the question of how hard the Bush administration
wants to pursue a space-based anti-missile program. Known popularly
as Star Wars, it was dear to the heart of President Reagan, but not
to most members of Congress. There is a suspicion Bush and national
security adviser Brent Scowcroft are skeptical about developing a
reliable scheme to shoot down Soviet ballistic missiles in space.
   The Soviets, meanwhile, with a touch of impatience, want to know
when strategic weapons reductions talks will be resumed. A treaty to
cut long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear submarines by 30
percent to 50 percent, depending on the system of counting, was
about 90 percent done when talks in Geneva were suspended last
December.
   There was a tentative agreement to resume in mid-February, but
Bush ordered an indefinite postponement for the policy review. The
10 percent of the treaty that isn`t finished is a very tough 10
percent. Among the unsettled problems are whether to try to limit
mobile missiles and how to verify compliance with negotiated
cutbacks.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze tried to get
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to set a date for a resumption
when they met in Vienna March 7. But Baker said the review had to be
completed first. However, they decided to meet in Moscow sometime in
the first half of May to begin preparations for a superpower summit
meeting.
   With winter just receding from Washington, the April 21 deadline
and the Baker-Shevardnadze meeting in May seem far away. But the
clock is ticking, and all those experts and analysts want to polish
their assessments in the most convincing way.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers diplomacy and arms control
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
