<FIRST>r a PM-MayorSuspension     03-17 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayor Suspension,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiny Town Having Trouble Keeping Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARYVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Florida Panhandle town is having
trouble keeping public officials in office because of their run-ins
with the law.
   Three officials have been ousted in the last year, including
former Mayor John Ed French, who has been removed from two different
jobs.
   ``I've had this happen so many times I'm used to it,'' French
said this week. ``Why is it that I was qualified to seek public
office, but not hold it?''
   Gov. Bob Martinez suspended French as mayor last year following
his conviction on an aggravated battery charge. French then was
hired as city manager but the governor suspended him from that job,
too, saying his appointment was made illegally.
   Undeterred, French won re-election as mayor last November, but
Martinez removed him from both offices _ through an executive order
Tuesday _ after an appeals court upheld his conviction in January.
State law prohibits convicted felons from holding public office.
   Walter Anderson, who lost to French in the mayoral election last
year, was named temporary mayor, but a formal move to replace French
with Anderson failed on a 2-2 vote of the City Council on Tuesday.
   The fifth councilman, Jerry Lee Griffin, was unable to vote
because Martinez had suspended Griffin after he was charged with
possession of beer with intent to distribute without a license.
   City Clerk Cheryl Green was fired last month after being accused
of embezzling from the city.
   ``We don't lack many episodes for a soap opera,'' French said.
</TEXT>
