<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings Bjt   03-17 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Gives Green Light to Impeachment Trial of Judge Hastings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Round two in the impeachment trial of Judge
Alcee L. Hastings begins today following Senate refusal to dismiss
charges that he plotted to get a $150,000 bribe and lied about it at
his trial.
   Senate leaders named a 12-member committee Thursday to hear
evidence after the lawmakers firmly refused to drop 16 of the 17
impeachment articles against the 52-year-old Hastings, the first
black federal judge in Florida history.
   Earlier, the Senate deliberated for 2{ hours behind closed doors
and then voted 93-0 against dismissal of an article accusing
Hastings of perjury at the 1983 trial that ended in his acquittal of
charges that he conspired to obtain the payoff.
   The Senate voted 92-1 against dismissal of the first 15 articles,
which accused him of plotting with a Washington attorney to take the
bribe.
   Hastings did not seek dismissal of an unrelated article accusing
him of disclosing information obtained from a wiretap and thus
wrecking a federal investigation of Miami-area corruption.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, was the only senator to vote
for dismissal of the first 15 articles.
   Metzenbaum press secretary Nancy Coffey said the senator believed
it might be unconstitutional to hold an impeachment trial on the
conspiracy charges when Hastings already had been acquitted of them
by a jury.
   ``The senator had constitutional concerns about double
jeopardy,'' Coffey said.
   The double jeopardy argument was the spearhead of Hastings'
defense when he took the Senate floor in a personal appeal to the
lawmakers for dismissal of the charges.
   ``I proclaimed my innocence then as I have from the outset and as
I do now,'' Hastings declared.
   Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, one of several prosecutors from the
House of Representatives, scoffed at the judge's claim that double
jeopardy protection applies to an impeachment trial. He urged the
senators to remove Hastings from the bench and shut off his $89,500
annual salary because of ``his inexcusable breaches of the public
trust.''
   Evidence now is to be presented to the 12-member committee and
videotaped for the benefit of senators too busy to attend the weeks
of sessions that are expected in the case. Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, scheduled an organizational meeting for the panel
today.
   Once the evidence has been heard, the matter then will be
returned to the Senate floor for a final decision.
   Members of the panel are: Sens. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; Patrick J.
Leahy, D-Vt.; Joe Lieberman, D-Conn.; David Pryor, D-Ark.; Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb.; Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev.; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.;
David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Warren Rudman, R-N.H.; Slade Gorton,
R-Wash.; Christopher S. Bond, R-Mo., and Conrad Burns, R-Mont.
   It appeared clear that the committee would have to slog through
weeks of testimony and tactical maneuvering before coming up with
its final report.
   The articles of impeachment say Hastings conspired with
Washington attorney William Borders in 1981 to reduce the punishment
of two brothers, Frank and Tom Romano of Miami, from three-year
prison sentences to probation. They had been convicted in Hastings'
court of skimming from a Teamsters pension fund loan.
   In return, Hastings and Borders allegedly were to receive
$150,000.
   The Romano brothers, both of whom have since died, refused to pay
any bribe, but the FBI mounted a sting-type operation and arrested
Borders pulling out of a suburban Virginia motel with a garment bag
containing $125,000 handed to him by an undercover agent
masquerading as Frank Romano.
   Borders was convicted in a separate trial of conspiracy and went
to prison. The House voted the articles of impeachment against
Hastings on a 413-3 vote Aug. 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
