<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     03-17 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>167 Thai Fishermen Freed After Poaching Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's pro-Vietnamese government has
freed 167 Thai fishermen caught poaching in its waters, officials
said.
   As a result of years of uncontrolled exploitation, most of Thai's
marine resources have been depleted so its huge fleet often fishes
illegally in neighboring countries' waters.
   Thai officials said the Cambodians later today also plan to
release 91 Thais who illegally crossed into Cambodia to mine for
sapphires and rubies.
   The fishermen, accompanied by several Thai legislators, returned
Thursday to eastern Trat province aboard a Cambodian trawler, an
official in the Prime Minister's office said. The official said the
fishermen were arrested several months ago in southern Kompongsom
province.
   Thai officials say about 300 other Thais, mostly fishermen, are
believed still held in Cambodian jails. Securing their release is
difficult because Thailand does not recognize the government there,
but relations have improved since the January visit of Cambodian
Prime Minister Hun Sen to Bangkok.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and Thailand backs
guerrillas fighting the Vietnamese.
</TEXT>
