<DOCNO> AP890317-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush'sBushes     03-17 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush's Bushes,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Men Who Hold George Bush's Old Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Thomas Pickering writes to the home office
that he likes the work but he can never keep straight the names of
all those little countries, the boss might say he understands.
   That's because the home office is the White House, the boss is
George Bush and Pickering, like several other officials, is holding
a job the president once had in his previous incarnations.
   So that means if James R. Lilley cables from Beijing that he
enjoys the job but sure would like to sink his teeth into an
old-fashioned ham and cheese on rye, Bush might nod that he knows
just what Lilley means.
   And if William H. Webster says the work is fine, but there is
something just a bit spooky about headquarters, Bush might reply he
knows that feeling too.
   With Bush's selection this week of Lilley as ambassador to China,
the president has now filled all the jobs he was appointed to in his
long climb to the top.
   Pickering, Lilley, Webster and two other gents _ Lee Atwater and
Dan Quayle _ might collectively be called George Bush's George
Bushes. What they all have in common is that they're white men who
spent most of their lives in government or politics:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS AMBASSADOR _ At 57, career diplomat Pickering is
10 years older than Bush was in 1971 when President Nixon gave the
former Texas congressman his first major post in government, as U.N.
ambassador.
   Pickering's 29-year career was free of even a hint of controversy
until he acknowledged in congressional testimony that he played a
role in the Iran-Contra affair. He helped arrange a secret
million-dollar donation of military equipment to the Nicaraguan
rebels after Congress banned aid to the Contras.
   Like Yaleman Bush, Pickering went to college in New England, in
his case Bowdoin College in Maine.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   REPUBLICAN NATIONAL CHAIRMAN _ Political gut fighter Lee Atwater,
37, bears scant resemblance to the 48-year-old George Bush who
headed the GOP during Richard Nixon's downfall.
   Atwater, a South Carolinian, is a political animal to the core, a
veteran of 30 local, state and national campaigns. His specialty is
negative campaigning. He once put it, ``You had to make the case
that the other guy, the other candidate, is a bad guy.''
   Bush in 1973-74 was a caretaker GOP chairman who tried to keep
the party afloat during Watergate and Nixon's resignation.
   Atwater masterminded the Bush campaign's attack against Democrat
Michael Dukakis, using the pledge of allegiance and the prison
furlough of a black murderer to portray Dukakis as out of line with
mainstream American values.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AMBASSADOR TO CHINA _ Old Asian hand Lilley became a Bush crony
in 1975-76 while both served in China _ Bush as chief of the U.S.
Liaison Office, before U.S. recognition, and Lilley as his
intelligence officer.
   They also had Yale in common. Lilley graduated in 1951, three
years after Bush.
   Lilley, 61, was born in China, where his father represented
Standard Oil. A former CIA intelligence officer, he has been U.S.
ambassador to South Korea and has served in U.S. missions in the
Philippines, Taiwan, Cambodia, Laos, Thailand and Hong Kong, on the
National Security Council staff, in the Pentagon and the State
Department.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DIRECTOR OF CENTRAL INTELLIGENCE _ Webster, 65, was named CIA
director by President Reagan and was kept on by Bush, who ran the
CIA in 1974-75.
   Before that, Webster headed the FBI. Just as Bush helped the CIA
recover from revelations of agency misdeeds, Webster restored morale
at the FBI at a time high-ranking officials stood accused of
violating the rights of citizens.
   A former federal judge in his native St. Louis, Webster, like
Bush, is an old Navy man, loves tennis and went to college in New
England: Amherst on a scholarship.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VICE PRESIDENT _ Dan Quayle, 42, had none of Bush's credentials
when Bush stunned Republicans at their New Orleans convention last
July by picking him for the job Bush then held, the vice presidency.
   Quayle was a junior senator from Indiana whose National Guard
service during the Vietnam War raised the suggestion that he used
family pull to avoid eligibility for the draft.
   Like Bush, Quayle had roots in a world of wealth and power, but
he lacked Bush's impressive resume, his distinguished college degree
or his record as a war hero.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Whistle-Blower     03-17 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whistle-Blower,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whistle-Blower Bill Moving Again in Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to shield federal employees who expose
waste, fraud and abuse is moving again toward enactment with
presidential backing after an earlier version was vetoed in the
final days of the Reagan administration.
   ``There is no more effective way for us to fight waste and
mismanagement in the federal government,'' Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.,
the chief sponsor, said Thursday before the Senate approved the
measure 97-0.
   The bill, backed by the Bush administration, appears to have
excellent prospects in the House, where action could come as early
as Tuesday.
   Under the bill, an independent special counsel's office would be
set up to protect federal employees, including whistle-blowers. The
office is now part of the Merit Systems Protection Board, which
enforces the civil service laws.
   Under the measure, it would be easier for federal employees to
prove that their firing or demotion came in retaliation for
whistle-blowing, and there would be additional guarantees of
confidentiality.
   The measure would permit employees to take their cases directly
to the Merit Systems Protection Board if the special counsel did not
do so within 120 days. The board could issue orders protecting the
employees from harassment during an investigation.
   The bill passed both houses unanimously last year and lawmakers
assumed that it was assured of then-President Reagan's signature.
But in October, Reagan killed it with a pocket veto, setting off
what Levin called ``a torrent of displeasure on a bipartisan basis''
among lawmakers.
   When Congress is out of session, the president can kill a measure
by simply refusing to sign it.
   The Reagan administration said last fall that the bill could have
resulted in government agencies filing suit against each other and
that it weighted the system too heavily in favor of the employees.
   A compromise was reached between the Bush administration and
senators last week under which the lawmakers agreed to drop a
provision enabling the special counsel to go to court on behalf of
whistle-blowers.
   Under the compromise, new safeguards were built into the bill.
For example, the special counsel would be barred from intervening
against an employee in a whistle-blower case.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, told the Senate that rank-and-file
federal workers ``are the ones who can best tell us that there is
waste, fraud, mismanagement and abuse ... and yet they are perhaps
the least protected of the federal employees.''
   ``Our bureaucracy has a very peculiar way of rewarding
whistle-blowers,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa. ``They are
harassed, they are demoted, they are even fired for doing what they
believe is right.''
   ``This bill when it becomes law will help restore the confidence
of the American people in their government,'' said Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn.
   The whistle-blower issue came into the spotlight in 1969 with the
dismissal of Defense Department aide A. Ernest Fitzgerald for
exposing $2 billion in cost overruns in the C-5A cargo plane
program. He was reinstated after a 13-year court fight.
   About 2,000 more obscure cases have been handled by the special
counsel's office over the last decade. There are indications that
most federal employees aware of waste, fraud and abuse are silent
because of a fear that blowing the whistle would cost them their
jobs.
   Twenty-five percent of federal employees surveyed by the Merit
Systems Protection Board in 1983 said they knew of waste, fraud and
abuse but 70 percent of those said they were unwilling to discuss it.
   Levin's office also said that at most 5 percent of whistle-blower
cases reported to the special counsel's office currently make it
past the initial screening process.
   Levin cited a remark that often has been attributed to former
special counsel William O'Connor in reply to prospective
whistle-blowers: ``I'd say that unless you're in a position to
retire or are independently wealthy, don't do it. Don't put your
head up, because it will get blown off.''
   ``Federal employee whistle-blowers deserve better,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ContraReturn     03-17 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Return,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cesar Says He'll Return to Nicaragua, Angers Colleague</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nicaraguan Contra leader is shunning stated
rebel policy by announcing he will return to his homeland and join
the internal opposition to the Sandinista government.
   The announcement Thursday by Alfredo Cesar, one of seven members
of the rebel directorate, was assailed by Contra spokesman Bosco
Matamoros, who accused Cesar of undercutting resistance policies.
   ``Exile politics is over,'' said Cesar, a political moderate who
has been a member of the directorate since 1987 and once served the
Sandinistas as president of the Central Bank.
   Rebel leaders have not been inside Nicaragua since their peace
talks with the Sandinistas broke down last June. Cesar is believed
to be the first Contra leader to announce an intention to return
permanently to Nicaragua since the rebels were formed almost seven
years ago.
   There was no immediate State Department reaction to Cesar's
disclosure. He said, however, the department officials left the
impression at a Tuesday meeting with the rebels that any decision on
returning home was theirs to make and no one else's.
   Cesar, 37, told a small gathering of reporters he supports the
Bush administration's view that the Contras should be maintained as
a cohesive _ but nonbelligerent _ force until it is clear that the
Sandinistas plan to carry out their promise to hold a fair election
next February.
   If the process goes smoothly, Cesar said he expects that some of
the more than 10,000 Contra fighters stationed in camps in southern
Honduras may return in peace to their homeland by next fall.
   ``If we reach the month of October, we may well be into an
irreversible (democratic) process in Nicaragua,'' Cesar said.
   He said he tentatively plans to return to Nicaragua during the
second part of May, assuming that preliminary discussions between
the Sandinistas and the internal opposition provide strong evidence
of Sandinista intentions to create a genuinely pluralistic system.
   Matamoros said that the Contra position calls for tripartite
discussions among the Sandinistas, the internal opposition and the
Contras on the ground rules governing the election process.
   By deciding unilaterally to return, Cesar is undercutting
resistance policy, Matamoros said.
   The Contra leadership has long been plagued by factional strife
and Thursday's statements suggest that will be a continuing problem
for the rebels.
   Cesar said he has no intention of seeking the presidency himself.
He said he would recommend that all segments of the opposition rally
around a single national figure, preferably someone who is ``above
partisan politics.''
   As Cesar described it, conditions for a democratic outcome in
Nicaragua are riper than they have been in years.
   He said the emergence of a bipartisan policy toward Nicaragua
under President Bush has been a major plus, and there is a stronger
consensus on the issue between the United States and Latin America
than there was under the previous administration.
   A common thread in the consensus is the need for the Sandinistas
to adopt western-style democracy, he said
   Cesar added that growing economic deprivation in Nicaragua also
has contributed to Sandinista flexibility on political questions.
   He expressed confidence that Congress will approve a forthcoming
administration request for additional humanitarian aid for the
rebels. Officials have said the figure will be in the $40 million to
$50 million range, enough to sustain the rebels until election time.
   Some Democratic lawmakers want to use some of the money to
re-integrate the Contras back into Nicaragua over the short term but
Cesar said a majority opinion in Congress holds that the money
should be used solely for food and other humanitarian items.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Ligachev     03-17 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ligachev,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin's Former No. 2 Denies Gorbachev Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Family Farms, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev denies reports
that he opposes the pace and scope of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms and says the Soviet leader ``splendidly fulfills
his duties.''
   Ligachev, peppered with questions about the reputed rift, told
reporters Thursday that reports he has deep differences with
Gorbachev are meant to turn the Soviet leader against him.
   ``You've said I'm cast as the leader of moderate forces in the
Soviet Union,'' he said at his first Moscow news conference. ``Some
people come up with even more outspoken characterizations, like the
leader of conservative forces, etc.
   ``Well, I view those assertions as the indication of a desire to
pit Gorbachev against Ligachev, and to introduce division in our
ranks.''
   Ligachev, 68, is widely rumored among Soviets to be a
conservative counterweight to Gorbachev in their country's
leadership. Last year Gorbachev stripped Ligachev of the ideology
portfolio that customarily goes with being the Kremlin's No. 2.
   Since then, Soviet officials have said the Kremlin has no No. 2.
Ligachev, named chief of the Communist Party's new commission on
agriculture in September, appeared to confirm that when he told
reporters: ``I cannot say that I am the head of the leading path or
direction.''
   Ligachev also indicated he no longer presides over meetings of
the ruling Politburo when Gorbachev is away, as Soviet sources had
previously reported.
   ``So far, Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev splendidly fulfills his
duties: He goes abroad, he goes to other regions, and he presides
over other Politburo members, and we are very satisfied with that,''
he said.
   Ligachev and other high-ranking party officials met journalists
at the end of the Central Committee plenum that decreed major
changes in agricultural policy to ease and ultimately eliminate
protracted Soviet food shortages.
   It was an extraordinarily high-powered news conference by Moscow
standards. Ligachev; Vadim A. Medvedev, his successor as party
ideologue, and Viktor P. Nikonov sat together on the stage at the
Foreign Ministry's Press Center.
   Despite Gorbachev's drive for ``glasnost,'' or greater openness,
the workings of the party's top bodies are still wreathed in
secrecy. The news conference was the first opportunity for
Moscow-based journalists to quiz Ligachev.
   Often joking, Ligachev fielded questions about the party
leadership's decision to permit lifetime leasing of farmland and
other agrarian reforms _ and about his political views and relations
with Gorbachev.
   ``I can tell you we see eye to eye, and on major issues, we are
quite unanimous,'' the white-haired Ligachev said at one point. ``We
have good comradely relations, which are very characteristic of
relations inside our party.''
   He acknowledged differences of approach may exist between himself
and Gorbachev, but said he discussed them with Gorbachev behind
closed doors, and that he always backed decisions of the Politburo,
which by tradition are unanimous.
   ``If we do have differing views on practical methods and forms of
implementing this or that reform, we take it up before sessions of
the Politburo and have a wide-ranging discussion on the issue,''
said Ligachev, elevated to the Politburo in April 1985, a month
after Gorbachev became leader.
</TEXT>
