<FIRST>r a PM-Bush     03-17 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Cites Sportsmen in Gun Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Departure from Colorado Springs 10 a.m. EST; arrival Washington
1 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says any
restrictions on rapid-fire assault weapons must protect ``the rights
of the legitimate sportsman'' as well as the lives of the nation's
police officers.
   ``This problem isn't a problem just for the federal government,''
Bush said in a speech Thursday.
   His remarks reinforced the impression Bush has left in recent
weeks that he is opposed to a total ban on semiautomatic weapons and
will insist that any curbs are carefully defined.
   The assault weapons have become closely identified with drug
traffickers and the rash of violence and death in some of the
nation's biggest cities.
   A member of the National Rifle Association, Bush was outspoken
against tighter gun controls during last year's presidential
campaign.
   After a 28-hour trip to Texas and Colorado, Bush was returning
today to Washington, where his wife Barbara was awaiting the birth
of puppies by their springer spaniel, Millie.
   Explaining the first lady's absence during a brief stop in his
adopted home state, Bush told a Houston audience, ``I think her
priorities may be slightly askew but she doesn't.''
   In a shift of position, the administration announced Tuesday it
was banning, at least temporarily, imports of five models of
semiautomatic weapons. However, the decision did not affect the sale
of such weapons made in the United States.
   ``I do want to find a solution to the so-called AK-47 assault
weapon problem, one that protects the rights of the legitimate
sportsman, but also protects the lives of our police officers who
are laying their lives on the line for us every single day,'' Bush
said in an address in Houston before flying here for another speech.
The audience of upwards of 1,000 people applauded his remark.
   The NRA says the military assault rifles affected by the federal
import ban are no different intrinsically from semiautomatic arms
that are used for self-defense or legitimate sport. The NRA opposes
all gun control.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater, accompanying Bush
on the overnight trip, said the administration welcomed the move by
Colt Industries to suspend sales of its AR-15, a civilian version of
the M-16 infantry rifle.
   He said Bush ``thinks it's a reasonable move on their part.''
Asked if the president wanted other gun-makers to take similar
steps, Fitzwater said, ``We'll leave it where it stands.''
   After his brief remark on assault weapons, Bush quickly moved on
to other subjects, prodding Congress for fast action on his proposal
to rescue the savings and loan industry and saying that his
administration is not bogged down or adrift.
   ``In this kind of work, more is going on than meets the eye or
makes the headlines,'' Bush said. Saying he was trying to lay the
groundwork for the next century, Bush said, ``The proof will come
when we look back from the year 2000.''
   In a brief question and answer session, Bush said that ``profound
changes'' are underway both in the Soviet Union and China.
   Speaking about reforms championed by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, Bush said, ``We've got a challenge facing the United
States. We've got to figure it out. We've got to measure Soviet
intentions and then move _ then come forward with proposals that
will enhance the peace for our kids and our grandkids.''
   In remarks in Colorado Springs, Bush focused on the theme of
education and discussed steps he has proposed to improve the
nation's school system.
   ``When it comes to our nation's future,'' Bush said, ``education
is the key. It's the best investment we can make.''
</TEXT>
