<FIRST>r w PM-DC-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0415 03-17 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Crime Wave Prompts Talk of Ending Home Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng Through Thursday, to correct year to
1989; picks up 17th graf, Barry, Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a record murder rate and its two top local
officials under federal investigation, the nation's capital has had
its share of unwanted publicity lately. Now, senators have begun
talking openly about what local politicians fear most _ the
possibility that Congress will take control of city government.
   Citing the city's inability to stem drug-related killings, two
senators suggested Thursday that the District of Columbia's police
department be replaced with a federally controlled police force.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., blamed the city's crime wave on
``inept local government that doesn't understand what it's doing.''
   ``We can't have people killed and blood running on the streets
like some Third World capital,'' Rudman said, adding that if the
killing continues, he would consider taking ``a look at home rule,
at least the law enforcement aspect.''
   Those remarks, supported by Sen. Ernest Hollings D-S.C., troubled
city officials who are worried that home rule, the right to
self-governance city residents obtained in 1973, may be more
vulnerable now than ever before.
   ``If the federal government thinks it can do a better job of
stopping drugs from coming into the city, why can't they do a better
job of stopping drugs from entering the country?'' asked Mayor
Marion Barry Jr.
   City Council Chairman David Clarke said that while the drug
problem may require additional federal involvement, home rule should
not be violated.
   ``What problems there are in this city will be dealt with by the
people in 1990,'' the next scheduled mayoral and council election,
Clarke said. ``They ought to let the democratic process run its
course.''
   Another council member, who spoke only on condition of anonymity,
went to what many consider the heart of the city's battles with
Congress:
   ``The problem is Barry, and they don't have the guts to go after
him, so they hit us on these other issues.''
   Barry, currently under federal investigation for his ties to a
drug suspect, has seen his _ and the city's _ support in Congress
plummet over the past several years.
   Last year, lawmakers forced the city to abolish or change
existing laws governing AIDS insurance, the rights of gay groups to
gather at Georgetown University and the city's residency requirement
for city workers. Had the city failed to change these laws, all or
part of its $2.8 billion budget would have been frozen.
   To make matters worse, Del. Walter Fauntroy, a civil rights
colleague of Barry's who is Washington's non-voting representative
in the House, is under federal investigation for his alleged
involvement in a payroll padding scheme in his Capitol Hill office.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is currently deciding whether to
appoint a special prosecutor to expand an FBI probe into allegations
that Fauntroy paid the son of a congressional colleague to work in
Washington, even though the employee _ Thomas John Savage, son of
Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., _ swore on Illinois election documents that
he was living in Chicago the entire time he was supposedly working
for Fauntroy.
   While the battles with Capitol Hill and the legal problems of
Fauntroy and Barry have preoccupied local leaders, the city's
spiraling crime rate has given the city another pressing problem.
   Through Thursday, 112 persons had been killed in the nation's
capital so far in 1989, more than twice the total at the same time
last year. For all of 1988, a record 372 persons were killed in the
streets of Washington.
   Barry, Police Chief Maurice T. Turner and other city leaders have
blamed the upsurge in murders on the arrival of crack, a highly
potent and addictive form of cocaine. A statistical study of city
homicides shows that about 60 percent are drug-related, and about 80
percent of those appear to be assassinations.
   The District of Columbia received limited self-governance from
Congress in 1973, but still must have its annual budget and all
legislation reviewed and approved by Congress.
   In addition, Fauntroy cannot vote on the House floor, and the
district has no representation in the Senate. District residents can
only elect a non-voting House delegate, their mayor, city council
and school board members.
   Under city law, Congress reserves the right to repeal any local
law or act, including part or all of the charter enacted by Congress
for the city.
   That's the clause of the charter most local politicians know best
and fear most, particularly when senators start talking about having
the federal government intervene in city affairs.
</TEXT>
