<DOCNO> AP890317-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-17 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Groups Calls for Boycott of Meetings with Pope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. Jewish groups are calling on Jews to
boycott meetings with Pope John Paul II because the Vatican has
failed to remove a convent from the site of the Nazi death camp at
Auschwitz
   The U.S. section of the World Jewish Congress, which represents
34 American groups, announced Thursday that it has adopted a
resolution that calls for WJC members in 70 countries to refrain
from meetings with the pope during his frequent travels.
   The resolution, adopted at a meeting of organization leaders in
New York, will be introduced at the May 7 meeting of the WJC's
International Executive in Montreal.
   The resolution said, ``The convent controversy is symptomatic of
a clear pattern by the Vatican to revise the history of the
Holocaust and the role of the church during that terrible period.''
Pope Pius XII has been widely criticized for failing to act or speak
out against the Nazis' murder of 6 million Jews during World War II.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Senate Votes to Ban Displaying Flag on the Floor</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial art exhibit in Chicago prompted
the Senate to approve a bill to bar placing the American flag on the
floor or on the ground.
   ``I don't know much about art, but I know desecration when I see
it,'' Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said after the
bill he introduced was approved 97-0 on Thursday.
   The move was a response to an exhibit by a student at the School
of the Art Institute of Chicago in which an American flag was
displayed on the floor in a fashion that resulted in spectators
standing on it.
   Dole's bill would expand existing law against flag desecration to
include the words ``knowingly displayed ... on the floor or ground.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Forest Service Say Sales From National Forests Netted $388 Million</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government made a $388.7 million profit on
timber sales in national forests during fiscal 1988 even though more
than two-thirds of the nation's 120 forests lost money on the sales.
   The Forest Service said Thursday that 74 national forests lost a
total of $53.7 million in the timber sales, while the other 46
forests logged $442.2 million in profits.
   Peter M. Emerson, chief economist and vice president for resource
planning and economics for the Wilderness Society, said the report
reinforces the society's view that the Forest Service's timber sales
program is an ``environmentally destructive federal boondoggle.''
   The Wilderness Society has been urging the Forest Service for
several years to halt timber sales in national forests where
expenses exceed revenue.
</TEXT>
