<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-17 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you are what you eat, kindergarten
and first-grade students at Central Elementary School in rural
Cabell County are as green as Ireland's old sod this St. Patrick's
Day.
   The school dished out green eggs and ham Thursday in a
celebration of the Irish holiday and Dr. Seuss' book, ``Green Eggs
and Ham.''
   Jessica Blank, 6, didn't seem to mind the color scheme of the
meal.
   ``I'd eat it anywhere,'' she said, repeating one of the lines in
the book.
   First-grade teacher Theresa Coleman thought it might be
interesting to bring the book by Theodore Seuss Geisel to life,
provided students were willing.
   The 27 students ate the colored scrambled eggs and chopped ham in
short order.
   Even green toast didn't dampen their appetites.
   In the book, a persistent character named Sam tries to get a cat
to eat green eggs and ham by offering every combination imaginable _
in a box, with a fox; in a house, with a mouse. Finally, the cat
tries the food to appease Sam, and finds he likes it.
   So did student Brandon Pauley _ ``in a house, with a mouse.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secret will be safe with restaurant
owners who have stocked up on corned beef and cabbage for St.
Patrick's Day today: The dish isn't very Irish at all.
   Louise Gunning, a native of Dublin who works in the registrar's
office at Trinity College, said she's mystified by the fixation on
corned beef.
   ``I've been here two years and when I came here, I was very
surprised on St. Patrick's Day seeing all the places selling corned
beef and cabbage,'' she said. ``What I would regard as the national
dish is Irish stew (or) bacon and cabbage.''
   Kathleen McGrory, president of Hartford College for Women and a
specialist in Irish studies, suggested that a ``shrewd
Irish-American in a country that eats a lot of beef'' concocted the
corned beef tradition.
   ``Both my parents were from Ireland, and they told us when we
were very young, if we wished to be authentic, we would have boiled
ham and cabbage on St. Patrick's Day.''
   McGrory said she has generally honored that advice, but couldn't
resist the 99-cent special of corned beef, cabbage and green beer in
a Vermont pub last year.
</TEXT>
