<FIRST>r a PM-Smoking-CervicalCancer     03-17 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking-Cervical Cancer,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Passive Smoking' Linked To Higher Risk of Cervical Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breathing the cigarette smoke of others may triple
a woman's likelihood of developing cervical cancer _ roughly the
same increase in risk that smoking itself seems to create, according
to a new study.
   But the finding should be interpreted cautiously, because the
study may have overestimated the risks of both types of exposure to
cigarette smoke, according to an independent researcher.
   Cervical cancer will strike more than 13,000 U.S. women this year
and kill 6,000 of them, according to the American Cancer Society.
   The most important cause of cervical cancer is believed to be
sexually transmitted virus called papillomavirus, but higher rates
of cervical cancer among smokers has led researchers to suspect that
cigarettes may play a role.
   Research has shown that substances in cigarette smoke can be
carried through the blood to distant tissues and organs, and these
substances have been detected in the neck of the uterus, the
researchers said.
   The study is the first to explore the possible role of ``passive
smoking,'' apart from active smoking, in the development of cervical
cancer, a malignancy of the neck of the uterus, the researchers said.
   Overall, women in the study who smoked had a 3.42 times greater
likelihood of developing cervical cancer than those who didn't,
according to findings published in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   The amount the women smoked made little difference in their risk,
said the researchers, led by Martha L. Slattery, an assistant
professor of family and preventive medicine at the University of
Utah School of Medicine at Salt Lake City.
   Passive smokers _ non-smoking women who breathed the smoke from
others' cigarettes for at least three hours a day _ had a 3.43
greater likelihood of developing cervical cancer than other
non-smokers, the study found.
   Considered together, smokers and non-smokers who breathed other
people's smoke had a 2.96 greater likelihood of developing cervical
cancer than smokers and non-smokers who didn't breathe other
people's smoke, the study found.
   ``Passive smoking had its greatest effect on women who were
non-smokers,'' Ms. Slattery said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   Findings were based on data collected on 270 urban women with
cervical cancer in four Utah counties between 1984 and 1987, and a
``control group'' of similar women were chosen randomly to serve as
a comparison group.
   The researchers said Utah is a good place for such a study
because of the large number of Mormon women whose religion forbids
them to smoke, making them good subjects for collecting data on the
effects of passive smoking alone.
   All findings were statistically adjusted to correct for
differences in cervical cancer risk associated with differences in
age, number of sexual partners and other factors, the researchers
said.
   ``Because this is the first study that has really looked at
passive smoking and cervical cancer, the results should be
interpreted cautiously,'' Ms. Slattery acknowledged. ``They do need
to be replicated by other studies.''
   An editorial accompanying the study said a cause-and-effect
relationship between smoking and cervical cancer remains to be
shown, and the similar risks found for active and passive smoking
seem surprising.
   The editorial, by Dr. Peter M. Layde of Marshfield Medical
Research Foundation in Marshfield, Wis., said the study also
probably overestimated both types of risks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
