<FIRST>r a PM-Arens-PLO     03-17 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arens-PLO,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister: Talks With PLO Sympathizers May Be OK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said his
country was willing to consider talking peace with ``authentic
interlocutors'' from the West Bank and Gaza Strip, even if they turn
out to be Palestine Liberation Organization sympathizers.
   Arens, a member of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing
Likud bloc, told the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations Thursday that Israel would ``spare no effort to
identify interlocutors amongst the Palestinian population'' in the
occupied territories.
   ``And it may very well be that such authentic interlocutors, some
of them may end up being sympathizers of the PLO,'' he said. ``But
there is a world of difference between somebody who has a
constituency, somebody who has to respond to that constituency on
the ground, or somebody who gets his orders from Tunis and knows
he's going to get a bullet in the head if he doesn't follow his
orders.''
   Arens statement was considered a significant departure from the
Likud line, which has been to rule out talks with anyone connected
in any way to the PLO.
   However, Yossi Ahimeir, a spokesman for Shamir in Jerusalem, told
The Associated Press that that position had not changed.
   ``We will never talk to people who are affiliated, who are
connected with the PLO. Sympathizers is a vague term. There are even
many PLO sympathizers among Israelis,'' Ahimeir said.
   Arens said that once the government found Palestinian
representatives ``that we can talk to, we will try to protect them
from threats, from terrorism.
   ``We will try to create a situation where their lives will not be
in danger. It's going to take courage on their part as well. That's
part of their contribution.''
   Arens, who met with President Bush and other officials in
Washington earlier this week, also strongly denounced the PLO and
its leader Yasser Arafat, and chastised members of the Israeli
parliament for going abroad to mobilize support for direct talks
with the organization.
   His meetings were preceded this weekend by a conference at
Columbia University where Palestinians, including members of the
PLO, met with Israelis, including Knesset members, to encourage
dialogue.
   ``I'm not helped by the appearance of Israeli members of the
Knesset here in New York with PLO,'' he said. ``Don't take that
argument abroad. Don't try to circumvent the decision of Israel's
electorate by going to New York or Stockholm, by trying to put
pressure on Israel's government via other governments.''
</TEXT>
