<FIRST>r a PM-Police-RapeCharge     03-17 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police-Rape Charge,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman Charged With Child Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say they have a strong case
against a police officer acquitted last summer of sexually abusing
an 8-year-old girl _ a videotape of the officer having sex with the
same girl.
   Warren A. Poole, 45, was acquitted by a judge last June when the
girl, placed on the witness stand in front of the defendant,
recanted her claim of sexual abuse.
   Several months later, however, police said the girl again told
them she had been molested. State and local police searched Poole's
apartment Wednesday and confiscated a videotape that prosecutors
said shows the policeman having sex with the girl. He was charged
with raping the child.
   Poole, who was suspended without pay, pleaded innocent at his
arraignment Thursday in Lynn District Court. Bail was set at
$350,000 with double surety, meaning Poole must put up bonds worth
at least $700,000 to secure his release.
   Assistant District Attorney Howard Whitehead said that the
videotape gave the prosecution a ``uniquely strong'' case.
   Poole's attorney, Alan Karahalis, did not respond to telephone
messages requesting comment.
   Poole, a divorced father of six, has served for 14 years on the
police force in Lynn, a industrial city of 78,500 people about 15
miles north of Boston.
   Poole was reinstated to the police department with back pay after
his acquital.
</TEXT>
