<FIRST>r a PM-Standoff-Arrest     03-17 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Standoff-Arrest,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Murder Suspect Surrenders After 3-Hour Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS M. SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A slaying suspect surrendered early today to end a
three-hour standoff with police during which he held a gun to a
teen-ager's head, authorities said.
   Maxwell Thomas, 18, is a suspect in the slaying of hairdresser
David Timoner, 33. A second suspect, identified by police as
18-year-old Michael Diaz, remained at large.
   Timoner's body, found in a burning car Wednesday morning, was
charred beyond recognition. Dental records were used to identify him.
   During the standoff, neighboring houses in the Capitol Hill area
of Denver were evacuated and the block was cordoned off. The
hostage, Michael DeLoach, 17, was freed when Thomas surrendered.
   The arrest capped a search of the area that began when police
tried to arrest Thomas at his apartment on a murder warrant. Police
said Thomas pulled a gun and fled on foot.
   The hunt for Thomas included a two-hour search of Morey Middle
School with students locked in their classrooms while police looked
for the suspect.
   ``He was scared, a mixed up 18-year-old kid,'' said Lt. Curtis
Williams, who negotiated with Thomas during the standoff. ``He said
he didn't have anything to lose and wanted to go down in a blaze of
glory. ... Maybe he didn't want to go out in a blaze of glory after
all.''
   Williams said Thomas denied any involvement in the slaying.
   Police said they suspected a drug connection in the slaying, but
Timoner's friends said he did not use drugs.
</TEXT>
