<FIRST>r a PM-AssaultWeapons     03-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Weapons,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Block Local Bans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Semiautomatic Sales, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court has refused to stop
the enforcement of local bans on semiautomatic assault rifles in
several California communities including Stockton, where a gunman
opened fire and killed five children.
   The court on Thursday also transferred several lawsuits, paid for
by the National Rifle Association, to the 1st District Court of
Appeal in San Francisco.
   The lawsuits contend that state law on gun registration and
licensing was intended to forbid local measures restricting gun
ownership.
   Police and gun-control groups have long been pushing for bans on
semiautomatic rifles, particularly in cities like Los Angeles, where
they are widely used by street gangs.
   Support for local and statewide restrictions gained momentum
after Patrick Purdy entered a Stockton elementary schoolyard on Jan.
17, and with rapid-fire shots from a semiautomatic AK-47 rifle,
killed five children and wounded 29 other pupils and a teacher
before taking his own life.
   Since then, the cities of Los Angeles, Berkeley, Stockton and the
county of Santa Clara have passed ordinances banning sale and
possession of the military-style weapons. It was enforcement of
those laws the state high court refused to block.
   Besides the four ordinances that were challenged in court, local
bans have been passed by the cities of Gardena, Compton and Carson
and are being considered elsewhere.
   The local ordinances in general forbid sale and possession of
assault weapons.
   The state Legislature has voted curbs on the sale and possession
of the weapons as of next Jan. 1.
   Colt Industries Inc. of Hartford, Conn., on Wednesday said it was
suspending sales to the public of its AR-15. The company said the
suspension was a voluntary reaction to the Bush administration's
temporary import ban on semiautomatics.
</TEXT>
