<FIRST>r a PM-Teamsters     03-17 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters Boss Wanted Mafia Help To Get Union Job, Court Papers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters asked the Mafia for help in his unsuccessful 1984 bid for
a high-level union position, according to government documents.
   The allegation is contained in the evidence the government
collected for a pretrial hearing in the Teamster racketeering trial
that was canceled Monday.
   The source of the allegation was Jackie Presser, the late
president of the Teamsters, who also was an undercover informer for
the FBI.
   In one of his reports, Presser said that William J. McCarthy
sought Mafia help to become secretary-treasurer _ the union's second
most powerful position.
   The position is supposed to be appointed by the president.
Presser, who was president at the time, told the FBI that he needed
Mafia approval to select anyone for the post, which then paid
$250,000 a year.
   Presser, who died last July and was succeeded by McCarthy, stated
that McCarthy had solicited support from the head of organized crime
families in New England and the New York area in 1984.
   Federal prosecutors have said that Presser's reports were
substantiated by court-approved wiretaps of Mafia leaders.
   McCarthy, speaking through James T. Grady, the union's general
counsel, denied the allegations, according to a report in today's
New York Times. In fact, Grady said that Presser had told McCarthy
to contact the ``wise guys'' if he wanted to be secretary-treasurer,
the Times said. ``Wise guys'' is used to refer to members of the
Mafia.
   McCarthy, 69, had led Teamsters Local 25 in Boston for 20 years
when he was elected president of the national union after Presser
died.
   The trial, which was set for Manhattan federal court, was
canceled after the Justice Department and the union agreed on a plan
that calls for court-appointed officers and an administrator to
oversee most of the union's business and rid it of alleged
corruption.
   Presser filed reports as an FBI informant from 1984 to 1985.
   Although the material was not used, the chief prosecutor in the
case, Randy M. Mastro, said the Presser reports could be used by the
court-appointed officers if necessary in future proceedings to
remove McCarthy and other union officers.
</TEXT>
