<SECOND>PM-Felony Littering,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Felony Littering Law Convicts Tire Dumpers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who dumped more than a ton
of old tires on a university campus became the first to receive
felony convictions under a tough, new Florida littering law.
   ``We're very pleased,'' said a spokesman for the Florida Game and
Fresh Water Fish Commission after a jury found Willie Hooks, 66, and
John W. Johnson, 45, guilty of littering Wednesday.
   ``This is a serious offense to the natural environment, and it
will send a message that this will not be tolerated,'' Jim Huffstodt
said.
   Under the new law _ which took effect Oct. 1 _ it is a felony to
dump more than 500 pounds of debris on public property.
   Hooks and Johnson testified at the trial they agreed to help Walt
``The Tire Man'' Baker dump 117 tires on Oct. 21 on the campus of
Florida Atlantic University to make a little extra cash. Baker also
was charged, but pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor in a plea bargain.
   Circuit Judge Thomas Sholts said he will probably sentence them
to community service _ picking up trash.
   Sentencing was set for May 8.
