<FIRST>u i PM-SouthKorea     03-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Battle Riot Squads At Three Colleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters battled riot
police at three colleges today after students stormed the
headquarters of the governing party and demanded the ouster of
President Roh Tae-woo, authorities said.
   Protesters threw firebombs and rocks during clashes in the
capital and police responded with tear gas. At least five students
were reported hurt.
   The protests broke out after about two dozen students stormed the
headquarters of the governing Democratic Justice Party in Seoul and
briefly occupied the roof and hurled firebombs at police.
   The protesters were overpowered and arrested by about 100 riot
police.
   Clashes later broke out at Seoul National, Dongguk and Kon Kuk
universities, with police involved in running battles with students
who hurled firebombs and rocks and shouted anti-Roh slogans.
   About 1,500 students were involved in the clashes.
   Police also reported an attack on a party office in eastern Seoul
by a dozen students Thursday night. Police said the students fled
after hurling firebombs and shattering windows.
   Some opposition and dissident groups are making a joint effort to
defeat Roh in an upcoming national referendum. Radical students vow
to stage a wave of anti-Roh street demonstrations prior to the
plebiscite, expected in mid-April.
   Roh told a meeting of senior government prosecutors today he
would soon call the referendum and that the government must take a
stand against radical groups espousing leftist revolution.
   Roh promised in a 1987 campaign to hold a referendum to let
people assess his performance. Government officials have said Roh
would stay in power even if he is defeated, but opponents contend
the president must resign if he fails to win a majority.
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam today urged Roh to resign to
clear the way for a new presidential election. The head of the
second-largest opposition party, Reunification Democratic Party,
said he would step up a campaign to defeat Roh in the referendum.
   Meanwhile, Seoul's subway service remained disrupted for the
second straight day today as many striking workers ignored a warning
or return to work immediately or face dismissal or other
disciplinary action.
   About half the subway's 7,732 workers reported today, but many of
them refused to work. Subway officials said several days would be
needed before full service is restored.
   Police arrested about 2,300 strikers Thursday at a subway depot,
but released most today.
   Prosecutors said they would charge 15 union leaders for
organizing the strike, which was spurred by demands that the head of
the subway corporation be fired for purportedly bargaining in bad
faith during recent labor talks.
</TEXT>
