<FIRST>r i PM-IslamicConference     03-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Islamic Conference,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamic Conference Opposes Iran on Rushdie, Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moslem conference has rejected
Iran's call for the execution of novelist Salman Rushdie and
embraced a provisional Afghan government that Tehran opposed.
   Foreign ministers of the 46-member Organization of Islamic
Conference on Thursday condemned Rushdie's book ``The Satanic
Verses,'' which many Moslems have protested as blasphemous. They
also issued a separate declaration condemning the author as an
apostate.
   However, they did not approve Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
fatwa, or religious decree, of Feb. 14 ordering Moslems to kill him.
   In addition, no mention was made in the declaration of Iran's
demand that Islamic Conference members break relations with Britain
and other Western powers on the ground they incited and protected
Rushdie. Iran severed relations with Britain earlier this month over
the dispute.
   Rushdie, 41, was born in Bombay, India, to Moslem parents but now
is a British citizen. He went into hiding after Khomeini pronounced
the death sentence and Iranian clerics added a reward of $5.2
million.
   The conference also gave the organization's vacant 46th seat to a
provisional government formed by the Moslem guerrillas trying to
overthrow the Soviet-backed Afghan government. The Afghan seat was
declared vacant after a communist coup in April 1978 began the civil
war in that nation.
   The government-in-exile, now based in Pakistan, is dominated by
Sunni Moslems. Shiite insurgents based in Iran oppose the
government, claiming it does not give them enough representation.
Iran backs their stand.
   Delegates adopted 50 resolutions at the final session of the
four-day conference on Thursday. They expressed support for the
Palestinian uprising in Israeli-occupied territories, now more than
15 months old, and regaining the Arab sector of Jerusalem now
controlled by Israel.
</TEXT>
