<FIRST>r w PM-EducationResignations 1stLd-Writethru a0436 03-17 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Resignations, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,xxx</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observers See Move Away from Ideology with Resignations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts dropped word leave in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The departure of six senior political
appointees at the Education Department paves the way for more
cooperation and less ideology at the agency, members of the
education community said.
   The department said Thursday that President Bush had accepted the
resignations this week of five assistant secretaries and a deputy
undersecretary. They will leave by next Thursday.
   ``There really is a new breeze,'' said education analyst Emily
Feistritzer, director of the National Center for Education
Information, an independent, nonpartisan research group.
   She predicted a return to ``collaborative efforts between the
special interest groups and the Department of Education'' that were
the norm before former secretary William Bennett brought his
confrontational style to bear.
   ``Bennett was very ideological and defined the Education
Department as a bully pulpit,'' she said. ``All the people (he
brought in) that didn't leave earlier of their own accord pretty
much are being moved on out.''
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, a conciliator who has reached
out to all segments of the education community, is a holdover from
late in the Reagan administration. Bush recently nominated Illinois
school superintendent Ted Sanders to be undersecretary, the No. 2
slot, and former White House aide Nancy Moore Kennedy to be
assistant secretary for legislation, a slot now vacant.
   There are seven assistant secretary and three deputy
undersecretary slots at the department. The six appointees whose
resignations were accepted are:
   _Patrick Pizzella, deputy undersecretary for management.
   _Legree Daniels, assistant secretary for civil rights.
   _Kenneth Whitehead, assistant secretary for postsecondary
education.
   _Beryl Dorsett, assistant secretary for elementary and secondary
education.
   _Madeleine Will, assistant secretary for special education and
rehabilitative services.
   _Patricia Hines, assistant secretary for educational research and
improvement.
   ``Just after the president was elected, he said he thought it
would be a good idea to bring a lot of fresh faces into
government,'' said department spokeswoman Mary Crawford. ``This is
consistent with his thinking. We don't have successors named for
those posts yet. What we'll do here is appoint acting office heads.''
   Lamar Haynes, manager for intergovernmental relations at the
National Education Association, said the teachers union has had
problems with some department offices, including lack of what the
union considered proper enforcement of education civil rights laws.
   ``When we began working with Secretary Cavazos, we immediately
saw some very hopeful signs of being able to collaborate on a lot of
issues and being able to have a voice at the department level,''
Haynes said. ``We are hopeful that the replacements will have
similar philosophies as the current secretary in terms of his
interests and priorities.''
   David Merkowitz, a spokesman for the American Council on
Education, an umbrella group for higher education organizations,
called the departures ``a continuation of the direction in which the
department's been moving'' since Bennett left.
   ``It's clear that Secretary Cavazos has been working to
re-establish a good relationship with higher education,'' Merkowitz
said. He said the newly constituted department will be less
ideological than the Bennett regime because ``that is the tone the
secretary has set.''
   Cavazos has said he is interested in helping disadvantaged
students, preventing dropouts, and making sure minorities have
access to higher education.
</TEXT>
