<FIRST>r a PM-GarageJamming     03-17 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Garage Jamming,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Is The Frequency That Jammed Garage Doors? The Navy Knows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has lifted the veil of secrecy
surrounding mysterious radio signals _ and allowed hundreds of
jammed garage doors to lift as well.
   When the Navy flicked a switch Thursday, life returned to normal
for suburbanites whose electronic garage doors had mysteriously
failed to operate for days.
   ``I was testing the (opener) every day, and then all of a sudden,
bingo, it started working,'' said Stan Stuttaford of Alamo.
   The culprit, the Navy disclosed, was a powerful radio wave it had
beamed off a satellite dish on Mount Diablo in Contra Costa County.
The signals provided communications to a ship at Alameda whose
regular communications devices had broken.
   ``Maybe it didn't dawn on people (in the Navy) how widespread the
effect would be,'' said Lt. Joe Murphy at the Navy's San Francisco
base. Murphy, who opens his own garage door by hand, said the Navy
will look into ways to prevent such disruptions in the future.
   Tom Hora, a spokesman with the Federal Communications Commission
in Livermore, on Tuesday said a government agency had been
transmitting the signals, but he declined to name it.
   Garage door openers operate on radio frequencies used by the
government and others with authorization. Hora said the public
wasn't told about the problem because the remote control openers are
considered ``unprotected devices.''
   Jammed garage doors were reported in Concord, Orinda, Walnut
Creek, Alamo, Lafayette, Moraga, Danville, San Ramon and Livermore.
</TEXT>
