<FIRST>r a PM-LandlordSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0412 03-17 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landlord Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against Landlord Who Wouldn't Rent To Unmarried Couple</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to insert state in dateline; SUBS 3rd graf, `The state's
...,' to include provision of law cited in lawsuit.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord discriminated against an
unmarried couple by refusing to rent a house to them, a judge has
ruled.
   Minnesota Human Rights Commissioner Stephen Cooper, whose lawsuit
against Layle French alleged violations of the state's Human Rights
Act, said the decision was filed Wednesday by Judge Peter Erickson.
He said Thursday that Erickson still must decide damages in the case.
   The state's lawsuit sought damages from French for refusing to
rent a house to Susan Parsons because she planned to live there with
her fiance. The lawsuit was based on a section of the state's law
that says refusal to rent on the basis of marital status is
discriminatory.
   French argued that the Human Rights Act violated his religious
beliefs forbidding sex before marriage.
   ``The Bible clearly states this is wrong,'' French had said. ``I
live with the Bible as my guide.''
   French claimed the law violated his First Amendment right to
freedom of religion and said he believed that by living together the
couple would violate a little-known state statute that prohibits
sexual intercourse between unmarried adults.
   But the judge said that, when a person engages in for-profit
undertakings, his religious beliefs are not totally protected by the
Constitution.
   French's attorney, James Anderson, said he would appeal after the
damages are assessed.
   ``I don't understand the logic behind the law,'' French said
Thursday, adding that it's ``frustrating to see these kinds of
things go on'' and not be able to do anything about it.
</TEXT>
