<FIRST>r a PM-DowneySuit     03-17 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Downey Suit,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talk Show Host Sued, Accused of Bilking Investors In 1982 Real Estate
Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some real estate investors are suing talk
show host Morton Downey Jr., accusing him of selling them worthless
plots of land in the California desert advertised as containing
gold, a newspaper reported today.
   A federal judge in California has set a May 24 hearing on the
lawsuit, The Record reported.
   The class action lawsuit, filed in December in U.S. District
Court in San Francisco, charges that from 1982 to 1983, the
then-unknown Downey bilked investors out of $10 million to $20
million.
   Downey, 56, whose ``Morton Downey Jr.'' television show is taped
at WWOR-TV in Secaucus, told the paper he was only a consultant for
the enterprise, and his only payment was $6,500 for giving
motivational speeches to company salespersons.
   Downey maintained that another partner in the venture, John W.
Mangham, added his name to a list of company officers without his
knowledge.
   However, the newspaper reported that documents in the Nevada
Secretary of State's Office list Downey as the sole officer of
Magdalena Mining Corp., one of three companies involved in the
lawsuit. Magdalena Mining's charter was revoked in 1987 after Downey
failed to make annual financial filings, the office said.
   Mangham, now a business consultant in San Diego, declined to
comment on Downey's charges. But, he said, ``There was no fraud
involved as far as Downey and I were concerned.''
   He said the $10 million to $20 million figure that the lawsuit
claims the companies earned is ``woefully inaccurate on the high
side.'' He declined to say how much the enterprise did collect.
   ``You have a couple of investors looking for money because the
deal was not successful,'' he said.
</TEXT>
