<FIRST>r a PM-WhaleRescue     03-17 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whale Rescue,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Call Off Search For Whale Tangled In Net</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine biologists have reluctantly
halted a rescue effort for a 35-foot California gray whale after the
giant mammal, ensnared in fishing nets, disappeared into the fog.
   When the fog lifted Thursday night the whale was gone, and
scientists who had lost track of the animal earlier in the day
called off their intensive search.
   The bologists said they hoped boaters who spot the 25-ton animal
would alert them.
   The northbound whale was first spotted Tuesday off Dana Point.
   A team of biologists from the Long Beach-based Whale Rescue Unit
tried to get close enough to cut away the nets, but lost the whale
in fog near Newport Beach, 45 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
   The netting wrapped around the whale's flukes eventually could
cause it to drown, said Joe Cordero, a spokesman for the National
Marine Fisheries Service.
   Debris picked up in the net could drag the mammal under water,
and the nets probably will wrap tighter around the whale as it
struggles to free itself, said Tom Lewis, co-director of the Whale
Rescue Unit.
   From 10 to 15 whales become trapped in giant nets and slowly die
each year during the migratory journey between California and
Mexico's Baja California, Lewis said.
   There are an estimated 21,000 California whales.
   Whales began migrating from the warmer waters in Mexico earlier
this month and will continue their northward treks through May.
</TEXT>
