<DOCNO> AP890317-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ElkDeaths     03-17 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elk Deaths,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Storms Take Toll On Yellowstone Elk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe winter weather has
taken a heavy toll on elk in Yellowstone National Park, and nearly
one-third of the park's 19,000-head northern herd may have died,
park biologists say.
   Mortality rates were highest following the arctic cold in early
February and a second severe storm at the end of the month,
biologists said.
   The elk death rate generally peaks during the last two weeks of
March, said park biologist Frank Singer. ``This year, we hit the
peak after the arctic front,'' he said.
   Singer said the mortality rate was estimated by tracking elk
equipped with radio collars. Nearly one-third of those animals have
died, he said.
   In addition to stress from severe cold and snow, summer forest
fires swept some grazing areas already affected by drought, forcing
the animals outside the protection of the park in search of food.
   About one-third of the elk deaths were attributed to hunters
outside the park near Gardiner, Mont.
   More than half of the Yellowsone elk herd remains outside the
park. Bison that also migrated outside Yellowstone in search of food
have begun moving back into the park's interior, but biologists say
it probably will be several weeks before the elk return.
   The elk probably will benefit from the growth of new vegetation
spurred by the fires, Singer said.
   ``I can't think of a species that will benefit more,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
