<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mail order preacher known for his work
with the homeless is charged with raping a 10-year-old girl, who
suffered through three years of molestation because she was afraid
of losing her home, police said.
   The child remained silent because William J. Keichline, 52,
threatened to evict her and her family if she said anything,
according to affidavits filed Thursday. Keichline, who owns several
rental properties, was the family's landlord.
   New Castle County police arrested Keichline on Thursday at his
home in Wilton and charged him with multiple counts of unlawful
sexual intercourse, unlawful sexual contact and sexually exploiting
a child, according to affidavits filed in Magistrate Court.
   Keichline is founder and pastor of Mission of Care Inc., which
helps the needy and homeless. The organization fired Keichline
within hours of his arrest and was not implicated in the
investigation, police said. Keichline's rental properties are
independent of the organization.
   Keichline, who was held in Gander Hill Prison for lack of
$330,000 bail, denied the charges through an attorney.
   In 1983, the Delaware General Assembly passed a resolution
honoring Mission of Care for opening a shelter for 17 homeless
people during record cold.
   According to the affidavits, Keichline showed the youngster child
pornography and sometimes forced her to pose for videotapes and
photos, which were found in a search of his home. The child spoke to
police after her mother became suspicious of Keichline, court
records indicated.
   Keichline paid $25 in 1984 to gain ordination in the National
Chaplains Association of the Christian Church in Pigeon Forge, Tenn.
