<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StarkeDiscrimination     03-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Starke Discrimination,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Town Agrees To Settle Voting Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Town officials have agreed to change to
district elections and to pay $195,000 to the NAACP after losing a
lawsuit charging the town's voting practices disenfranchised black
residents.
   The Bradford County chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People filed the lawsuit in 1986 to challenge
the city's at-large election system.
   The Starke City Commission Wednesday approved the settlement and
a plan to establish a black majority voting district on the
northeast side of town.
   No black official has ever been elected in Starke. The northern
Florida town of 5,300 is 31 percent black.
   U.S. District Judge W. Terrell Hodges ruled Feb. 27 that
political opportunity had been denied Starke's black residents
because of at-large elections and gave attorneys 30 days to propose
remedies.
   The NAACP, the American Civil Liberties Union and other groups
have been challenging the at-large voting system in Southern
communities for many years.
   Among the discriminatory practices cited by the NAACP was a
clause in the 1927 city charter, never amended, that requires blacks
to live in the northeast.
   ``I'm sorry we lost the case and we lost $195,000. On the other
hand, I fought for what I thought was right,'' City Commissioner
Charles Schaefer said Thursday.
   He said he would not seek re-election to the post he has held for
16 years so his seat can be filled by someone elected from the black
district.
</TEXT>
