<DOCNO> AP890317-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103 4thLd-Writethru   03-17 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0550,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Channon Says His Warning About Bomb Followed Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Channon saying warning his office
issued merely supplemented others. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb warning dated two days before Pan Am Flight
103 was destroyed over Scotland was an unimportant document and was
mailed after the disaster, the transport secretary said in an
interview published today.
   ``It went out after Christmas. I cannot tell you the exact date
but some days after Christmas,'' the secretary, Paul Channon, was
quoted by The Times of London as saying. ``It was not a great new
warning which we had to send out by telex. It was a bit of
supplementary information containing some color photographs,'' the
newspaper quoted him as saying.
   Disclosure of the Dec. 19 letter, warning of a radio-cassette
bomb such as the one which has been identified as killing 270 people
in the Pan Am disaster, brought new demands from opposition
lawmakers for a full public inquiry.
   Published reports that investigators have identified and even
arrested a suspect in the bombing were denied by authorities in
Britain and West Germany.
   As criticism mounted of the government's handling of bomb
warnings, a spokesman for the governing Conservative Party pointed a
finger at Pan Am.
   ``The truth of the matter is that the West German authorities
told Pan Am about a bomb in early November. The American government
told Pan Am about it on Nov. 18,'' Conservative lawmaker David
Wilshire said today. ``So what has it got to do with the British
government? Are Pan Am deaf or not?''
   Pamela Hanlon, a Pan Am spokeswoman in New York, confirmed today
that the airline received a warning from the West German government
on Nov. 10 and another warning from the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration on Nov. 18.
   Wilshire charged that Pan Am had covered up the earlier warnings,
but Ms. Hanlon said: ``Frankly, I don't think it's for the company
to disclose that.
   ``The Nov. 18 advisory that went out from the FAA was not openly
disclosed by the company per the FAA's directive,'' she said.
   The Times of London, quoting unidentified government sources,
reported today that authorities know who bombed Flight 103. But the
report was denied by British officials and an official in West
Germany, where the flight originated.
   ``I can confirm to you that there is insufficient evidence to
establish the identity of the person or group responsible for
this,'' said Inspector Tom McCulloch, a spokesman for the crash
investigation in Lockerbie, Scotland. He said there were no plans
for an announcement as reported by the newspaper.
   ``I haven't given any insructions for the arrest of anyone,''
Scotland's chief legal officer, Lord Fraser, told ``CBS This
Morning,'' but added, ``Of course, there are suspicions.''
   ``I certainly do not have an identification which I could
consider putting before a court in Scotland, in England, or indeed
in any civilized jurisdiction,'' said Fraser, who is lord advocate
of Scotland.
   ``It would be useful if all these sources would share this
information with us,'' Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for chief West
German federal prosecutor Kurt Rebmann, said today of the reports
the identity of the bomber is known.
   Prechtel dismissed the story as ``absolute nonsense.''
   British and West German authorities also dismissed another report
in a British tabloid today that said a suspect belonging to a
radical Palestinian group had been taken into custody in Europe.
   All 259 people on the New York-bound flight and 11 people on the
ground in Lockerbie were killed in the disaster. The flight
originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, and passengers changed to a
Boeing 747 at London's Heathrow airport.
   The Times said police and security services know who made and
placed the bomb aboard the craft, as well as the whereabouts of the
bomber.
   ``The results of what Whitehall (British government) sources term
`one of the most remarkable feats of criminal detection ever known'
are expected to be disclosed next week,'' The Times said without
elaborating.
   The London tabloid Today reported this morning that a terrorist
who planted the bomb had been arrested. ``The prime suspect, a
member of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, is believed to be under heavy guard somewhere in Europe,''
it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
