<FIRST>r i PM-AxMurders     03-17 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ax Murders,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Convicted In Ax Murders Of Four Family Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW WESTMINSTER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers have been
convicted in the ax murders of four members of one family, including
the father of one of the youths.
   Eric Peever, 18, and Tyrone Borglund, 17, appeared impassive
after their conviction Thursday when they were sentenced to life in
prison with no chance of parole for at least 25 years.
   ``Words cannot possibly describe the ghastly and violent nature
of your acts,'' said British Columbia Supreme Court Justice Wallace
Oppal. ``The premeditated violence that took place in this case is
immeasurable.''
   Karsten Madsen, 38; his second wife, Leny, 30; and their
children, Jason, 11, and Michelle, 9, were killed in their sleep
Jan. 17, 1988, in Mission, about 30 miles east of Vancouver.
   Peever was Madsen's son from his first marriage and Borglund
lived with the family as a foster child.
   ``You have wiped out a whole family,'' Oppal said. ``In all my
years I have never seen such havoc and violence as in this case.''
   Michael Peever, 16, testified that his older brother and Borglund
decided to kill and rob the family because they were angry over
Madsen's discipline.
   According to testimony, Borglund was intoxicated when he attacked
Madsen and his wife, and then the children.
   Peever admitted hitting Mrs. Madsen once with a hatchet before
fleeing.
   Mrs. Madsen's sister, Beppie Henry, said Borglund was ``a problem
child.'' She and her husband, Pidge, said Mrs. Madsen was terrified
of Borglund and several times insisted that provincial Human
Resources Ministry officials place him in another foster home.
   He was moved a few times during the year he spent with the
Madsens, but each time asked to be sent back, the Henrys said.
   Ministry officials refused to comment on the case.
</TEXT>
