<HEAD>Judge Allows Lesbian To Seek Custody Of Female Lover's Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman will be allowed to pursue a lawsuit
seeking joint custody of her former female lover's daughter, who was
born during their lesbian relationship, a court official has ruled.
   ``It's exciting that a person who is not a natural biological
parent can proceed in a same-sex relationship case,'' said attorney
Gloria Allred, who is representing the mother's former lover, Terri
Sabol.
   Superior Court Commissioner James Endman allowed the custody case
to proceed Thursday after a closed session with attorneys for Ms.
Sabol and the mother, who has not been identified.
   Ms. Sabol claims she is entitled to parental rights because she
intended to have the child, planned for it, arranged for sperm to be
donated by one of her relatives, assisted with the artificial
insemination, paid child and spousal support after the baby was born
on Dec. 16, 1986, and parented the child until she and the mother
broke up.
   Ms. Sabol, 32, has a court hearing March 30 to seek temporary
visitation rights of the 2-year-old girl known as Baby B until the
matter is resolved at trial.
   Mitchell Jacobs, the mother's attorney, said his client will seek
dismissal of the case at that hearing.
   Ms. Sabol filed a lawsuit seeking joint custody after the
29-year-old mother began to restrict her time with the child after
their break-up.
