<FIRST>u a PM-StPatrick'sDay 2ndLd-Writethru a0558 03-17 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-St Patrick's Day, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0558,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Female Grand Marshal `Walking on Air'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with parade in New York under way, quotes
from cardinal's sermon, other details; No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Illegal Irish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's oldest and largest St. Patrick's Day
parade headed up Fifth Avenue today, with its first woman grand
marshal saying she felt she was ``walking on air.''
   Green, white and gold Irish flags fluttered above the avenue on a
warm, sunny morning as the first of 150,000 marchers, including 186
marching bands, stepped off. Spectators massed behind police
barricades to cheer or jeer politicians and to hear bagpipes, fifes
and drums.
   Sponsors predicted 1.25 million spectators along the avenue for
the parade, which was preceded by a Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral
celebrated by Cardinal John O'Connor.
   O'Connor used the occasion to deliver a politically charged
sermon in which he said the fallacy that the Irish are a violent
people needs to be corrected.
   ``How little we concern ourselves with the problems of Northern
Ireland because we believe the Irish love to fight, that they're a
violent people,'' he said.
   In Savannah, Ga., organizers of the nation's second-largest
celebration of Ireland's patron saint, said they expected a turnout
of 500,000.
   At Cape Canaveral, Fla., engineers monitoring the flight of the
space shuttle Discovery changed the shading on a world map from its
normal blue to a vivid green. The map is used to track the orbital
progress of the shuttle.
   At a breakfast before the New York parade, Mayor Edward I. Koch
compared the struggle of Dorothy Hayden Cudahy to become grand
marshal to that of women in the suffragette movement.
   Wearing green leather boots and a white dress of Donegal wool
``handmade just for the occasion,'' she said before the march:
``They're honoring St. Patrick. ... I'm the grand marshal and I'm
walking on air.''
   Mrs. Cudahy is known as the First Lady of Irish Radio because of
a local radio program she has been host of for more than 40 years.
   As part of the city's celebration, the top 30 floors of the
Empire State Building are being illuminated with green lights.
   In Savannah, workers added green dye to the city's downtown
fountains.
   The grand marshal for today's parade was Charles Ray, 65, the
grandson of Irish immigrants.
   According to Irish folklore, Ray said, ``The grand marshal is
supposed to die the day after the parade so (he) can't do anything
bigger than that. But that probably won't happen. I'll be too
happy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-writethru a0464 03-17 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-writethru, a0464,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Mayors Resign In El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with mayors' resignations, army searches
at national university. Trims to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas forced two
city mayors to resign today and disrupted public transportation and
electrical power nationwide in a bid to disrupt Sunday's
presidential election.
   The mayors of the northern provincial capital of Chalatenango and
the northwest city of Metapan resigned after the rebels renewed
threats against the country's mayors over clandestine radio.
   The armed forces said guerrilla threats to shoot people driving
on the nation's highways reduced traffic by 90 percent. Officials
said the rebels had knocked out about 60 percent of the electrical
power nationwide. Rebel sabotage also halted water and telephone
service in some areas, the officials said.
   Leftist rebels, who boycotted the last five elections, renewed
calls on Salvadorans to boycott Sunday's voting, broadcasting death
threats against poll workers. Three-pronged metal tacks were
scattered on streets to puncture tires.
   The three main presidential contenders in the election are
Alfredo Cristiani, 41, of the rightist Repubican Nationalist
Alliance, or Arena; Fidel Chavez Mena of the incumbent Christian
Democrats; and Guillermo Ungo of the leftist Democratic Convergence
alliance. The Arena candidate is favored to win.
   The incumbent, President Napoleon Duarte, is barred by law from
seeking a second five-year term.
   The mayors' resignations brought to 137 the number who have left
their jobs because of rebel threats. Nine Salvadoran mayors have
been assassinated.
   The guerrillas refuse to recognize mayors elected in municipal
voting they consider illegitimate, and more than half the country's
towns and cities are now without chief executives.
   Streets remained vacant in the capital early today.
   Troops stationed at the national university searched vehicles and
everyone who entered and left the campus. A lieutenant who refused
to give his name said the soldiers were looking for bombs and
weapons.
   Reports of guerrilla violence were down today, two days after
campaigning officially ended. But authorities did not expect the
lull to last until Sunday's election.
   ``We are going to hear some bombs, and we are going to see
sabotage and they will make us a bit nervous,'' the defense
minister, Gen. Eugenio Vides Casanova, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
