<HEAD>Ex-Congressman Being Treated For Bone Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Bill Chappell,
defeated last year after 20 years in Congress, announced today that
he is being treated for bone cancer.
   ``I want all my friends to know I'm feeling fine and plan to see
them back in the district soon,'' Chappell, 67, said in a news
release issued by the law offices of Coble and Barkin in Daytona
Beach. A woman who answered the phone there refused to give her name
and said she couldn't make any additional comment.
   Chappell was admitted to the Warren Grant Magnuson Clinical
Center in Methesda, Md., on Feb. 23 by the National Cancer Institute
and is in stable condition, said Irene Haske, chief of the
hospital's communications department.
   The Pentagon procurement scandal may have cost Chappell, a
Democrat, his 4th District seat in November's election. The
investigation has spawned reports that Chappell received political
contributions and financial aid from military suppliers, some of
whom are targets of the inquiry.
   He has said he did nothing wrong and fears nothing from the
investigation into bribery and kickbacks among defense consultants,
Pentagon officials and military contractors.
   ``Nobody has ever put a face on any accusation; nobody has come
forth and said I have done anything, only by innuendo and
insinuation,'' Chappell told the Orlando Sentinel.
   In an interview published Sunday, he said he was enjoying his
retirement.
   ``I have been in politics 36 years, and I honest to goodness
didn't realize how much I was hooked up, tied down to things. I
can't believe the pressure is off. There are days when I don't see a
newspaper of even think about a newspaper,'' Chappell said.
