<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Executions     03-17 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Executions,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Aide To Idi Amin Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities hanged a former associate of
deposed dictator Idi Amin and two other convicted killers in the
African country's first legal executions of civilians in 10 years, a
newspaper reported Friday.
   Kassim Obura, who headed the feared Public Safety Unit during
Amin's 9-year rule, was hanged in Luzira prison near Kampala on
Wednesday, the state-owned New Vision newspaper said.
   Two other men convicted of murder also were hanged, the report
said.
   Obura was arrested after Amin's overthrow in 1979 and convicted
three years later of shooting on the head with a shotgun a Kampala
trader whose business he later seized.
   At the time of his execution, Obura was was among 80 convicts
waiting to be hanged in the country's jails.
   New Vision said various presidents had failed to sanction death
sentences since 1979 because Uganda's gallows ``were out of order.''
   Although the gallows had not been used, thousands of Ugandans
were killed by security forces during Amin's rule and in subsequent
fighting in which two governments were overthrown.
   President Yoweri Museveni's government, formed after his fighters
chased military rulers from office in 1986, has announced several
firing squad executions of soldiers convicted of committing
atrocities against civilians.
</TEXT>
