<DOCNO> AP890317-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   03-17 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills 12 in Beirut's Christian Sector</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded 50 yards from the
British Embassy in Christian east Beirut on Friday, demolishing a
crowded bakery and killing 12 people. Police said 75 were wounded.
   No group claimed responsibility. The commander of Christian army
units blamed Syria but a Christian radio station said the target may
have been the embassy because of the controversy over ``The Satanic
Verses'' by Salman Rushdie, a British citizen.
   People were lined up to buy bread at the Habib bakery on a
coastal highway in the Jal el-Deeb district when the car blew up,
hurling bodies into the air, police reported.
   Shattered glass littered the street. Pieces of human flesh could
be seen in the wreckage.
   ``People had taken advantage of the relative calm to buy some
bread and food in fear of another round of shelling,'' a police
spokesman said.
   Beirut residents had taken shelter for more than a week because
of artillery exchanges between Christian soldiers and Moslem
militiamen that rained shells on the city.
   Sporadic shelling continued during the day despite a truce in the
artillery and rocket battle.
   The explosion, which police said equaled 110 pounds of TNT,
wrecked 20 nearby vehicles and devastated shops and restaurants
around the bakery.
   Its force broke the windows of the British Embassy. Edgy Lebanese
guards crouched at corners of the mission, keeping reporters out and
firing volleys into the air from their automatic weapons.
   Hospitals appealed by radio for blood donations. A doctor at the
Abu-Jaoudeh hospital in Jal el-Deeb, his gown stained with blood,
said two bodies were disfigured beyond recognition.
   The emergency ward's waiting area became a makeshift operating
room. Doctors removed glass slivers from the legs and faces of
dozens of victims.
   It was the fifth bombing in Lebanon this year. Police say 13
people were killed and 68 wounded in the four other explosions.
   Voice of Lebanon, the radio station of the Christian Phalange
party, said the nearness to the six-story embassy building suggested
it was the target.
   ``The British Embassy has received threats of attacks over Salman
Rushdie's controversial novel,'' the broadcast said.
   Many Moslems feel ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam, and
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran has ordered the author killed.
   Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian army command issued a statement
claiming the Syrian army, which oversees security in Moslem west
Beirut, arranged the bombing to provoke more sectarian artillery
battles.
   ``Our army units will not be be dragged into bombarding our
people in west Beirut,'' it said.
   About three hours after the blast, six shells landed in Christian
east Beirut and four of them hit the government-run port. There were
no reports of casualties or serious damage.
   A cease-fire was proclaimed at midnight Thursday in the
confrontation between Aoun's men and the Syrian-backed Druse militia
led by Walid Jumblatt.
   Fighting began March 8, two days after Aoun impose a blockade on
illegal ports run by Moslem militias.
   It threatened efforts of Arab League mediators to resolve a
political crisis that created Christian and Moslem governments and
has split the army into sectarian commands. Aoun leads the Christian
government in addition to commanding the Christian army.
   Police said 49 people were killed and 161 wounded, nearly all of
them civilians, in the artillery battles. It was the most serious
fighting between Christians and Moslems since 1985 in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war.
   Aoun's Christian military cabinet competes with a predominantly
Moslem government led by Premier Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem.
   President Amin Gemayel chose Aoun to lead the government when his
own six-year term expired in September and conservative Christians
would not accept Syria's nominees to succeed him. Moslems then
pledged allegiance to Hoss.
   By tradition, Lebanon's president is Christian, the premier Sunni
and the parliament speaker Shiite Moslem.
   Syrian has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon and has become the nation's
main power broker.
</TEXT>
