<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-Artist     03-17 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Artist,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronaut's Wife Documents Discovery Flight With Paintings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of one of the astronauts
aboard the space shuttle Discovery is a watercolor artist who plans
to remember the mission with one ``very special'' painting.
   ``I've been following the flight very closely, but the idea of
what I'm going to do hasn't congealed yet,'' Molly Springer said
Friday from her home near the Johnson Space Center in Houston. Her
husband is Bob Springer, who was making his first space flight.
   ``It may be something on the landing,'' she said.
   ``But whatever it is, it definitely will be something very
special,'' she added.
   Discovery's landing was scheduled Saturday morning at Edwards Air
Force Base, Calif.
   Mrs. Springer is a member of the NASA Art Team and one of several
artists commissioned to document the flight of the shuttle Atlantis
with the Magellan Venus probe, scheduled for launch April 28. Her
painting of that flight will become part of the space agency's
official art collection.
   Mrs. Springer's work on her husband's mission was on her own.
   She has been working on a watercolor series which she describes
as an unofficial glimpse of preparations for a space shuttle flight.
   For months, she followed her husband and his crewmates through
their training and she snapped hundreds of photographs, which she
uses as references for her paintings.
   She often points her camera away from the astronauts to focus on
the engineers and technicians ``who never get on camera, never get
in paintings, the people who make it all possible.''
   Space flight is ``a tapestry of people who really care what
happens,'' Mrs. Springer said. ``It just so happens that the
astronaut is the one we see the most.''
   Springer took the camera to places she was not allowed to go.
   ``Where she cannot participate or observe the training, I've been
trying to cover some of that for her,'' Springer said in a
pre-launch interview. He said her paintings lend to the space
program ``a tremendous insight beyond what somebody else from the
outside can see.''
</TEXT>
