<FIRST>u w PM-Eagleburger 1stLd-Writethru a0417 03-17 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eagleburger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0417,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagleburger Approved for State Department Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Senate vote; picks up 4th graf pvs, Senator
after senator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate gave quick approval today to
Lawrence Eagleburger as deputy secretary of state, the State
Department's No. 2 position.
   The approval was by voice vote.
   Eagleburger's nomination was approved Thursday by the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, but only after sharp questioning from
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
   Helms, who spent two days questioning the nominee's business
relations with former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, took part
in the 19-0 vote to approve Eagleburger.
   Senator after senator praised Eagleburger repeatedly during his
two days of testimony for his distinguished 30-year career in
government.
   However, the hearings at times were shadowed by the recent bitter
conflict over former Sen. John Tower's failed nomination to be
Secretary of Defense.
   ``I have the uncomfortable feeling that I'm a test-tube case
here,'' Eagleburger quipped once while under some intense
questioning by Helms.
   Helms asserted that his queries into Eagleburger's dealings with
the consulting firm Kissinger Associates weren't out of line, given
the attention paid to Tower's $1 million in earnings from defense
contractors.
   Tower's nomination was defeated last week. The Senate was
expected to approve the nomination of Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., as
secretary of Defense today.
   ``I wish he had an opportunity to answer questions in public
about his income,'' Helms said of Tower. ``He wasn't allowed to
defend himself.''
   The senator also jabbed at Eagleburger's $900,000 in earnings
from Kissinger's firm and an affiliate, commenting that the
assessments he gave to multinational corporations on international
affairs ``must be extraordinary advice.''
   The firms Eagleburger dealt with, according to disclosure forms
filed with the Senate, include Anheuser-Busch, the South Korean
conglomerate Daewoo Corp., H.J. Heinz, the Italian car maker Fiat
S.p.a., ITT Corp., A.B. Volvo, Union Carbide, and Coca-Cola.
   Helms also tweaked Kissinger, calling him a ``revolving,
peripatetic entity.''
   ``Henry Kissinger was ... a political entity. He still is. That's
why Larry Eagleburger got well over a million dollars, ... not
because he (Kissinger) was good looking or speaks English
fluently,'' Helms said, a clear dig at Kissinger's looks and thick
accent.
   Helms, a staunch conservative, has been critical for years of
Kissinger's conduct of foreign policy, especially moves toward
closer relations with the Soviet Union, during the Nixon and Ford
administrations.
   Helms questioned whether Eagleburger's work for Kissinger's firm
conflicted with laws that require those who lobby for foreign
governments to register their activities with the U.S. government.
   Eagleburger stressed to the committee that he had never lobbied
the U.S. government on behalf of any of the firm's clients, and had
strictly abided by the law.
   His nomination was approved unanimously after he agreed to
disqualify himself from all matters involving clients who'd had
contact with the firm over the last two years, one of several steps
he agreed to take that went beyond the demands of the Ethics in
Government Act.
   Eagleburger received numerous plaudits for his years at the State
Department, including service as ambassador to Yugoslavia and
undersecretary of state for political affairs, the department's No.
3 post.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said Secretary of State James A.
Baker III was ``not an expert in foreign policy'' and needed
Eagleburger's expertise from 30 years in government.
   ``I want to see the president given this choice,'' Cranston said.
</TEXT>
