<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial 2ndLdWritethru a0520 03-17 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial, 2nd Ld Writethru, a0520,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Dissidents Given Suspended Jail Sentences</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with activists sentenced. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Prague court today gave 10-month
suspended sentences to two young dissidents who have been jailed
since October on charges stemming from anti-government protests.
   Anna Sabatova, a member of the Charter 77 human rights
organization, told reporters that Tomas Dvorak, 23, and Hana
Marvanova, a 26-year-old lawyer, were found guilty on charges of
preparation to incite.
   The judge dropped a more serious charge of incitement that could
have brought the leaders of the Independent Peace Association up to
three years in jail, Ms. Sabatova said.
   But a government prosecutor, Karel Florian, immediately appealed
the sentences, and filed a petition that will keep the two jailed
for at least another 10 days, a source familiar with Czechoslovak
legal procedure said.
   In a related development, the same source, speaking in Vienna on
condition of anonymity, said former Charter 77 spokesman Stanislav
Devaty was arrested in front of the Prague courtroom Thursday and
taken to his hometown of Gottwaldov in Moravia, where he remains in
detention.
   The two-day trial was the latest in a crackdown by the communist
government on dissent following an anti-government demonstrations in
August and January.
   The Aug. 21 protest that drew more than 10,000 marked the 20th
aniversary of the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia and was the
most substantial demonstration against the government in 19 years.
   Another Peace Association activist, Jane Petrova, was sentenced
last month to nine months in jail after participating in a peaceful
memorial for Jan Palach, a student who burned himself alive in 1969
to protest the invasion.
   Vaclav Havel, a playwright and prominent human rights activist,
was also sentenced in February to nine months in jail for
involvement in the protest. Seven other activists were jailed, fined
or given suspended sentences.
</TEXT>
