<FIRST>u w PM-SovietInspectors 1stLd-Writethru a0521 03-17 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Inspectors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0521,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Arriving for Nuclear Inspection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with second team at Maryland plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-member team of Soviet nuclear weapon
inspectors was conducting a ``short-notice inspection'' today at
Fort Sill, Okla., site of training facilities for troops operating
the Army's Pershing nuclear missiles, the Pentagon said.
   A second Soviet team was inspecting a Martin Marietta Corp.
manufacturing plant in Middle River, Md.
   The inspections, authorized by the U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces Treaty ratified last year, are the eighth and ninth
such inspections of the 20 allowed each side this year.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard had announced the arrival of the
two teams on Thursday, noting they were allowed to wait until today
to disclose which sites they wished to inspect.
   The INF treaty requires the United States and Soviet Union to
cease production, and destroy all existing stocks, of nuclear
missiles with a range of roughly 300 to 3,000 miles.
</TEXT>
