<FIRST>r a PM-Apples-Schools 1stLd-Writethru a0491 03-17 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apples-Schools, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apples Returning To School Cafeterias After Chemical Scare</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with apple sales off, changes pesticide
to chemical in references to Alar; Picks up 5th graf, `The announcement
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Apple-Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apples expelled from school cafeterias because
of a nationwide cancer scare will return to menus in the nation's
second-largest school district after passing chemical tests.
   Tests for the allegedly cancer-causing chemical Alar, known as
daminozide, proved negative for fresh apples, apple juice,
apple-raisin bars and frozen apple-cherry juice bars, Los Angeles
Unified School District Superintendent Leonard Britton said Thursday.
   ``We're delighted to report that apples will be back in school
and that they are absolutely safe,'' said district spokeswoman Diana
Munatones.
   The district still will withhold other apple products, including
apple sauce and canned apple slices, from school menus until test
results are delivered next week, officials said.
   Meanwhile, shipments of Washington apples dropped by 152,000
boxes in the past week, a sign that consumer sales are being hurt by
the Alar scare, an industry official said today in Yakima, Wash.
   The weekly report of out-of-state shipments of the nation's
largest apple crop showed a drop from 1.56 million boxes two weeks
ago to 1.4 million boxes last week. Each box contains 42 pounds of
apples.
   The announcement in the nearly 600,000-student district coincided
with similar pronouncements by the federal Environmental Protection
Agency, Food and Drug Administration and Department of Agriculture.
In a separate statement, the EPA, FDA and the Agriculture Department
said, ``The federal government believes that it is safe for
Americans to eat apples.''
   Although the EPA has acknowledged the link between daminozide and
cancer, James Moore, acting deputy EPA administrator, said Thursday
he considers the health risk insufficient at current use and residue
levels to warrant its removal from the market.
   The chemical is used by apple growers to regulate the ripening
rate of apples and to prolong shelf life.
   School district business service administrator Beth Louargand
said she didn't regret the weeklong apple ban.
   ``Our first concern is to be absolutely sure that children are
safe,'' Louargand said.
</TEXT>
