<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0498 03-17 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,900 Former Guardsmen Freed In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with former Guardsmen freed. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government today
released almost 1,900 former National Guardsmen, most of them jailed
since the 1979 revolution that ousted President Anastasio Somoza.
   The prisoners were freed in a ceremony at the Jorge Navarro Penal
Rehabilitation Center in Tipitapa, 15 miles east of Managua, where
the guardsmen were being held.
   The release was a first step in complying with an agreement by
Central American presidents on democratization in Nicaragua and the
eventual disbanding of U.S.-supported guerrillas that have been
fighting the Sandinista government.
   President Daniel Ortega presided over the release, accompanied by
the secretary general of the Organization of American States, Joao
Baena Soares; the minister of the interior, Tomas Borge; and Bishop
Bosco Vivas, a vicar of the Roman Catholic church in Managua.
   More than a thousand friends and family members waited at the
edge of the road near the penitentiary for the release. The Red
Cross said it was providing 60 buses to take the former guardsmen to
their homes throughout the nation.
   Most of the 1,894 prisoners had been jailed since the Sandinistas
came to power. The National Guard was disbanded after the overthrow
of Somoza.
   The National Assembly on Tuesday approved an amnesty for the
former guardsmen. The release was scheduled for Sunday but was moved
ahead to today.
   The assembly, however, refused to grant amnesty to 39 other
detainees who it said had committed ``atrocious crimes'' against the
Nicaraguan people.
   The government has also asked the United Nations to monitor the
country's elections, set for February 1990, and the 10-month
political campaign, a U.N. spokesman said Thursday.
   Ortega asked the assembly to grant the pardons under a peace
accord he signed in El Salvador on Feb. 14 with the presidents of
that country, Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica.
   Ortega also agreed to adopt democratic reforms and move up the
date of general elections by 10 months to February 1990.
   In exchange, the presidents agreed to draft a plan to dismantle
the 11,000-member Nicaraguan rebel army, known as the Contras, who
are now in base camps in Honduras. Their forces have faded since the
United States cut off most military aid to them early last year.
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo told Ortega during
a meeting Wednesday that the amnesty should be extended to all
jailed guardsmen and political prisoners, including 1,500 rebels in
Nicaraguan jails.
   The opposition Permanent Human Rights Commission says 6,000
people are in jail accused of aiding the Contras. Ortega has said
all Nicaraguan political prisoners will be freed if the Contras are
disbanded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ManchinImpeachment     03-17 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manchin Impeachment,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Virginia Treasurer Appears Before Impeachment Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Treasurer A. James Manchin
defended himself before an impeachment committee today, saying he
knew nothing of massive state losses for 1{ years because other
employees kept the information from him.
   ``Not a single witness has testified that I knew of the magnitude
of the losses,'' Manchin said.
   Manchin said he depended on then-Associate Treasurer Arnold
Margolin to run the investment office, and Margolin and his
employees did not tell him or his chief of staff about the losses,
which eventually totaled $279 million.
   ``The system failed,'' Manchin told the state House Judiciary
Committee. ``The checks didn't check. The balances didn't balance.''
   Manchin said the first he heard of the losses, the bulk of which
occurred from April to June 1987, in late November or early December
1988.
   Since then, Manchin said he has been keeping a close eye on the
investment division.
   ``No more trust in one person,'' Manchin said.
   But when Del. Rod Berry asked Manchin how much the investment
division made or lost last week, Manchin would not answer.
   ``We can get you a report on that,'' Manchin said.
   Manchin is the last witness scheduled to testify before the
committee.
   Former Gov. Arch Moore told committee on Thursday he had no idea
the consolidated investment fund was suffering losses in 1987, even
though he knew some bonds had suffered a significant drop in value.
   Moore said he learned of trouble in the investment fund in late
1988 from the private Touche Ross &amp; Co., which he had hired to
conduct an audit of state government.
   ``Had we had any idea, we certainly would have treated the
treasurer's office the same as a private investment firm giving us
professional counseling and reporting massive losses,'' Moore said.
``We would have had them on the carpet in a moment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
