<FIRST>r i AM-GandhiInquiry     03-17 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gandhi Inquiry,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Will Release Secret Report About Mother's Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi said Friday
he will release a secret report on his mother's assassination in
order to stop ``malicious innuendo'' about what it contains.
   Indira Gandhi, who preceded her son as prime minister, was killed
in 1984 by members of her personal guard.
   India's largest English-language newspaper, the Indian Express,
declared Tuesday the report prepared by Supreme Court Justice M.P.
Thakkar says Rajendra Kumar Dhawan, Mrs. Gandhi's personal
secretary, had ``consciously or unconsciously ... facilitated the
commission of a crime.''
   ``The needle of suspicion significantly points at his complicity
or involvement,'' the paper said.
   Dhawan, 52, was dismissed after Mrs. Gandhi's death but became an
aide to Rajiv Gandhi in February.
   Excerpts published in the Indian Express accuse Dhawan of lying
during questioning and giving unconvincing explanations about
entries in his diary, including the name of one of the two assassins.
   Dhawan has refused comment on the allegations but senior
government officials, including Home Minister Buta Singh, told
Parliament he was innocent.
   After the Indian Express article appeared, opposition parties
demanded the report be made public and dissension developed in
Gandhi's governing Congress Party.
   On Wednesday, the government suspended 63 opposition members of
Parliament who shouted slogans against supression of the report.
   Earlier Friday, about 80 members from the government party said
they would tell the prime minister they would release the report if
he did not. The Congress Party members said they had obtained
extensive portions of the text.
   Gandhi told Parliament: ``The events of the past few days have
caused the people of India immense distress. I, for my part, have
relived the terrible trauma of that time.
   ``The investigations are now complete and necessary followup
action will be taken soon. Therefore, the release of the report
would no longer prejudice the course of the criminal
investigations.''
   He said the published version ``is fueling willful distortion,
malicious innuendo and irresponsible character assassination. To put
a stop to this, it is important that the full text of the report be
made public.''
   It will be given to Parliament on March 27 when it reconvenes
after a vacation, he said.
   Thakkar's inquiry ran parallel to police investigations and he
submitted the report 15 months after Mrs. Gandhi was killed on Oct.
31, 1984.
   The government withheld it, citing national security. Gandhi told
lawmakers Thakkar wanted the report be kept secret because it might
jeopardize criminal investigations.
   Mrs. Gandhi was killed in the garden of her New Delhi residence
by two Sikh bodyguards as she walked to a television interview
accompanied by Dhawan.
   The Indian Express quoted the report as saying Dhawan ``fell
behind her just in the nick of the time as they were approaching the
scene of the assassination.''
   One assassin was shot and killed by other guards minutes later
and the other was convicted of murder and hanged in January. A third
Sikh, convicted of conspiracy, also was hanged.
</TEXT>
