<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-17 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Pledges to Probe Torture Charges Against Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguay's attorney general pledged
Friday to reopen dozens of lawsuits filed by Paraguayans who alleged
they were tortured by police during the regime of deposed Gen.
Alfredo Stroessner.
   ``I will personally make sure those suits already filed are
located and reactivated,'' the official, Diogenes Martinez, said
after meeting with human rights attorneys and people who allege they
were victims of torture.
   ``We want to make sure the abuses that happened in the past are
not repeated, and we are committed to clarifying the facts and
punishing the guilty,'' said Martinez, who received a folder of 42
criminal suits from the group.
   Stroessner was toppled in a Feb. 3 coup by Gen. Andres Rodriguez,
who pledged he would respect human rights.
   Justice and police authorities recently suspended from duty two
members of the Asuncion police department who were accused of
torture, but the authorities said no further action could be taken
until formal charges were filed.
   The suspended police officers, Augusto Caceres Spelt and Carmilo
Almada Saprissa, were named in several of the cases presented to
Martinez, said human rights lawyer Francisco Vargas.
   ``There are many, many more cases besides the ones we have
presented today,'' Vargas said.
   The Interior Ministry has started an investigation of another
officer mentioned in the suits, the chief of a Department of
Investigation section in the Asuncion police department, Alberto
Cantero.
   Feliz Bogado Gondra, a medical doctor, said he was beaten and
repeatedly submerged in water in 1977 because of his alleged links
with guerrillas and communists. Cantero conducted the torture,
Bogado Gonda said.
   ``The dunking is the worst. It gives you the sensation of death
and makes you sign anything they want,'' the 43-year-old Bogado
Gondra said.
   Author Jorge Canese also charged Cantero with directing his 1977
torture by dunking for activism in a university magazine that
criticized the government.
   ``Cantero was the one who would direct the tortures with a
walkie-talkie,'' said Canese, 41.
</TEXT>
