<FIRST>r a AM-Movie-CreditCards     03-17 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movie-Credit Cards,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie Theater Debuts Credit Card System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A credit card is all movie-lovers need to
buy tickets, popcorn and candy at a new suburban Washington theater,
but owners said Friday most patrons probably aren't ready to leave
their cash at home.
   ``I think we have a lifetime of cash transactions to overcome,''
said Dick Dodderidge, senior vice president for corporate marketing
of Kansas City-based American Multi-Cinema Inc. ``People obviously
are not used to whipping out a credit card when they go to the movie
theatre, so I think it's going to take a while for it to catch on.''
   By midday Friday, the opening day for the new AMC Courthouse
Plaza 8 Theaters, eight people had telephoned ahead to charge
tickets and concession stand vouchers, said manager Charlie
Stoessel. The theater began accepting credit card reservations
Tuesday.
   The Courthouse Plaza is the first U.S. cinema to have electronic
facilities for credit card transactions incorporated into its
design, although AMC began experimenting with the idea at a Kansas
theater several weeks ago, said Dodderidge.
   The theatre charges a 50-cent handling fee for telephoned advance
credit card reservations, which don't save specific seats but let
moviegoers avoid long ticket lines the day of a show, said Stoessel.
There is no extra charge for charges made in person.
   The computerized automatic ticket sales system can register
credit cards as quickly as cash, with a quick flick through a
scanning device, Dodderidge said. AMC imported the system from the
United Kingdom, where the credit concept has become popular over the
past three years.
   Another local chain, K-B Theatres, also plans to introduce credit
card transactions.
   ``We want to see how it works out for them first,'' said KB
general manager John Bailey. ``We think it will give our theatres an
edge. When people are trying to decide between one theatre and
another, that may be the thing that helps them make a decision.''
   Moviegoers have not been flocking to put their movie tickets on
plastic at a theatre in Overland Park, Kan., where AMC has been
testing the concept for three weeks. Credit card transactions at the
Oak Park Plaza have accounted for about 1{ percent of ticket sales _
up from six-tenths of 1 percent the first week, said manager Keith
Weidenkeller.
   ``It's growing,'' Weidenkeller said. ``Everybody that uses it
seems to want to use it again. I think it will just keep going. The
general response is, `Well, it's about time.'''
   ``It's all so new. We really don't know what to expect,'' said
Dodderidge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
