<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-17 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Denies Power Struggle, Calls For Patience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the governing
National Party denied Friday that he was attempting to oust
President P.W. Botha but conceded that their awkward relationship
needed to be clarified.
   The main white opposition party meanwhile said National Party
leader F.W. de Klerk lacked the political strength to complete the
``mini-coup'' he launched while Botha was recovering from a stroke.
   De Klerk, the education minister, became head of the National
Party on Feb. 2 when Botha resigned from the post two weeks after
suffering a stroke.
   The National Party's parliamentary caucus resolved this week that
it wants de Klerk to become president. However, Botha returned to
office Wednesday and has made clear he will remain in his post
indefinitely, regardless of the wishes of his party.
   ``It is my and my party's wish that the relationship with (Botha)
shall remain warm, sincere and healthy,'' de Klerk said in
Parliament in Cape Town. ``Be calm. We will find a sensible way.''
   De Klerk also said that a new constitution _ presumably one that
would include the black majority _ would have to be introduced to
replace the one Botha helped introduce in 1984.
   ``The National Party remains committed to its goal of power
sharing,'' said de Klerk. ``A new constitution, differing
substantially from what we have today, must come about.''
   The role of the president would have to be ``reviewed
drastically,'' de Klerk added.
   Under South Africa's apartheid policies of racial segregation,
the country's 5 million whites maintain political and economic
control over the country's 28 million blacks, who have no vote in
national affairs.
   De Klerk has been depicted as more pragmatic and flexible than
Botha, although they appear to agree on most major policy issues.
   In recent speeches, de Klerk has called for race reform, but has
not put forward any specific proposals. Also, he has emphasized his
commitment to continued segregation of white neighborhoods and
schools.
   Ferdie Hartzenberg, deputy leader of the extreme right
Conservative Party, said de Klerk wanted to oust Botha, but lacked
the political strength to do so.
   ``The whole of South Africa can be behind (de Klerk), he still
knows he cannot match P.W. Botha in a man-to-man contest ... he is
too weak.''
   Hartzenberg, whose party favors strict segregation, also
questioned de Klerk's commitment to sharing power with blacks.
   ``Mr. de Klerk does not even want to share power with the state
president, let alone other groups.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
