<FIRST>r i AM-Tibet     03-17 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Official Warns of More Protests in Tibet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Chinese Communist Party in Tibet
said Tibetan activists may defy martial law and adopt ``new
methods'' to fight Chinese rule of the remote region, the official
press said Friday.
   A Tibetan, contacted by telephone in Lhasa, said the city was
quiet on the 30th anniversary of the flight of Tibet's spiritual
leader, the Dalai Lama, from his homeland to India during an
uprising against Chinese rule.
   He said police and soldiers were posted throughout the city and
arrests continued of Tibetans suspected of taking part in three days
of protests last week. At least 16 people were reported killed in
the protests.
   Tibetans contacted on March 10, after foreign tourists were
expelled from the city, reported large-scale roundups by Chinese
security forces.
   A Nepalese businessman said the city was ``very quiet'' but that
authorities had not let him leave his hotel.
   The People's Daily quoted party leader Hu Jintao as saying the
situation in Lhasa ``was reaching stability'' after 10 days of
martial law.
   ``But a minority of (separatists) will not let the matter drop,''
he was quoted as saying. ``They might switch their tricks and adopt
new methods of opposition. Because of this we must raise our
vigilance.''
   Hu did not elaborate as to what new methods of protest Tibetans
might use.
   Last week, an official at the provincial office of Tibet reported
scattered cases of rock throwing by Tibetans defying martial law.
   Hu said the riots were the most violent since protests against
nearly four decades of Communist rule began in September 1987.
   In Friday's report, the People's Daily said the demonstrators
concentrated their attacks on government and party buildings, police
stations and facilities belonging to the state-run news media.
   Twenty-four government and party buildings, 99 private
Chinese-owned businesses, more than 20 automobilies, scores of
bicycles and three-wheeled motorcars were destroyed in the riots,
the report said.
   The martial law has led to fears that China will adopt an even
harder line toward the remote mountainous region. But Hu was quoted
as saying Tibet would be reopened to foreign tourists once martial
law was lifted.
   Martial law was ordered after three days of protests began March
5, leaving 16 dead and about 100 people injured by official count.
Tibetans said that between 20 and 30 people died.
   The March protests came as Tibetans tried to commemorate the one
year anniversary of an anti-Chinese clash with police that left an
estimated 24 people dead.
   Beijing claims that Tibet has been part of China since the 13th
century. Tibetans contend their homeland was independent for most of
that time.
   The goals of the protests have been to express four decades of
anger over what is perceived as alien rule and possibly win outside
support. Independence remains a vague concept among the protesters,
who call simply for the return of the Dalai Lama to power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
