<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-17 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Negotiators to Exchange Offers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget negotiators will start exchanging offers
next week and Democrats will push to make military cuts equal to
domestic spending cuts in fiscal 1990, the chairman of the House
Budget Committee said Friday.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., following a negotiating session with
White House representatives, said the two sides talked about
President Bush's plan to increase military spending but freeze
domestic programs to meet the deficit targets of the Gramm-Rudman
law.
   ``I made the point that from a congressional point of view,
Gramm-Rudman has established the principle that... you get equal
amounts out of defense and non-defense,'' Panetta said.
   Richard Darman, the director of the president's Office of
Management and Budget, declined to comment on Friday's meeting.
   Panetta said he and Senate Budget Committee Chairman Jim Sasser,
D-Tenn., planned to work together in drafting a Democratic budget
proposal. In addition to the balance between domestic and military
spending cuts, Panetta said he wants new revenues to equal the
overall spending cuts.
   ``We're going to start exchanging offers and the direction I'm
heading in is basically to do dollar for dollar,'' he said.
   In addition to the White House-congressional budget talks Friday,
Sasser convened his committee on Friday to officially begin drafting
a budget, in parallel to the talks with the administration. He and
other committee members pointed out the insistent demands for new
federal spending, for cleaning up nuclear plants, bailing out
savings and loans, education, health care, defense, and a wide swath
of other programs.
   ``The overwhelming impression is a radical mismatch between the
ends most of us acknowledge, and the means we have at our disposal
for reaching them,'' Sasser said.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., and several other members of the
committee expressed frustration that, despite claims it would turn
things around, the deficit has begun going up again under
Gramm-Rudman.
   ``The Gramm-Rudman law reduces deficit, and not deficit
estimates,'' he said.
</TEXT>
