<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Prince of Wales, after a
much-touted plan to star in an international polo tournament in the
United Arab Emirates, did not show up at all on Friday.
   People who spent up to $260 for the privilege of watching Charles
swing his mallet at the Dubai Polo Club were told that Charles had
been advised by Britain not to play ``for security reasons.''
   Charles left later in the day for a two-day visit to Saudi Arabia.
   Iran has criticized the tour of the Gulf states that Charles and
his wife, the Princess of Wales, started Sunday.
   Iran broke relations with Britain on March 7, accusing it of
trying to undermine Islam by supporting British novelist Salman
Rushdie and his book ``The Satanic Verses.'' Moslems consider the
book blasphemous and Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued an execution
order against Rushdie.
   Tehran radio accused the British government of exploiting the
royal tour to ``give a cold shoulder to the world Moslems,'' warning
that Britain would face their ``wrath.''
   Charles and Diana made stops in Kuwait and Bahrain before
arriving in the United Arab Emirates on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STRATFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After spending countless nights in hotels
on the campaign trail, former presidential candidate George McGovern
has become an innkeeper himself.
   McGovern helped celebrate the grand opening Thursday of the
renovated Stratford Inn, the 150-room motel he bought last year for
$1 million from the Irish Hotel Group Inc.
   ``I've been in politics for 30 years and I spent a third of that
in hotels and inns,'' the fit-looking, 66-year-old former senator
from South Dakota said. The inn is McGovern's first business venture.
   McGovern, who left the Senate in 1980, has been making weekly
trips to the motel to direct $500,000 worth of renovations.
   He and his wife, Eleanor, will stay in the motel's newly renamed
McGovern suite when they are not on the road.
   McGovern said he will continue on the lecture circuit, leaving
day-to-day operations to his manager, James O'Donnell, and
O'Donnell's assistant, McGovern's 35-year-old son, Steven.
   McGovern met O'Donnell several years ago, when a fire destroyed
McGovern's apartment in Washington and he and his wife took up
temporary residence at the Normandy Inn, also run by the Irish Hotel
Group.
   When the company decided to divest its American holdings,
O'Donnell called McGovern, who had expressed interest in owning a
hotel.
</TEXT>
