<FIRST>r w AM-Homeless-Oz     03-17 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless-Oz,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>`There's No Place Like Home' Campaign Targets Homeless Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Using footage from the classic children's film
``The Wizard of Oz,'' the National Association of Social Workers
launched a national campaign Friday to highlight the issue of
homelessness, especially as it affects families with children.
   ``The point obviously is that Dorothy discovered `there's no
place like home,''' said NASW spokeswoman Lucy Sanchez, referring to
the role portrayed by Judy Garland, who is swept away by a tornado
from her Kansas home into the fantasyland of Oz.
   ``But for 3 million Americans, home is no place,'' said Sanchez.
   The association selected Dorothy's heel-clicking refrain for its
annual theme to assure the public doesn't become desensitized to the
issue of homelessness when families with children represent the
fastest growing segment of the homeless population, said NASW
Executive Director Mark Battle.
   The campaign comes as Hollywood readies a 50th anniversary
celebration for the 1939 movie and association members' work is
recognized during Social Work Month in March.
   The 30-second public service announcements will air on radio and
television stations during March and April in cities including Los
Angeles, Atlanta, Miami, Detroit, Washington D.C., Chicago, Denver,
Philadelphia and Houston with an estimated audience of 38 million
households.
   The NASW is a 120,000-member group of social workers employed in
hospitals, business and industry, schools and government agencies.
</TEXT>
