<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Husak     03-17 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Husak,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husak Suffers Mild Stroke; Dubcek denied Visa to Leave Prague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Gustav Husak has suffered
a mild stroke and is recovering in hospital, the official news
agency said Friday.
   The brief report from the official CTK news agency was the first
confirmation that Husak, who replaced Alexander Dubcek as Communist
Party leader after the 1968 Soviet-led invasion, was ill.
   Husak, 75, relinquished the party leadership to Milos Jakes in
December 1987 but remained a member of the 13-man ruling Politburo.
There has been persistent but unconfirmed speculation that Husak may
quit the Politburo at the Central Committee meeting scheduled for
Thursday and Friday.
   Husak presided over the ``normalization policy'' that followed
the 1968 invasion and partial occupation of Czechoslovakia by Warsaw
Pact forces, crushing Dubcek's ``Prague Spring'' economic reforms.
   Also Friday, in the southern city of Bratislava, Dubcek's wife
said Dubcek has been denied a visa to attend the Communist Party
Congress in Italy, his wife said.
   Anna Dubcek said by telephone from the couple's home that her
husband had planned to leave Friday for Italy, where the congress
begins this weekend.
   In Italy, a spokesman for the congress told the Associated Press
that the party would protest if Dubcek did not receive a visa before
the congress ends on Wednesday.
