<DOCNO> AP890317-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 2103EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Collapse     03-17 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Collapse,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed, 25 Injured As Medieval Tower Crumbles In Italy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MIL3,5,8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAVIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 900-year-old tower collapsed onto a square
Friday, killing two people, injuring 25 and damaging an adjacent
cathedral. Rescue workers pulled three people from the rubble.
   None of those treated at the San Matteo hospital in the northern
Italian town of Pavia were injured seriously, doctors said.
   Experts said the 255-foot tower crumbled either because of
natural decay in the mortar holding the bricks together or because
of a sudden sinking following a dry spell that lowered the water
table.
   Shortly before the thick walls toppled, several rocks fell from
the top, prompting passers-by in the square to flee, authorities
said.
   ``The toll could have been higher without that warning,'' said a
spokeswoman for Mayor Sandro Bruni.
   She said there had been no signs indicating the tower was in
danger of collapsing but added that experts had recently checked to
see if it needed restoration. The dead were identified as
52-year-old Giuseppina Casella, whose newspaper stand was buried by
the bricks, and Giulio Fontana, 62.
   After the collapse, firefighters frantically dug through a pile
of rubble at least 30 feet high and eventually pulled out two men
and a woman.
   The red bricks that fell on the downtown square buried several
parked cars and damaged several shops and one building.
   The 501-year-old Duomo cathedral, partly designed by Donato
Bramante, also suffered substantial damage.
   Bramante introduced a style of architecture combining Renaissance
ideas with experimentation that came to be known as the High
Renaissance style, which influenced European architecture for 300
years.
   He is best known for the design for St. Peter's Basilica.
   Pavia Archbishop Giovanni Volta said that the baptistery of the
Duomo cathedral and one arch of the church were cracked in Friday's
disaster.
   Residents were evacuated from two old buildings near the
collapsed tower.
   ``It's (the collapse) something due to age, which cannot be
predicted,'' said Maria Antonietta Abrate, an official of the local
government office for protection of monuments. ``It's typical of
ancient towers. It also happened to the belltower of Venice.''
   In 1902, the 1,000-year-old St. Mark Bell Tower in Venice
collapsed without warning, causing no injuries. A worldwide
fund-raising drive raised enough money to build a replica, completed
in 1912.
   Pavia, 20 miles southwest of Milan, is rich with medieval art and
architecture and is called ``the city of the 100 towers.''
   It was founded in 568 by the German tribe of the Longobards.
   Italy's most famous tower, the Leaning Tower of Pisa, has long
been judged in danger of collapsing although not in the immediate
future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 2243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-McGivern     03-17 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McGivern,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Killing Policeman Released On Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTISVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sentenced to 25 years to life for
his conviction in the 1968 killing of a sheriff's deputy was
released from prison on parole Friday, after serving 14 years.
   Gary McGivern, whose release had been supported by a group of
celebrities, ``waved and said, `It's nice to be out,''' reported
James Flateau, spokesman for the state prison system.
   McGivern was granted clemency on New Year's Eve 1985 by Gov.
Mario Cuomo, making him eligible for parole. On Wednesday, the state
Board of Parole approved McGivern's third parole request.
   McGivern has maintained that he had no part in the deputy's death.
   Flateau said McGivern was picked up at the medium-security
Otisville prison by his wife, free-lance writer Marguerite Culp of
Woodstock, who led the battle to free him.
   Culp attracted support from well-known people including folk
singer Pete Seeger, conservative columnist William F. Buckley and
liberal lawyer William Kunstler.
   However, their 1978 prison marriage isn't legally recognized in
New York state because he was serving a life term at the time. For
contract purposes, lifers are considered to be legally dead and thus
cannot marry.
   Prosecutors said McGivern and co-defendant Charles Culhane were
involved in a 1968 escape attempt, while being driven to a court
appearance, in which a Westchester County deputy was killed. The
prosecution said McGivern fired the shot that killed the deputy.
   McGivern and Culhane have steadfastly maintained that a third
inmate in the car, Robert Bowerman, was the only one involved in the
escape attempt and that he shot the deputy. Bowerman also was killed.
   A second deputy in the car survived and testified that McGivern
and Culhane were involved in the escape attempt.
   McGivern and Culhane were tried three times for the deputy's
murder. The first trial ended in a hung jury. Convictions in the
second trial were overturned on appeal. They were convicted again in
1975.
   Culhane won't be eligible for parole until late 1991. Cuomo has
refused to grant him clemency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
