<FIRST>r a AM-CrimeVictims     03-17 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crime Victims,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims' Families Launch Court Reform Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITTIER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of slain automobile racing
promoter Mickey Thompson, Charles Manson ``family'' victim Sharon
Tate and others have launched a drive to speed up trials and
increase criminal penalties.
   The relatives of Thompson and Miss Tate announced Thursday, the
first anniversary of the racing promoter's murder, they had begun a
petition to put an initiative before voters next year.
   Miss Tate's mother, Doris, said she has gathered 352,000
signatures since 1984 from people opposing paroles for Manson's
followers who killed her actress-daughter and eight other people in
1969.
   Relatives of Thompson and his wife, Trudy, who were shot at their
home, said they decided to use the anniversary of the killing to do
something for victims' relatives.
   ``At first we didn't know how to recognize this anniversary,''
Collene Thompson Campbell, Thompson's daughter, said during the news
conference at Rose Hills Cemetery. ``We're still devastated, angry,
lonely and frustrated. We decided Mickey and Trudy would want us to
do something that would make a difference to every Californian.''
   ``Our fond hope today is that very soon the killers will be
caught and brought to justice,'' said Thompson's son, Danny. ``Now
we are preparing for that day.''
   A $260,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of the Thompsons' assailants is being offered.
   The initiative, which if passed would amend the state
constitution, consists of 13 proposals ranging from changing grand
jury and preliminary hearing procedures to speeding the flow of
trials through the court system.
   The measure also would create a crime of torture, with a sentence
of life in prison, and would increase penalties for some crimes.
   A similar ballot measure last year was abandoned after it failed
to gather enough signatures.
   In the latest effort, a section pertaining to the death penalty
was deleted in the hopes of achieving more bipartisan support, said
Orange County Deputy District Attorney Jim Cloninger, one of the
initiative's authors.
   To qualify for the November 1990 ballot, measure organizers need
to collect 600,000 signatures of registered voters over 150 days. It
is expected to cost about $300,000 just to qualify the initiative.
</TEXT>
