<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovak-Trial     03-17 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Trial,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Group Members Given Suspended Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of an independent peace
group imprisoned since October were given suspended sentences of 10
months each Friday after a two-day trial.
   Anna Sabatova of the Charter 77 human rights group, who attended
the trial, said Tomas Dvorak, 23, and Hana Marvanova, 26, of the
Independent Peace Assocation were convicted of preparation to
incitement in connection with an illegal rally in October.
   More serious charges of incitement connected with an
anti-government rally in August were dropped, she said.
   Prosecutor Karel Florian appealed the suspended sentences and
filed a complaint against an order by Judge Jan Belohradsky to free
the defendants, Ms. Sabatova said.
   Florian had demanded half of the maximum three-year sentence
provided by the criminal code.
   About 50 people cheered Dvorak and Ms. Marvanova as they were led
from the court. They remained in custody Friday night.
   The trial was the latest event in a crackdown on dissent stemming
from the August and October protests and a week of unrest in January.
   Playwright Vaclav Havel was sentenced in February to nine months
in jail and seven other activists were jailed, fined or given
suspended sentences. Havel's appeal is to be heard Tuesday.
   Last week, two activists were given sentences of 6 and 16 months
for organizing a petition demanding an explanation of the death in
jail last year of dissident Pavel Wonka.
   An emigre source in Vienna said Friday that Stanislav Devaty, a
former Charter 77 spokesman detained by police outside the Prague
courtroom Thursday, was under arrest in his hometown of Gottwaldov
in Moravia.
   Police searched the homes of five people in Moravia and five in
Brno hin the previous 24 hours, the source said on condition of
anonymity.
   Charges against Dvorak and Ms. Marvanova changed several times
during their detention. CTK, the official news agency said in a
short report late Friday the original charges of hooliganism were
dropped after a presidential amnesty in October.
   Ms. Sabatova and fellow Charter 77 activist Vaclav Maly were in
the courtroom on both days of the proceedings. They were joined
Friday by Charter 77 spokesman Alexander Vondra.
   Last Aug. 21, the 20th anniversary of the Soviet-led invasion of
Czechoslovakia, Dvorak and Ms. Marvanova helped draw up a petition
read by Dvorak and including demands for free elections, release of
all political prisoners and withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   After it was read, a crowd estimated at 10,000 marched around
Prague in the first such mass protest in 19 years.
   Dvorak was arrested Oct. 22 and Ms. Marvanova Oct. 28, before the
banned rally to mark Czechoslovakia's independence in 1918. Riot
police dispersed about 5,000 people who attended.
</TEXT>
