<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle Bjt   03-17 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt,0935</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Pack Up, Head for Saturday Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HTN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Discovery astronauts packed up
their gear Friday, checked their experiments one last time and
prepared the space shuttle for a fiery dash through the Earth's
atmosphere and a dawn landing Saturday on a California desert.
   Crew members, said to be ``excellent spirits'' throughout the
mission, also took more photographs of the Earth and gave an
interview from space on the last full day of their flight.
   The astronauts were to awake early Saturday to get ready for the
hourlong plunge through the atmosphere and a powerless glide halfway
around the world. Landing is scheduled at 6:35 a.m. PST at Edwards
Air Force Base, Calif.
   ``We're looking for a good, clean landing tomorrow,'' flight
director Lee Briscoe said, adding that the forecast calls for
scattered clouds and light winds.
   ``This one (flight) probably ranks as one of the more
trouble-free,'' Briscoe said.
   Discovery commander Michael L. Coats and pilot John E. Blaha
checked several shuttle systems 180 miles above the Earth on Friday,
making sure the computers and control jets were ready for the trip
home.
   Unlike most previous flights, Discovery's re-entry will not go
through the eerie radio blackout that has occurred when a shuttle is
descending through the atmosphere.
   The blackout, which used to last about 15 minutes, occurs when a
spacecraft generates heat during its re-entry, ionizing atoms that
form a layer of electrically charged gas around the shuttle. The
layer blocks radio transmissions between the orbiter and the ground.
   But with the help of a $100 million communications satellite
deployed during the first post-Challenger flight last fall, Briscoe
said, ground controllers' contact with the shuttle should be
interrupted only about three minutes.
   Instead of trying to send radio messages straight to the ground,
the shuttle can send them to the satellite more than 20,000 miles
above Earth, which relays them to the ground.
   The satellite was first used in December during a classified
Defense Department mission by shuttle Atlantis, the second mission
since the Challenger disaster. It had a blackout of only about three
minutes, Briscoe said.
   Although controllers don't plan to communicate with Discovery
during the traditional blackout time, the ability is there in case a
problem occurs or if they wants the orbiter to land on a different
runway at Edwards, he said.
   If winds Saturday morning are 14-17 mph, Mission Control would
like Discovery to land on the dry lakebed to determine how the
shuttle handles under higher winds. But if the winds aren't strong
enough, the shuttle will land on a concrete runway to test its new
brake system, Briscoe said. The forecast makes the runway landing
more likely, he said.
   A final decision will be made about an hour before Coats and
Blaha fire two powerful rockets on the back of the shuttle to slow
the spacecraft and allow it to drop into the Earth's atmosphere.
   The other crew members are James F. Buchli, Robert C. Springer
and Dr. James M. Bagian, a physician.
   Discovery, the first of seven shuttle missions planned this year,
rocketed into orbit Monday after being delayed for about two hours
because of the weather. The flight is the third since the Challenger
explosion killed its seven astronauts more than three years ago.
   Several hours after blastoff, the crew completed its primary
mission _ deployment of a $100 million communications satellite that
completes a network NASA can use to communicate with shuttles and
other satellites nearly all the time.
   On Tuesday, the crew had to turn off unnecessary lights and
computers because of concern about erratic pressure readings from a
hydrogen tank that helps provide electricity to the orbiter. But the
shuttle was back on full power the next day after engineers
corrected the problem.
   Among the scientific experiments on board Discovery are four rats
and 32 fertilized chicken eggs _ two projects designed by students.
   The end of the mission also will be the end for the four rats,
which will be killed shortly after touchdown so researchers can
determine how their intentionally cut legs healed in space.
   But the eggs, housed in an incubator on the shuttle, will be
allowed to hatch to see if embryos can develop normally in space.
   Discovery's astronauts will return with nearly three miles of
film shot with a 70mm IMAX camera. The crew captured views of
pollution patterns in the oceans, floods in Africa, burned areas of
the Florida Everglades and western United States, and erupting
volcanoes in South America and Southeast Asia.
   During an interview Friday morning on the ``Today'' show on NBC,
Buchli said the scale and scope of air pollution ``is much more
dramatic'' as seen from orbit.
   ``What we're trying to do is get some evidence and documentation
to bring back and show people just how much we are dumping into the
atmosphere and perhaps get a feel how that might affect us in future
generations,'' he said.
   The IMAX film will be edited to create a study of the
environmental wounds man has inflicted on the Earth.
   Other experiments on Discovery include a group of plants grown in
space to test the effects of weightlessness on root growth; a
protein crystal growth study using 19 different proteins; and a
device called the heat pipe, which is a type of cooling system being
tested for use on the space station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
