<FIRST>r a AM-NevadaExecution     03-17 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nevada Execution,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Row Inmate Wants No Stays Of Scheduled Nevada Execution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Harol' in second graf is correct.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old man sentenced to be
executed for killing a Las Vegas store clerk wants no stay of his
scheduled March 31 execution, a prison official says.
   David Pellegrini has been getting visits from relatives trying to
talk him into filing for a stay but he hasn't wavered in his
decision not to appeal, said Nevada State Prison Warden Harol
Whitley.
   ``We're going ahead with our preparations,'' said Whitley.
   However, he also said a court representative will be on hand as
the execution nears ``in case he changes his mind at the last
minute.''
   The warden said he doesn't know why Pellegrini wants no stay. He
also said the convict has said he won't allow any interviews unless
he is paid $500.
   Pellegrini had appealed to the state Supreme Court, but last
November the high court said the record provided substantial support
for the verdict and the penalty in the case.
   Pellegrini was sentenced to death for the October 1986 slaying of
Barry Hancock, 27, a convenience store clerk who was handcuffed and
shot in the head during a robbery.
   If Pellegrini is executed on schedule March 31, he would be the
107th person to be executed in this country since the U.S. Supreme
Court reviewed the death penalty in 1976. Two men have been executed
in Nevada since then. Ted Bundy was the last person to be executed
in the country, in Florida on Jan. 24.
</TEXT>
