<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviet     03-17 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Scorns Soviet Critique on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department accused a Soviet official
on Friday of attempting to ``rewrite history'' with charges that the
United States and Pakistan are prolonging the war in Afghanistan.
   ``There is no doubt in anyone's mind about the origin of the
current conflict and the difficulties in Afghanistan today. ... The
Soviets occupied and invaded Afghanistan,'' said spokesman Charles
E. Redman.
   ``He's trying to rewrite history,'' Redman said of comments made
in Kabul by the Soviet ambassador, Yuli Vorontsov.
   Vorontsov called the United States ``tremendously immoral'' for
continuing to supply arms to the Afghan rebels, who are opposing the
Soviet-backed government of Afghan leader Najib.
   The Soviet official also charged that the United States and
Pakistan were risking a wider war in the region because of their
support for the Afghan guerrilla attack on the city of Jalalabad.
   The guerrillas have moved on Jalalabad, located some 85 miles
east of Kabul, in the hopes of advancing on the capital city.
   Although the Soviets completed the withdrawal of their troops in
mid-February, a major new Soviet arms airlift began last week.
   Redman asserted that new shipments of heavy artillery rockets
have been made and that they are being used to ``terrorize the
Afghan people.''
   Redman also accused the Soviet ambassador of attempting to
intimidate Pakistan with his comments. He said, ``The Soviets should
know that Pakistan has our full support in this situation.''
   The spokesman said he could not quantify U.S. support for the
rebels.
   ``Our position has always been that our support for the
resistance, the Mujahedeen, was firm, and that we would do what was
necessary. And I'd just leave it at that,'' Redman said.
