<FIRST>r a AM-SleepyParamedics     03-17 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleepy Paramedics,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramedics Slept After Being Summoned to Help Heart Attack Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two paramedics were fired after they
slept through three emergency calls for a heart attack victim who
died en route to the hospital, a hospital official said.
   ``We have determined that human error was at fault,'' Pat Gouldy,
vice president of the Dallas-Fort Worth Medical Center, told the
Grand Prairie Emergency Services Advisory Board on Thursday night.
``We assume he (the ambulance driver) took the calls and fell back
asleep.''
   Gouldy said Clarence Cowden, 77, was dead when he arrived at the
hospital about an hour after his wife first called a 911 dispatcher.
   Ms. Gouldy said a chronology of the Feb. 8 incident was received
during an investigation. Both paramedics, who were not identified,
were fired later, Ms. Gouldy said.
   Cowden's two children listened as the report was read. His son,
Marvin, said the family was not seeking to punish anyone, but,
``Something has got to be done to make sure these people are on the
ball.''
   Since the incident, Ms. Gouldy said, the ambulance service has
installed loud alarm bells in each station and has ordered pagers to
be issued to crew members.
   ``The alarm bell rings when the phone rings,'' she said. ``All
unit pagers will have a coded tone to sound when the particular
station is being called.''
   Ms. Gouldy said a 911 dispatcher received a call from Cowden's
wife, Thelma, at 3:14 a.m. The dispatcher called the ambulance crew
at a substation 1{ miles from Cowden's home.
   The driver received the call at 3:15 a.m. in one of two bedrooms
at the station, Ms. Gouldy said. The other crew member did not have
a telephone in his room, she said.
   The dispatcher made two more calls when the crew did not announce
its departure on the radio. Both times a crew member answered the
telephone, but the ambulance did not move, Ms. Gouldy said.
   At 3:30 a.m., Ms. Gouldy said, an ambulance from another station
was dispatched. It arrived at the Cowden home at 3:35 a.m., 21
minutes after the first call, she said.
</TEXT>
