<HEAD>Nigerian Ambassador Visiting Houston to Ease Tensions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nigerian ambassador to the United States is
planning a trip here next week to try to ease what local Nigerians
say is a growing atmosphere of prejudice and persecution.
   Emeka Ozurumba, a Houston attorney and head of the Nigerian
Foundation, an organization of about 1,000 Nigerians in the city,
said Thursday the January shooting death of a Nigerian by police and
a television news report linking Nigerians to credit card scams is
fueling outrage in the community.
   ``The prejudice is everywhere,'' he said. ``The Nigerian
community has decided enough is enough, and they don't want to take
it anymore. They just want to live peacefully.''
   Nigerian Ambassador Hamzat Ahmadu will meet Monday and Tuesday
with city officials, Ozurumba said.
   Ozurumba does not dispute some Nigerians are criminals, but
insists they represent only a few of the 5,000 Nigerians living in
Houston.
   ``I do not pretend that all Nigerians are angels,'' he said. ``It
doesn't give anyone the right to generalize that all Nigerians are
criminals.''
   In January, Martin Nana, 33, was killed by police who were
summoned to his apartment by a security guard who said the man
refused to turn down loud music. Police who responded said the
Nigerian was shot after he lunged at an officer.
