<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Reform     03-17 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Reform,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sociologist Says 1989 Crucial Year For Soviet Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet sociologist on Friday said 1989 is
a critical year for President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms because
empty store shelves have damaged people's faith that things will
change.
   ``1989 will be a crucial year for perestroika,'' said Tatyana
Zaslavskaya. ``It is necessary to begin implementing promises.
Expectations are high.''
   Ms. Zaslavskaya is a leading theorist of reform efforts and heads
the Soviet Public Opinion Center. Her comments at a news conference
came a day after the Communist Party Central Committee approved a
farm reform to counter urgent food shortages.
   Gorbachev embarked on his reform program upon taking power in
1985, and Ms. Zaslavskaya said enthusiasm for the program reached a
peak in 1987. However, since then ``we are witnessing a
deterioration. The most important factor is the supply in the
shops,'' she said.
   Intellectuals still strongly support the reform effort because it
has provided a freer atmosphere for public discussion, art and
literature. But workers are more interested in their standard of
living, and polling data indicates most believe they are worse off,
she said.
   Gorbachev's measures include a major drive to make state-run
enterprises pay their own way rather than count on state subsidies.
Some experts say subsidies discourage producers from manufacturing
the cheap consumer goods that are in high demand.
   ``The Soviet people, the Russian people, have a lot of patience,
but some results are needed,'' Ms. Zaslavskaya said. ``The worst
thing is when the people become indifferent. Without the people, you
cannot go ahead.''
   Ms. Zaslavskaya said to heal its stagnating economy the Soviet
Union must enact broad price reforms, including eliminating many
heavy subsidies on retail prices. But any such changes must wait two
or three years, she said.
   ``If there is a price reform now it will harm perestroika
(Gorbachev's economic restructuring plan),'' Ms. Zaslavskaya said.
``In present conditions it would create a social uproar,'' she said.
   Some workers also are concerned about reforms that tie wages to
productivity, Ms. Zaslavskaya said.
   ``A considerable number of people working at factories and plants
for an average wage produce shoddy goods at a leisurely pace,'' she
said.
   The Soviet Central Committee on Thursday adopted an agriculture
program it says will improve food supplies by the mid-1990s.
   The program depends largely on giving farmers the right to take
long-term leases on state-run land and decide what to plant.
   Gorbachev sharply criticized the Soviet farm system and told the
Central Committee that the inability of state and collective farms
to feed the country was leading to social discontent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
