<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Fruit     03-17 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Fruit,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile Says Japanese Trawlers Retained For Inspection, Not Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The navy on Friday said five Japanese
fishing boats held by Chilean authorities were ``detained for safety
inspection'' and not seized in retaliation for a ban on Chilean
fruit imports.
   ``No foreign boats, including those from Japan, are currently
seized in Chile or prevented from operating normally,'' the Foreign
Ministry said in a communique.
   But in Talcahuano, a Japanese trawler was ``detained on orders
from the from the commander-in-chief's office,'' according to a
naval officer who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The discovery during the weekend of two grapes tainted with
cyanide in Philadelphia's port kicked off a public health scare.
   Japan imposed a ban on fruit imports from this South American
nation.
   The United States issued a four-day consumer alert but announced
Friday that it would lift a warning against Chilean produce.
   The Chilean Foreign Ministry statement was an apparent move away
from statements Thursday by navy commander Adm. Jose Merino that the
ships were ``seized'' until Japan lifted its ban.
   ``The boats are retained and being subject to a mandatory
thorough inspection,`` navy Lt. Jose Araya said in a telephone
interview. ``This is necessary for the safety of all people on board
those vessels. Once inspectors are satisfied with the safety
standards of the boats, they will let them sail off.''
   President Bush told reporters on Friday that Chilean produce
would be subject to increased inspection but would be allowed back
on U.S. markets.
   The decision was announced despite a third poisoning threat
received by the U.S. Embassy in Chile. Earlier calls to the U.S. and
Japanese embassies in Santiago prompted U.S. officials to conduct
the spot checks.
   At the White House, Chile's foreign minister, Felipe Hernan
Errazuriz, called the decision ``a workable solution.''
   ``It takes into account the interest of the U.S. citizens and the
Chileans, the consumers and the workers from Chile and everyone,''
Errazuriz said.
   The foreign minister Thursday had said at least 200,000 fruit
industry workers would be left ``without jobs and almost destitute''
if the U.S. government maintained the consumer warnings.
   Fruit accounts for 10 percent of all Chilean exports, and 65
percent of the nation's produce is sent to the United States, the
government said.
</TEXT>
