<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina-Attack     03-17 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Attack,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armed Group Fires at Army Sentinels and Flees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed group of five to eight
people attacked a guard post at an army artillery unit on the
outskirts of the capital and fled when sentinels returned their
fire, the army said Friday.
   The incident occurred shortly before midnight Thursday at the Air
Defense Artillery Group 101 in Ciudadela, 12 miles west of the
capital, the office of the chief of staff said in a brief communique.
   No one was killed or injured, and the attack, which ended when
the attackers fled in two or three vehicles, is under investigation,
the communique said.
   The incident was one of several that have occurred since the Jan.
23 attack by civilian commandos on La Tablada infantry base west of
the city. The government said the attackers were leftist extremists
and that 28 commandos and 11 troops were killed.
   Federal Judge Gerardo Larrambebere, who is investigating the La
Tablada attack, said there were no indications that the Thursday
night incident was related. ``Nevertheless, it is a hypothesis that
can't be discarded,'' he added.
   Twenty people who were arrested at La Tablada or shortly after
face charges of homicide and assault and are being held in
preventive detention pending trial.
   Gen. Francisco Gassino, the army chief of staff, told about 100
retired generals on Wednesday that there have been about 100 acts of
hostility against the armed forces since Jan. 23, the private news
agency Noticias Argentinas and the newspaper Clarin reported.
   Gassino ``even revealed that shots were fired against his
residence in Campo de Mayo (army base) when he was taking a few days
off last February,'' Clarin reported.
</TEXT>
