<FIRST>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0601 03-17 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Chief Rebuffs Calls For Multiparty Democracy, Privatization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `However, many...' with 4 grafs to include appointment
of `non-Communist' vice-ministers; picks up 8th pvs `Several delegates'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang
issued his strongest rebuff yet to increasingly vocal advocates of
multiparty democracy and vowed in a speech published Friday that the
party will never be supplanted.
   The speech was published on the eve of an annual legislative
session expected to witness open calls by some delegates for
democracy and an amnesty for political prisoners.
   But Zhao said China does not need opposition parties and upheaval
will not be tolerated.
   ``At present no one is satisfied with our backward condition but
in my view we don't need a new prescription,'' he told a party
seminar. ``The leadership of the Communist Party is in the interests
of the entire nation. China cannot adopt the Western multiparty
system.''
   The text of Zhao's speech, said to have been delivered in
January, filled the top half of national newspapers' front pages and
nearly a full page inside. No explanation was given for the delay in
its publication.
   It was the strongest of several recent warnings by Zhao and other
senior officials on the need for political stability as they work to
resolve thorny economic problems, including 36 percent annual
inflation.
   However, many intellectuals say China cannot solve its economic
problems and develop a market-style economy unless it relaxes
political controls.
   Xinhua, the official news agency, said Friday the government
appointed two members of ``democratic'' parties to vice-ministerial
posts.
   China has eight such parties, all operating under orders from the
Communist Party. Most of their 170,000 members _ compared to 44
million Communists _ are aging intellectuals or former capitalists.
   Those appointed were Li Peiyao of the Revolutionary Committee of
the Chinese Kuomintang in the Labor Ministry and Hong Fuzeng of the
September 3rd Society at the Agriculture Ministry.
   Several delegates to the 2,796-member National People's Congress,
China's legislature, said they will issue a call at the annual
session that begins Monday for an amnesty for prisoners of
conscience.
   More than 100 intellectuals already have signed letters to the
congress calling for such an amnesty, especially for Wei Jingsheng.
Wei was sentenced in 1979 to 15 years in prison for
``counterrevolutionary activities.''
   But a judge, Tang Zhanyun, quashed any hopes for such an amnesty
on Friday. The official Xinhua News Agency quoted Tang as saying
Wei's sentence was just. The agency also quoted Tang as denying
China has political or ideological prisoners.
   Zhao did not mention Wei or the petitions, but his speech
indicated authorities have no intention of letting the congress
become a platform for critics of the regime.
   ``Those who dislike our party ... know there is no way from the
outside to destroy or supplant us,'' he said.
   The party, he said, is the key to resolving every national
problem, and economic development cannot succeed without its
leadership.
   But he cautioned that corruption within the party has become a
major problem and repeatedly called for tougher discipline against
corrupt party members.
   He also acknowledged conflicts within the party, saying some
members do not understand the necessity of current efforts to reduce
central economic planning in favor of market-style reforms. Others,
he said, want to move too fast.
   In his speech, Zhao called for step-by-step change and emphasized
that China will never reject socialism for capitalism. Although some
private ownership is permitted, public ownership must remain
dominant, he said.
   ``Some people ... compare China with developed nations and think
socialism is no good,'' Zhao said. But he rejected such comparisons,
saying China was starting from a lower level of development.
   ``If you compare China with foreign capitalist countries at the
same level of development. ... There is none that doesn't have gaps
between rich and poor, social unrest and political upheaval,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
