<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-17 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow In Upper Midwest, Record Warmth In East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold air surging into the north-central part of the nation
produced heavy snow Friday over parts of the upper Midwest, while
sections of the East had unseasonably warm weather.
   Snow fell from the northern High Plains through the middle
Missouri Valley to Michigan during the afternoon, with heavy snow
across parts of South Dakota and Wisconsin.
   Snowfall totals in Minnesota ranged up to 7.5 inches at
Farmington by mid morning and up to a foot of snow was expected to
blanket central Wisconsin by Saturday morning.
   The snow was expected to spread across the upper Great Lakes
region into northern New England, and a winter storm watch was
posted for Saturday for northern Vermont and northeastern New York
state.
   South of the snow belt, a mixture of snow, sleet and freezing
rain extended across northern Iowa, southern Wisconsin and northern
Illinois, and showers and thunderstorms spread over parts of central
Illinois.
   Strong, gusty wind blew across the central Rockies and the
central high Plains during the morning, with gusts to 85 mph
reported in the Loveland ski area of Colorado and gusts to 58 mph in
Nebraska at Scottsbluff and Sydney.
   A low pressure system off the northern Pacific Coast produced
light showers over western Oregon and northern California, with snow
at higher elevations of western Oregon.
   Elsewhere, southern Florida had light showers.
   A cold front curving through the central and eastern part of the
nation created a sharp contrast in temperatures.
   Afternoon temperatures were generally below freezing from the
northern Rockies through the northern and central Plains to northern
New England. And readings were only in the teens and single digits
from Montana through the Dakotas to Upper Michigan and northern
Lower Michigan.
   Ahead of the front, temperatures were generally in the 70s and
80s across the south-central and southeastern states.
   Boston tied its record of 66 degrees, and in West Virginia,
Beckley warmed to a record 73 and Huntington hit a record 76.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., Warroad, Minn., and Watertown, S.D., to
88 at McAllen, Texas. Friday's low for the Lower 48 states was 24
degrees below zero at Hibbing, Minn.
   For Saturday, rain was forecast from the upper Ohio Valley and
the lower Great Lakes region across the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast states, with snow and freezing rain in northern New England.
Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast over the lower
Mississippi Valley and the central Gulf Coast states. Snow was
forecast over the northern Rockies and the northern high Plains, and
scattered showers were forecast across the northern and central
Pacific Coast region.
   Highs in the 20s and lower 30s were predicted from Montana
through Minnesota to Upper Michigan, and across northern Maine; in
the 40s from the central Rockies through the middle and upper
Mississippi Valley to northern New England; above 70 from southern
California through southern and central Texas to the southern and
middle Atlantic Coast region; and in the 80s in the desert Southwest
and from south-central Texas to Florida and southern Georgia.
</TEXT>
