<FIRST>r w AM-FlagDesecration     03-17 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Desecration,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Ban Displaying Flag on the Floor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, reacting to a controversial Chicago
art exhibit, approved on a 97-0 vote Thursday a bill expanding
federal law against desecration of the flag to include placing it on
the floor or on the ground.
   ``I don't know much about art, but I know desecration when I see
it,'' Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., the measure's
sponsor, said in a statement.
   The move came in response to an exhibit by a student at the
School of the Art Institute of Chicago in which an American flag was
displayed on the floor in a fashion that resulted in spectators
standing on it.
   ``What Is The Proper Way To Display The U.S. Flag,'' is the name
of the exhibit, which for the last four weeks has brought throngs of
angry demonstrators to march in front of the museum on Michigan
Avenue in the heart of downtown Chicago.
   Dole's bill would expand existing law against flag desecration to
include the words ``knowingly displayed ... on the floor or ground.''
   Dole said the Chicago display ``is not an appropriate use of this
nation's symbol of freedom _ our flag.''
   ``Quite frankly, it shows direspect and contempt for our flag,
and should be expressly prohibited by law,'' he said.
   The controversy followed last year's furor over an Art Institute
student's painting of the late Mayor Harold Washington wearing
women's garments.
   Emotions ran so high at that time that one alderman stormed into
the museum and ripped down the portrait of Washington, much beloved
among black Chicagoans and members of the city's independent
political movement.
   The flag exhibit by 24-year-old art student Scott Tyler was to be
taken down on Thursday after being on display for four weeks.
   It already has drawn censure from the Illinois state House of
Representatives. But a judge quickly threw out a lawsuit aimed at
having the exhibit removed from public display.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
