<FIRST>u a AM-SafeApples     03-17 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Safe Apples,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Health Chief Okays Apples As Safe, Knocks Scare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's public health chief assured
apple-lovers Friday that tests indicated the fruit is safe to eat,
and the state's schools were told to return apples to lunch rooms.
   ``An apple a day ...'' is excellent diet policy, state health
director Dr. Kenneth W. Kizer suggested at a news conference.
   ``The message to mom and dad out there is that these are safe,
you can eat `em; there's no problem,'' Kizer said.
   At the center of the controversy is the chemical daminozide, sold
under the trade name Alar, which the EPA said has caused cancer in
test animals. Last month an environmental group issued a report
suggesting that children are especially at risk from Alar because
they eat many times more apples and apple products, compared to
their weight, than adults.
   Alar has been used as a spray on some apples to increase
firmness, enhance color and extend storage life.
   Kizer said tests of canned apple juice, apple slices and apple
sauce taken from Department of Education warehouses failed to show
residues of Alar or related compounds greater than 0.055 parts per
million.
   The residues are ``approximately 400 times below the legally
allowed tolerance for daminozide in apple and apple products,'' he
said.
   On Thursday, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, Food and Drug
Administration and Environmental Protection Agency pronounced apple
and apple products safe to eat.
   ``There's no foundation or basis for the scare,'' Kizer said.
``It got going, and whatever it was got it going it steamrolled.''
   Kizer declined to place blame, but estimated the scare would
probably cost state agencies ``a few hundred thousand dollars'' for
the tests and other expenses.
   Kizer said he had advised state schools Superintendent Bill Honig
``that there is no real threat to the health of children from the
consumption of the apple products we tested.
   ``I have urged that fresh and canned apples and other fruits and
vegetables be served as a regular part of the diet of all California
school children, and I urge parents who have withdrawn those
products from their childrens' diets to begin serving them again.''
   Kizer said the state tests were conducted at the state's food and
drug laboratories in Emeryville, and results were confirmed at the
University of California at Davis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
