<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-AIDS     03-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-AIDS,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Infections From Hospital's Unsterilized Syringe Rises to 49</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of mothers and children known to be
infected with the fatal AIDS virus by nurses using an unsterilized
syringe at a provincial hospital has risen to 49, Soviet health
officials said Friday.
   Officials expect to find several more victims as the
investigation continues, said Valentin Pokrovsky, president of the
Academy of Sciences.
   Speaking at a news briefing on an international conference in
Moscow on acquired immune deficiency syndrome, Pokrovsky said 21 of
the 49 already identified are children.
   He blamed the tragedy in Elista, a city near the Caspian Sea, on
health workers who used the same syringe to inject drugs into the
intravenous feeding catheters of numerous patients.
   The AIDS virus damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often
through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers,
infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their
offspring.
   The Soviet Union suffers extreme shortages of numerous products,
including syringes. The country produced just 30 million disposable
syringes last year, while health workers dispensed 3 billion
injections, said Deputy Health Minister Alexander Kondrusev.
   Nurses are supposed to sterilize their reusable syringes between
patients, but this apparently was not done in Elista, he said. Nor
do disposable syringes solve the problem, because they too are often
used repeatedly, he said.
   ``We still have cases of health workers using syringes not
properly boiled, or simply changing needles,'' he said. ``There
should be a system of responsibility'' to prevent such dangerous
behavior, he continued.
   A government newspaper recently commented on a shortage of
condoms, which doctors say are an effective way to stem the spread
of AIDS.
   The Elista case began when a Soviet man contracted AIDS in
Africa,then came home and transmitted it to his wife. She or her
child apparently was a patient in the maternity hospital last June
when the infections began.
   Pokrovsky said it is possible some of the mothers contracted the
fatal, slow-acting virus from their nursing infants. Scientists
found that all of the children in this group _ who were already
seriously ill and confined to an intensive care ward _ had mouth
infections. They believe infected blood from the babies' mouths
entered the mothers through their nipples to the lymph glands, but
this is not yet proven, Prokrovsky said.
   So far, authorities have identified only eight people who have
developed AIDS symptoms in the Soviet Union, Kondrusev and Pokrovsky
said. Three African victims have died, as have three Soviets. Two
other Soviets are being treated.
   Kondrusev said the Soviet Union has found 554 carriers of the
infectious virus, including 378 foreigners and 176 Soviets. All of
the foreigners have been deported or are in the process of leaving,
he said.
   All of the Soviet infections came from sexual activity, except
for the Elista cases, said Kondrusev. The Soviet Union has not yet
had an AIDS case caused by drug abusers sharing needles, he said.
   Worldwide, 142,000 people have developed the deadly disease, and
an estimated 5 to 10 million are infected, according to World Health
Organization statistics offered at the briefing.
   Pokrovsky said a few Soviets are panicking about AIDS but he is
more concerned that most citizens are utterly indifferent to the
danger. ``We need to explain that their safety depends on their
individual actions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0154 </DOCNO>
