<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Clash With Guerrillas, Two Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs to UPDATE with detail, background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers clashed with guerrillas who
apparently infiltrated into Israel from Jordan on Friday, and at
least two soldiers were wounded, the army said.
   But knowledgeable Israeli sources said one soldier was killed and
another wounded in the 10 p.m. attack. They said on condition of
anonymity that the guerrillas apparently crossed the border back
into Jordan.
   An army spokesman said an initial report showed the guerrillas
crossed into Israel near the southern border communal farm of Ein
Yahav, 74 miles south of Jerusalem.
   Two Israeli soldiers were wounded in the ensuing firefight, the
spokesman said. He said no details were available.
   One soldier who was shot and slightly wounded in the arm was
treated at the Soroka Hospital in the southern town of Beersheva,
hospital spokeswoman Tami Lunenfeld said.
   On Wednesday, two Palestinian guerrillas slipped across border in
the occupied Gaza Strip town of Rafah and hurled a grenade at an
army outpost. The guerrillas were captured by Israeli troops. There
were no Israeli casualties.
   On Friday, one of the guerrillas, 18-year-old Iman Mohammed
Hassan Yunis from the Canada refugee camp on the Egyptian side of
Rafah, said he has been operating on orders from Yasser Arafat's
Fatah wing of the PLO.
   Wednesday's raid was the first attempted infiltration attributed
to Fatah since Arafat in December renounced terrorism and recognized
Israel's right to exist. After Arafat's statements, the United
States launched a dialogue with the PLO.
   U.S. officials reportedly have sought to work out a cease-fire
between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization to stop
infiltrations from Lebanon. The PLO claims these are attacks on
military targets that are not included in Arafat's renunciation of
terrorism.
   Army officials say at least 30 guerrillas have been killed in
southern Lebanon this year while attempting to cross into Israel.
Five were killed in two attempts this week.
   The last infiltration from Jordan was on May 17, 1988. One Arab
guerrilla was wounded and captured, and two escaped during that raid.
</TEXT>
