<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NewspageMarkets 1stLd-Writethru a0712 03-17 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0712,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds Plunge Following News Of Higher Inflation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with final closing market and bond
prices, biggest drop since last April. A version moving on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock and bond prices plunged Friday after the
government reported another surge in wholesale prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell about 50
points in the opening minutes of trading, then stabilized and
finished 48.57 points lower at 2,292.14. It was the biggest drop
since a 101.46-point plunge last April 14.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which are highly sensitive
to inflation speculation, were down more than $17 for every $1,000
in face value by late in the trading day.
   Lower bond prices mean higher interest rates. The yield on the
Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond leaped to about 9.3 percent from
about 9.1 percent late Thursday.
   The Labor Department said Friday that wholesale prices, pushed up
by surging energy and food costs, soared 1.0 percent in February
after an identical rise in January.
   The back-to-back increases mean inflation at the wholesale level
one stop short of retail is running at a 12.6 percent annual rate so
far in 1989. That is more than triple the 4.0 percent increase for
all of last year.
   Both large jumps have surprised analysts, who in advance of both
reports had predicted moderate rises of about 0.4 percent. After
January's numbers were reported, economists dismissed them as an
aberration and said inflation would return to the 4 percent to 5
percent annual pace of late last year.
   The stock market lost ground late in the session after
International Business Machines Corp. said a short-term chip problem
had caused delays in deliveries of mainframe computers and that it
expects first-quarter earnings to be below the range of security
analysts' estimates.
   The intensity of activity in the stock market was heightened by
the so-called ``triple witching hour,'' a quarterly occasion when
the last trading occurs in a set of expiring options and futures on
stock indexes.
   This situation often prompts heavy trading by professionals
engaged in computer program strategies that involve both the options
and futures and individual stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
