<FIRST>u w AM-Fruit-Cyanide 1stld-writethru a0720 03-17 1024</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit-Cyanide, 1st ld-writethru, a0720,1060</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 6 grafs at end with Chilean action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration announced a stepped-up
inspection plan for imported fruit on Friday, clearing the way for
new shipments of Chilean produce to U.S. supermarkets after a
week-long health scare sparked by cyanide-tainted grapes.
   Under the plan, Chilean fruit already held by importers,
wholesalers and retailers in the United States is to be destroyed
``to eliminate fruit that cannot be practically inspected,'' said
Frank Young, commissioner of the Food and Drug Administration.
   Under the new inspection safeguards, ``we believe that this
program will provide the maximum feasible safety for fruit from
Chile,'' Young said at a news conference.
   He said that while not every piece of fruit will be inspected,
the plan is ``based on the assumptions of the type of sampling that
would be required to have a high confidence of detecting anything if
something is there.''
   ``It is impossible to assure 100 percent safety,'' he said.
   Chilean grapes, which make up the bulk of grapes on sale this
time of year, and other fruit could be back on the shelves of U.S.
stores in less than a week, officials said.
   The plan was announced despite a new poisoning threat received by
the U.S. Embassy in Santiago, Young said. He said the third threat
raises no more concern than two earlier ones, which preceded
discovery of the tainted grapes, though officials believe the caller
may be the same.
   As the government inspection plan was being announced,
longshoremen in Florida began unloading boxes of Chilean fruit from
a ship that has been anchored off Tampa for the past few days.
   Responsibility to see that fruit already in the United States is
dumped lies with state health departments, Young said.
   About 5 percent of Chilean fruit at U.S. docks or in transit to
the United States will be visually inspected and all
suspicious-looking fruit will be subjected to laboratory tests
before it is released.
   In addition, Chile will begin increased security surveillance of
fruit still in that country awaiting export, Young said. A team of
FDA inspectors will fly to the South American country soon to
oversee that effort.
   ``As always, we believe consumers should inspect all products,
regardless of country of origin,'' Young said. ``In this particular
case, consumers should look especially for injection marks, any
unusual appearance or discoloration or chemical or `burned almond'
smell.''
   Neither FDA nor representatives of Chilean exporters could give
figures on the value of the fruit to be destroyed.
   Young said grapes _ which constitute about 70 percent of Chile's
sales in the United States _ raspberries, blueberries, blackberries
and strawberries will be the first fruits to be released because
cyanide contamination of those fruits is the easiest to spot since
the fruit discolors and becomes mushy.
   These Chilean fruits will be on store shelves within five to nine
days, Young said, but he had no estimate of time for return of the
other Chilean fruit exports, including melons, cantaloupes, pears,
apples, nectarines, plums and peaches. Once fruit has been
inspected, crates will be labeled as such so wholesalers and
retailers can be assured of its safety, he said.
   He said that since the small amounts of cyanide were found in two
seedless red grapes over the weekend, no additional evidence of
contamination has been uncovered. He said 13,000 crates of fruit
have been inspected since the two poisoned grapes were found.
   Minutes before Young announced details of the plan, President
Bush said the FDA's action in taking Chilean fruit off the market
``has cost some economic hardship that I regret.''
   However, he added, ``I think when the health of the American
people might be threatened you've got to take prudent action.''
   Discovery of the poisoned grapes touched off a major public
health scare in this country and economic difficulties of a
different sort in Chile, where fruit is a major export and where
thousands of agricultural workers have been threatened with the loss
of their jobs during the peak harvest season.
   Chilean Foreign Minister Hernan Felipe Errazuriz called the U.S.
decision ``a workable solution'' and said ``we are very grateful.''
   ``It takes into account the interest of the U.S. citizens and the
Chileans, the consumers and the workers from Chile,'' he said at the
White House, where he met with Vice President Dan Quayle.
   Young said questions about who would bear the cost of the lost
fruit and the inspections are not his to consider. ``The day I start
to look at health with regard to somebody's left hip pocket or
pocketbook, then I am not focusing enough in regard to safety,'' he
said.
   Some economic impact will be felt by American consumers, who are
likely to soon see, at least temporarily, higher prices for fruit on
supermarket shelves, said economist Donald Ratajczak of Georgia
State University.
   ``Most of what will be left on the shelves will be hothouse grown
(domestically) and that will be more expensive,'' he said.
   In Santiago, after hearing that the U.S. government had lifted
the restrictions, the military government announced a package of
economic measures to counter the damage caused by the crisis of the
nation's booming fruit export industry.
   President Augusto Pinochet said he signed a bill authorizing the
government to make emergency loans to affected fruit growers and
exporters. Also, he said, the government will buy part of the
production the exporters were not able to sell abroad.
   Interior Minister Carlos Caceres said the government will also
aid exporters to finance a mass advertising campaign abroad aimed at
recovering the consumers' confidence, especially in the United
States.
   Effective immediately, Caceres said, the government will
implement a $12 million emergency job program in the fruit-growing
regions to hire workers who lost their jobs as a result of the
temporary paralization of the fruit industry.
   In addition, tue government will encourage banks to re-negotiate
credits with fruit businessmen.
   In the foreign front, Caceres added, the government will seek new
credits from the World Bank and will re-negotiate standing
agreements with the International monetary funds. He did not
elaborate.
</TEXT>
