<FIRST>r a AM-ConcernedScientists     03-17 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Concerned Scientists,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concerned Scientists Celebrate 20 Years Of Activism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years ago, students and teachers
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology started a movement
against what they considered a dangerous trend of focusing
technology on military expansion.
   What started out as an MIT teach-in and became known as the Union
of Concerned Scientists has grown two decades later into an
influential national organization promoting social and environmental
uses of technology and nuclear arms reduction.
   The organization claims 100,000 contributing members and a
30-member staff in Cambridge and Washington engaged in research,
lobbying and litigation.
   On Wednesday night, about 200 people celebrated the group's
anniversary at the Boston Museum of Science. At the reception, the
UCS previewed a video on the group's policy on avoiding perilous
global warming known as the greenhouse effect.
   Among those present was Henry W. Kendall, an MIT physics
professor and Defense Department consultant who has been chairman of
the union's board since 1973.
   Kendall's involvement traces to the group's inception as the
March Fourth Movement. On the MIT campus on March 4, 1969, the
university's regular activities were disrupted for weeklong
discussions on the Vietnam War, which those participating thought
was unwinnable.
   At the time, MIT was designing components for nuclear weaponry,
which many students and faculty opposed. Kendall and other
instructors released a faculty statement outlining their goals as:
   _ A ``continuing examination of governmental policy in areas
where science and technology are of actual or potential
significance.''
   _ To direct the ``emphasis on military technology'' towards
environmental and social problems.
   _ To encourage students to focus their scientific and
technological energies on serving mankind, and to ``scrutinize the
issues ... before participating in the construction of destructive
weapons systems.''
   Howard Ris, the union's executive director since 1984, said the
group is celebrating the end of the Reagan era. The union opposed
President Reagan on many issues, such as his Strategic Defense
Initiative and his relaxation of regulations restricting auto
emissions.
   Nevertheless, Kendall says the group has worked with liberals and
conservatives alike to pursue its goals.
   ``We've been against a number of technically unsatisfactory
weapons systems, like Star Wars, that were ill-chosen and unwise,''
Kendall said. ``Our views have now become the standard reaction.''
   Perceptions of the group in Washington, D.C., vary.
   A public relations worker for the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank, when asked about the Union of Concerned
Scientists, said, ``They're a peace group, right?''
   But Michael Mariotte, the director of the Nuclear Information and
Resource Service, said: ``We've got a lot of respect for them. They
have the expertise we and a lot of other people rely on.''
   ``Of course, we don't agree on every single thing,'' Mariotte
said. As an example, Mariotte pointed to the union's support of
further development of advanced nuclear reactors, which his
organization is against.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
