<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Cambodia     03-17 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cambodia,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prince Says US Supports Resistance But Does Not Promise Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Prince Norodom Rinariddh, whose father leads the
Cambodian resistance, said Friday the United States had expressed
``strong and clear'' support but gave no commitment to provide arms.
   He told reporters after several days of talks in Washington the
question of military assistance is being debated, but ``we haven't
gotten any aid from the United States.''
   Rinariddh is the military commander of guerrillas led by his
father Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former ruler of Cambodia.
   The three-party resistance coalition also includes a
non-communist group led by former Premier Son Sann and the communist
Khmer Rouge, who gained control of Cambodia in 1975 and conducted a
reign of terror in which at least 1 million people died before the
Vietnamese invasion of December 1978.
   After the news conference, Rinariddh met with Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar about the Cambodian situation, possible U.N.
supervision of a Vietnamese withdrawal and a proposed U.N.-sponsored
peace conference. There was no immediate report on their discussions.
   The prince said the non-communist resistance groups wanted U.S.
military aid to give them greater strength relative to the Khmer
Rouge, the main fighting force, and enable them to compete more
effectively in a future settlement.
   He told the journalists, however: ``To be very frank, I do not
have a clear and positive response to my requirement to have lethal
aid to the non-communists.''
   He said there were indications of support and ``the reaction
appeared to me to be very positive,'' but ``I can't say I'm 100
percent sure the U.S. will provide lethal assistance.''
   Bush administration sources have said privately they discussed
the possibility of increasing assistance to the non-communist
factions, projected to be $7.5 million in non-lethal aid for fiscal
1990.
   They added, however, that the administration opposes providing
military aid. China and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
are the major providers of arms and the administration is satisfied
with the status quo, the sources said.
</TEXT>
