<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Reforms     03-17 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Reforms,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Anounces Reforms; Urges U.S. To Support Regional Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega announced
electoral and other reforms on Friday and said the measures point to
his leftist Sandinista government's commitment to bring peace to
Central America.
   Hours earlier, the Sandinistas freed 1,894 former national
guardsmen from prison.
   Ortega appealed to the U.S. Congress not to renew humanitarian
aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, beyond 90 days
because it would go against the desire of the region's presidents to
dismantle the U.S.-backed force.
   ``We appeal to the government of the United States, President
George Bush and the U.S. Congress so that what is being discussed
today in Congress regarding renewed aid to the Contras will be
contemplated within the framework of the joint declaration of the
Central American presidents,'' Ortega said in a speech before
opposition party leaders and the archbishop of Managua, Cardinal
Miguel Obando y Bravo.
   Ortega was refering to an accord he and the presidents of El
Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa Rica signed on Feb. 14 in El
Salvador. The five agreed to draft a plan by mid-May to dismantle
the Contras, most of whom are in jungle camps in Honduras near the
Nicaraguan border.
   In the pact, Ortega promised legal reforms to guarantee fair
general elections, which he moved up by 10 months, to Feb. 25, 1990.
   Government sources in Washington and Contra leaders have said the
Bush administration will ask Congress for up to $50 million in new,
non-lethal aid for the Contras. The current package of $27 million
expires March 31.
   Ortega said talks he has been holding with his political foes
have been ``positive ... frank and constructive'' but that the El
Salvador accord did not oblige his government to hold negotiations
with the opposition.
   ``Rather, the Nicaraguan government assumes the responsibility of
enacting certain reforms,'' Ortega said.
   He announced 20 reforms he said his government will send to the
National Assembly within the next few days, including:
   _Allowing exiled Nicaraguans to vote from abroad. Thousands of
Nicaraguans have fled eight years of civil war and a dismal economy.
   _Forbidding use of state resources or employees in the campaign;
   _Changing laws on financing political parties;
   _Reducing the number of regional polling and vote-counting
stations;
   _Making the Supreme Electoral Council more representative of
opposition parties.
   Passage is virtually assured. The Sandinistas dominate the
96-member National Assembly, with 61 deputies to the opposition's 35.
   Hundreds of former members of ousted President Anastasio Somoza's
national guard were released earlier Friday at La Modelo prison in
Tipitapa village just outside Managua.
   Most were jailed in the months following the July 19, 1979, rise
to power of the Sandinistas, who defeated Somoza in a popular
uprising.
</TEXT>
