<FIRST>u a AM-EasternRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0713 03-17 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Pan Am Union Officials Plan to Meet to Discuss Employee
Buyout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Eastern putting aircraft up
for sale; picks up 2nd graf pvs: `William F...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines has notified aircraft brokers it
wants to sell part of its 250-plane fleet as its owners and
Machinists union hint that talks are under way to sell the carrier,
now reorganizing in bankruptcy court.
   ``We're exploring the market,'' Eastern spokesman Robin Matell
told The Associated Press on Friday. He added that he did not know
the total number of aircraft for sale, but that it was ``nowhere
near most of the fleet.''
   The notice to aircraft brokers worldwide was issued either
Thursday or Friday and included listings of DC-9s, Boeing 727s and
757s, Matell said. He said that the airline made similar notices
``hundreds'' of times in the past.
   ``Given the current situation it obviously draws much greater
attention and people wonder just what it means,'' Matell said,
noting that the company had made it clear since the Machinists
struck the carrier nearly two weeks ago that assets would be sold to
finance Eastern's rebuilding.
   ``There is nothing unusual'' about the company's latest attempt
to sell aircraft, Matell insisted.
   Eastern's pilots, who joined with flight attendants in sympathy
strikes against the carrier, have maintained that Eastern's parent
company is stripping the company's assets to prop up non-union
sister Continental Airlines.
   In another development Friday, a Pan Am Corp. union official said
he would meet with the leader of Eastern's striking Machinists in
Miami to discuss a possible joint employee buyout of the two
airlines.
   William F. Genoese, director of the Teamsters union's Airline
Division, told The Associated Press that he and Machinists District
100 President Charles Bryan plan to discuss a buyout plan Saturday
to combine the airlines.
   Pan Am, like Eastern, has been racked by financial losses and
labor tensions. Pan Am Chairman Tom Plaskett recently said the
carrier probably would need to merge with another airline to ensure
its survival.
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo has indicated a renewed
interest in selling all or parts of Eastern since the airline filed
for bankruptcy protection March 9. Eastern is operating only about
10 percent of its pre-strike schedule of 1,040 daily flights.
   ``It's possible that the most sensible way for Eastern Airlines
to proceed would be for some different types of ownership in some
way,'' Lorenzo said in an interview recorded for ABC-TV's ``20-20''
show Friday night.
   But Lorenzo promised that his goal hasn't been to sell off
Eastern.
   Bryan, the union chief who for years has advocated employee
control as a leading solution for Eastern's problems, confirmed he
would meet with Genoese but declined to say whether they would
explore an Eastern-Pan Am combination.
   ``We're going to be discussing a whole range of subjects,'' the
Machinists leader said, adding, ``I never make any statements about
any possible sales or transactions.''
   Financial analysts say the leading potential buyer for Eastern
remains financier Carl Icahn, the owner and chairman of Trans World
Airlines Inc. Bryan has talked to Icahn several times in the past
year about buying Eastern.
   Meanwhile, attorneys for Eastern pilots on Friday promised to
protest to a bankruptcy judge about the apparent transfer of Eastern
landing slots to sister carrier Continental on the eve of the
bankruptcy filing.
   Other documents obtained by the attorneys indicated Eastern also
gained federal approval for transfer of other slots to rivals Pan Am
and United Airlines just before the strike began two weeks ago.
   ``We think these transactions just strengthen the employees'
position that a trustee should be appointed (by the bankruptcy
court) to oust the present management, which has been doing this for
years,'' said James Linsey, a New York attorney for the Air Line
Pilots Association.
   The unions contend that Lorenzo has systematically sold off
Eastern assets or transferred them to predominantly nonunion
Continental at cut-rate prices.
   The pilots' attorneys say they believe the transfers of eight
landing slots at New York's La Guardia Airport and eight at
Washington's National Airport to Continental are permanent, although
Continental spokesman Art Kent said they were 60-day leases. No
details were made public on the amount of money involved.
   Continental has been advertising new flights between Miami and La
Guardia and Washington on Miami radio stations.
   Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said the deals for the slot
transfers, which are effective in April, were made last October.
   ``These two things just don't relate to the strike or bankruptcy.
They were made before we knew that was going to happen,'' Ashlock
said.
   Ashlock said the transfers of six Pan Am slots at New York's
Kennedy Airport are temporary and only for summer, which is Pan Am's
peak travel season. The transfers of six Chicago slots to United are
permanent. He didn't have details on the amounts of money involved.
   Bryan indicated union attorneys will challenge all recent assets
transfers and sales before the bankruptcy court, including deals
made before the strike and bankruptcy filing.
   The strike began March 4 with a walkout by 8,500 Machinists
mechanics and ground service workers in a dispute over $125 million
in proposed wage cuts. The strike quickly escalated with the support
of pilots and flight attendants. Five days later, Eastern filed for
bankruptcy reorganization.
</TEXT>
