<HEAD>Catholic Killed At Home, Bomb Explodes, IRA Claims Other Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with police identifying victim,
one of his daughters also home during shooting. Pickup 4th graf `Earlier
Friday...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a 42-year-old
Roman Catholic man in front of his wife Friday night, police said,
in the latest in an apparent series of retaliatory sectarian
killings.
   Police said the killers smashed their way into the man's home in
Glengormley, on the outskirts of Belfast, and shot him.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the Friday night
murder of the Catholic man police identified as 42-year-old civil
servant Niall Davies, the father of two daughters.
   Davies' his 11-year-old daughter was in the house at the time of
the shooting. His other daughter, age 18, was at St. Patrick's Day
celebrations when she heard of her father's death, police said.
   Earlier Friday a bomb exploded near a joint army and police foot
patrol in mainly Catholic west Belfast but no one was injured, the
Royal Ulster Constabulary said. The patrol had been moving into
position to guard the St. Patrick's Day parade in the Falls Road.
   On Thursday, the outlawed, mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican
Army killed Jackie Irvine, 50, the Protestant owner of a Belfast
grocery store, and warned of more shootings to come.
   The IRA's Belfast Brigade claimed on Friday that Irvine belonged
to an outlawed Protestant paramilitary group and that there were
clear indications he was involved in recent murders of Catholics. It
did not identify the group.
   A Belfast police statement said Irvine was shot as he ran out the
front door of his home in north Belfast when at least two gunmen
tried to break in from the rear.
   Neighbors said they heard as many as eight shots and then saw a
car race from the scene.
   Press Association said Irvine was a former member of the
so-called brigade staff of the Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed
Protestant paramilitary group.
   It said the group was allegedly involved in shootings of members
of Sinn Fein, the legal political arm of the IRA, and others.
   Northern Ireland suffers periodic retaliatory sectarian attacks
on victims from either side of the Protestant-Catholic divide.
   The latest round began Feb. 12 when gunmen stormed the home of
Catholic lawyer PatrickFinucane in north Belfast and killed him.
Finucane had acted for clients allegedly involved in the IRA's fight
against British rule in Northern Ireland.
   An outlawed Protestant paramilitary group, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters, claimed responsibility, saying he was an IRA officer. His
widow denied it.
   The IRA wants to unite predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland
with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist
rule.
   On Feb. 14, gunmen killed Sinn Fein councilman John Davey as he
drove to his home in Glenduff village, 30 miles northwest of
Belfast. No group claimed responsibility.
   On Feb. 16, gunmen burst into a Protestant bar in Belfast and
wounded five people. The Irish National Liberation Army, a Marxist
offshoot of the IRA, claimed responsibility.
   On March 8, IRA gunmen killed three Protestants outside a gas
station.
   On March 10, gunmen killed one man leaving a Catholic bar in west
Belfast and wounded another.
</TEXT>
