<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-17 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0893</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. industrial operating rate eased last
month for the first time since September, the government said in a
report welcomed by those worried that strains on the economy are
pushing up prices.
   U.S. factories, mines and utilities operated at 84.3 percent of
capacity in February, down 0.2 percentage point from January, when
the 84.5 percent rate was the highest in nearly a decade, the
Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   At the same time, the pace of industrial production held steady
in February after 12 months of steady advances, the central bank
said in a second report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction plummeted 11.4 percent in
February, the government reported, with analysts blaming the sharp
decline on harsher weather last month and the bite of higher
mortgage interest rates.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that new homes and
apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5
million units last month as the weather turned cold again after an
unseasonably mild January.
   February's pace was down from a rate of 1.69 million units in
January, the highest level in nearly two years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators announced the takeover of
another 47 failed savings and loan institutions, while President
Bush urged Congress to act more swiftly on his rescue plan for the
industry.
   The takeovers bring the number of institutions under the control
of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. to 165 in 25 states. In the
latest action, the agency took over 16 institutions in Texas, 10 in
Illinois, nine each in Louisiana and Florida and three in Oklahoma.
Their assets totaled $6.8 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just five weeks after announcing a potential $7
billion, 150-plane purchase, American Airlines appeared to be on the
verge of a $3.09 billion deal with Dutch manufacturer Fokker for up
to 150 more planes.
   Analysts said Thursday the spending spree reflects American's
financial strength and strategy for modernizing its fleet and
expanding its routes.
   American announced Wednesday it plans to spend $95 million to
expand its corporate headquarters in Fort Worth and is expected
within the next few weeks to announce a location for a new $200
million maintenance facility.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some rivals of strike-torn Eastern Airlines have
raised fares on competitive routes since the 13-day-old walkout
began, moves they say stem from higher demand but that one consumer
group complains is price gouging.
   Some competitors said Thursday their recent fare hikes were
unrelated to the Eastern strike, which has grounded most of the
airline's flights.
   The walkout by Machinists has been supported by most of the
pilots and flight attendants at Eastern, which sought bankruptcy
protection from its creditors about a week ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-struggling Maxicare Health Plans Inc.
filed a federal bankruptcy petition but promised to keep serving the
1 million Americans covered by its plans in a dozen states.
   The company, which operates health maintenance organizations
under the names Maxicare, HealthCare USA and HealthAmerica,
announced Thursday it sought protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators may need to maintain a
permanent force of undercover agents on the floors of the nation's
futures exchanges to detect cheating, a key congressional lawmaker
said.
   ``I like to inject the worry factor in there,'' said Rep. Glenn
English, D-Okla., who chairs a House agriculture subcommittee
examining the fitness of futures-industry regulators.
   English made the comments Thursday at a news conference following
a luncheon speech at the annual meeting of the Futures Industry
Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TW Services Inc. said it will explore
alternatives to Coniston Partners' unwanted $1.4 billion takeover
bid, a move that could include the sale of the food services and
restaurant giant.
   The aggressive New York investment firm, which has been pursuing
TW since the fall with a $29-a-share tender offer, welcomed the TW
board's decision Thursday and indicated it might increase its offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission abolished
two-decades-old price regulations on American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
Co.'s long-distance services, saying consumers should reap $900
million in savings under a new pricing plan over the next four years.
   One consumer group, however, said Thursday the plan could lead to
the first increases in long-distance rates, particularly on nights
and weekends, since the 1984 breakup of AT&amp;T.
   The 3-0 commission decision will replace AT&amp;T's so-called
rate-of-return rules on July 1 with a plan that would tie
long-distance prices to productivity gains and the rate of inflation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market climbed to a six-week high Thursday, propelled
by new evidence of a slackening in economic growth. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials climbed 20.17 to 2,340.71.
   The dollar finished mixed in domestic dealings after rising in
Europe despite central bank intervention.
   Bond prices finished little changed.
   Sugar futures prices surged to their highest levels in nine
months; energy futures were mixed to marginally higher; gold and
silver futures dipped, but platinum rose; and livestock and pork
futures edged lower.
