<DOCNO> AP890317-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NationalLampoon     03-17 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Lampoon,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Animal House'' Star, Partner Take Control of National Lampoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1978 movie ``Animal House,'' actor Tim
Matheson played a college Don Juan negotiating his way through a
series of romantic liaisons.
   Now, 11 years later, Matheson has negotiated his way into a
liaison with the company that produced the hit film, National
Lampoon Inc.
   Matheson and his business partner, Daniel Grodnik, announced
Thursday they had won control of National Lampoon by buying the
stake in the entertainment and publishing company held by its
founder and chairman, Matty Simmons. The two investors paid Simmons
$6 a share, or more than $761,400.
   Simmons resigned from National Lampoon and was replaced by
Matheson and Grodnik, who will serve as co-chairmen. But Simmons,
who has formed his own production company, will produce an
unspecified number of films for National Lampoon over the next four
years, the company said.
   The acquisition of Simmons' stake gives Matheson and Grodnik
control of about 30 percent of the stock in the company, which
publishes the humor magazine National Lampoon and has also produced
films such as ``National Lampoon's Vacation.''
   In December, Matheson and Grodnik, an independent film producer,
said they might seek control of National Lampoon. In January, they
were named to the company's board.
   Matheson has appeared in a number of films and television
programs, but is best known for his role as Otter, the shallow,
fast-talking womanizer in ``Animal House,'' the raunchy comedy about
a Midwestern fraternity house. The film also starred the late John
Belushi.
   Grodnik said in a telephone interview it was coincidental that he
and Matheson _ who together produced the film ``Blind Fury'' _ ended
up pursuing the company that created ``Animal House.''
   The pair had wanted to raise funds to produce pictures, but were
advised by David Batchelder _ who formerly worked with takeover
specialist T. Boone Pickens Jr. _ to instead search for an existing
entertainment firm that was undervalued.
   Matheson and Grodnik found 23 companies that were possible
candidates, and after they narrowed the field, National Lampoon
emerged as their first choice, Grodnik said.
   ``It was just a marriage that was meant to be,'' he said.
   They approached several shareholders, who agreed to assign the
pair their voting rights. After buying their own stake, Matheson and
Grodnik said they controled more than 21 percent of the company's
stock.
   National Lampoon said it has 10 films in various stages of
development. The firm's next project, ``National Lampoon's Christmas
Vacation,'' is scheduled to go into production later this month.
   Grodnik said he and Matheson would produce films solely through
National Lampoon.
   The new co-chairmen said they were bringing in new executives to
handle the publishing end of the firm. National Lampoon magazine
suffered a readership decline in the early 1980s, but has begun to
turn around, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TW-Coniston     03-17 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TW-Coniston,0535</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Coniston Mulls Raising Bid For TW Services</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coniston Partners says it might raise its $1.4
billion bid for food services giant TW Services Inc., but the
aggressive investment firm may have little choice if it is taking
its cue from the market.
   On Thursday, TW climbed $2.62{ in active New York Stock Exchange
trading to close at $31.75 a share, a 52-week high that outpaced
Coniston's current $29-a-share tender offer.
   Trading was spurred by the announcement that TW's board was
exploring alternatives to boost shareholder value. Those options
range from selling or reorganizing the company, which owns the
Denny's restaurant chain, to repurchasing shares.
   ``No alternatives are precluded,'' said TW spokesman James Ryan.
   Coniston principal Paul E. Tierney Jr. said in a telephone
interview that the firm planned to review TW's ``information and
adjust our offer accordingly.'' Throughout his exchanges with TW
Chairman Frank Salizzoni, however, Tierney has maintained that
Coniston is offering a premium price to TW shareholders.
   In December letter to Salizzoni, Tierney wrote that Coniston did
not believe ``the market price of TW as a public company is likely
to equal the price we are prepared to pay today for years to come.''
   TW directors, who met Wednesday, reiterated their contention that
Coniston's offer is inadequate. The board authorized financial
advisers First Boston Corp. and Merrill Lynch Capital Markets to
seek ``transactions that reflect ... our strong forward momentum.''
   Coniston repeatedly has pressed TW to ``either negotiate with us
or to auction the company,'' Tierney said. ``We're pleased that
after what seems to be a very long time that they have finally
agreed to sell the business.''
   TW, parent of the 1,220-restaurant Denny's and Spartan Food
Systems Inc., the largest franchisee of Hardee's fast-food
restaurants, reported 1988 profits of $53.7 million, up 15 percent
from a year earlier.
   Coniston owns about 19 percent of TW's 48.5 million outstanding
shares. Together with shares tendered under the offer, Tierney says
over 90 percent of TW stock would be in Coniston's hands.
   In advising shareholders not to tender and to withdraw shares
that already have been tendered, Salizzoni noted that TW operations
``have performed exceedingly well and over plan, reflecting their
growing, leading market positions and improving sales and
profitability ...'' since Coniston made its first overture.
   Separately, the TW board agreed to postpone indefinitely the
company's April 26 annual meeting, where Coniston had planned to
wage a proxy fight to get its candidates elected to TW's 11-member
board. Shareholders are to elect three directors at the annual
meeting.
   Ryan said the meeting was postponed to allow the board time to
``review and entertain alternatives that may produce a higher
value,'' rather than to head off a proxy fight.
   Earlier this month Coniston amended its offer by, among other
changes, removing the condition that the TW board approve a
takeover. The change came after the Delaware Chancery Court upheld
TW's poison pill, which was designed make an unwanted takeover
prohibitively expensive.
   Coniston has said it has spent over $15 million in its effort to
acquire TW.
</TEXT>
