<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FuturesMeeting-Aurora Bjt   03-17 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Futures Meeting-Aurora, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBOT Unveils Electronic Trading System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traders are calling it ``Nintendo II,''
but whatever the name, the Chicago Board of Trade says its new
electronic futures trading system will usher in a new era of
international futures transactions.
   The Aurora system gets its first public showing today at the
Futures Industry Association's annual meeting here.
   Journalists covering the conference got a sneak preview Wednesday
night. The system resembles a video game and attempts to replicate
on a computer screen the fast-paced competition of a futures trading
pit.
   Aurora will compete with Globex, an electronic trading network
developed by the rival Chicago Mercantile Exchange and London-based
Reuters PLC.
   Like Globex, Aurora is designed for trading of futures contracts
during the hours that the exchange's trading floor is closed,
primarily to capture business overseas.
   But unlike Globex and unlike any other electronic trading system
devised over the past 20 years, Aurora can disclose what other
traders are doing in the market and allow users to select the person
with whom they wish to trade.
   A working prototype of Aurora should be ready in September, Board
of Trade officials said.
   The Board of Trade will be the sole owner of the Aurora system,
which incorporates technology developed specifically for the project
by Apple Computer Inc., Texas Insruments Inc. and Tandem Computers
Inc.
   Some Board of Trade members who have been shown a model of the
system during the past month call it ``Nintendo trading'' or
``Nintendo II'' after the popular video game.
   The Board of Trade's entry into electronic trading comes more
than a year after the Chicago Merc announced plans for Globex, which
also goes on line this fall.
   The Merc also leads the Board of Trade in signing up other
exchanges to offer its products for electronic trading.
   The Merc, the world's second-largest futures exchange after the
Board of Trade, has announced Globex links with the New York
Mercantile Exchange, the Sydney Futures Exchange of Australia and
the French futures exchange Marche a Terme International de France,
known as MATIF.
   But Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann said the
revolutionary features of Aurora will appeal to traders and win the
industry over.
   ``Aurora is truly the dawning of a new age in international
trading,'' Mahlmann said.
   Futures are binding contracts to buy and sell commodities and
financial instruments at a specified price at a future date.
   The exchanges say they will limit the contracts traded
electronically to financial futures, which are used extensively by
large institutional investors to hedge their risks in financial cash
markets.
   Globex, which is also on display at the Futures Industry
Association meeting, is known in the industry as a ``black box''
system because buy and sell orders entered into the system are
matched by a computer.
   The user of a ``black box'' system does not know the identity of
the person on the other side of the trade.
   The most startling aspect of Aurora is the computer-screen
display. Instead of the rows and columns of information displayed on
the terminal screens of black-box systems, an Aurora user sees blue
squares and red circles on a field of gray.
   Each symbol contains a trader's acronym and a number representing
the price at which that trader is offering to sell (red circle) or
bidding to buy (blue square) a futures contract.
   To make a trade, the Aurora user moves a cursor via a hand-held
``mouse'' from his own symbol to that of another trader and clicks
the mouse's button.
   With many traders in the market, all vying to buy low and sell
high, the action can move very quickly in a fashion that resembles
open-outcry trading, the traditional futures-trading method in which
traders face off in recessed pits and execute trades through a
combination of yelling and hand signals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
