<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-17 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Advances Against Yen, Shares Off In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar advanced further today against the
Japanese yen in a carry-over from overseas markets to close at a
five-month high in Tokyo, while share prices lost ground on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar started trading at 131.20 yen and edged down to below
131.00 yen briefly. Late morning trading was met by profit-taking,
traders said.
   But the market's strong desire for yen-selling and dollar-buying
lifted the currency back to close at 131.07 yen, up 0.34 yen from
Thursday's close of 130.73 yen. It was the highest close since Oct.
11 when it closed at 131.15 yen.
   The dollar's bullishness followed a strong showing on overseas
markets overnight following favorable U.S. trade reports released
Wednesday, traders said. In New York, the dollar gained 0.25 yen to
finish at 130.86 yen.
   ``The dollar's strength is a continuation of a worldwide trend
reflecting better-than-expected trade reports of the United States
Wednesday,'' said a trader with a major U.S. bank in Tokyo.
   Another trader for a Japanese commercial bank said political
uncertainties caused by an ongoing stock-profiteering scandal, in
which influential politicians and businessmen were sold unlisted
stocks at artificially low prices, is encouraging yen-selling.
   A Bank of Japan official, however, said the current decline of
the yen does not require immediate action.
   ``We will closely watch further developments,'' he said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, the exchange's most widely followed index, lost 77.01 points
to close at 32,021.01.
   The market's main index opened higher on the heels of a sharp
20.17-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York
overnight. But the market's anxiety about creeping inflation and
rising interest rates pulled the index down, traders said.
   ``The market situation is very sensitive right now about
inflation and interest rates,'' said Mike Morizumi, a trader with
Merrill Lynch's Tokyo office. ``Investors are hesitating to buy
shares because of various uncertain factors.''
   He said anticipation over the U.S. producer price index, to be
released in Washington today, has also sidelined many investors.
   ``There is anticipation of a stronger market as reflected in the
strong opening,'' he added.
</TEXT>
