<FIRST>r f PM-Third-WorldDebt     03-17 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third-World Debt,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Skeptical of Bush Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administration officials claim their new
approach to Third World debt could reduce developing nations' burden
20 percent over three years, but members of Congress doubt that will
be enough even if the plan works.
   Linking the issue to waves of illegal immigrants and tons of
illegal drugs entering the United States from Latin America _ as
well as the heightened political instability there _ both Democrats
and Republicans say they are disappointed the new initiative is not
bolder.
   ``I'm not sure that is going to be sufficient given the magnitude
of the problem,'' Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, told Assistant Treasury
Secretary David Mulford on Thursday.
   Mulford, testifying before House and Senate banking
subcommittees, described a 20 percent reduction in the $340 billion
owed by the 39 largest Third World debtors as a ``rough estimate''
of what can be achieved globally.
   He said some countries could do much better, depending on their
willingness to swap ownership of their natural resources or
industries to banks in exchange for forgiveness of some of the loans
or reduced interest rates.
   The new plan, unveiled last Friday by Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady and formally endorsed this week by President Bush and Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, for the first time calls on private
banks to discount their loans voluntarily.
   Whether the banks will go along remains to be seen. They largely
rejected urgings four years ago by former Treasury Secretary and now
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to increase their lending to
developing countries.
   Mulford, the chief architect of the new plan, said the first big
test will come when the banks try to negotiate among themselves for
waivers to provisions in many of the multi-bank loan packages that
now preclude them from writing down loans individually.
   Prior to that, however, the United States will get an idea
whether the plan will fly when the 151-nation World Bank and
International Monetary Fund meet in Washington early next month.
   Both Democrats and Republicans praised President Bush's
willingness to embrace the concept that private banks should forgive
a portion of the debt _ an idea brusquely rejected by former
President Reagan and his two Treasury secretaries, Baker and Donald
Regan.
   Senate Banking Committee Chairman Donald Riegle likened Regan's
approach of emphasizing primarily investment-oriented austerity
programs in developing countries to telling ``people dying of thirst
not to be thirsty.''
   ``Secretary Baker put a glass in front of them and thought he
would be able to get water into the glass and it didn't work,''
Riegle, D-Mich., told Mulford. ``Now you've come with a glass and
with a concept that will put some water into the glass. The question
is will it be enough to address the thirst?''
   Senators from states with large populations of recent Third World
immigrants were more skeptical.
   ``In terms of a glass of water, I'm afraid we've been given
another rock,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. ``We've been bombarded
with a series of small ideas on how to deal with this problem and I
had hoped we would hear a concept that had a breath of vision.''
   ``Many of the United States' most fundamental problems are tied
to this,'' Graham said. Among them, he cited increased drug traffic
because other trade is precluded and a ``staggering increase in
refugees'' from countries where a bulk of the earnings is devoted to
paying interest on the loans.
</TEXT>
