<FIRST>r f PM-ShipbuildersStrike     03-17 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shipbuilders Strike,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Workers Strike Bethlehem Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 Bethlehem Steel workers struck a
shipyard today after a last-ditch meeting with a federal mediator
failed to resolve a dispute over wages and benefits.
   Company officials said the strike could endanger the Sparrows
Point yard, which Bethlehem Steel said posted a $41 million deficit
last year.
   Strikers, who are trying to reclaim salary concessions made in
the early 1980s when Bethlehem Steel was on the brink of bankruptcy,
said the risk was worth it. Bethlehem Steel reported a $403 million
profit for 1988.
   ``It took me 37 years to make $10 an hour,'' said Ross
Caldarazzo, a sheet metal worker. ``I've got 37 years in, and I
won't get out with $500 (per month in pension benefits). They call
that a pension plan.
   ``We'll stay on strike as long as it takes,'' Caldarazzo said.
   Bethlehem Steel and union officials were called together by a
federal mediator Thursday afternoon but a two-hour meeting yielded
no progress, the union said.
   Workers on Wednesday rejected the company's latest offer by a
6-to-1 margin, following the recommendation made by leaders of Local
33, the International Association of Machinists-Industrial Union of
Marine and Shipbuilding Workers of America.
   The three-year pact expired at midnight.
   Bethlehem Steel told union members this week that despite the
overall profit last year, the yard lost $41 million last year and
$30 million the year before.
   The union initially asked for across-the-board increases of $2 an
hour the first year of the contract and $1 an hour during each of
the following two years. But Murphy Thornton, president of the
shipbuilders' local, said the union lowered its proposal during
negotiations.
   Bethlehem Steel offered some wage increases but not enough to
replace wage concessions granted in 1984, union officials said. The
offer reportedly also did not contain pension improvements sought by
the union.
   Thornton said the last raise the members received was in 1983,
and that was followed in 1984 by a $1 an hour pay cut.
   Under the company offer, first-class mechanics, who now earn
$10.62 an hour with cost-of-living increases included, would get
raises of 85 cents an hour in the first year, 45 cents in the second
year and 50 cents in the third.
   Second-class mechanics who now earn $10.50 would see raises of 22
cents, 15 cents and 21 cents. Third-class mechanics would get raises
of 18 cents, 10 cents and 14 cents, Thornton said.
</TEXT>
