<FIRST>r f PM-ContaminatedPoultry     03-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contaminated Poultry,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Charges Possible If Those To Blame For Feed Contamination
Caught</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges will be filed against whoever
introduced a banned pesticide into chicken feed, forcing the
slaughter of 400,000 tainted birds, a federal Food Safety and
Inspection Service official said.
   None of the contaminated meat reached consumers because the
presence of heptachlor was detected through routine testing before
the poultry made it to grocery shelves, inspection chief Lester
Crawford said Thursday.
   Authorities were investigating how the feed at Townsend's Poultry
Products in Batesville, Ark., was mixed with the suspected
cancer-causing pesticide that was banned for agricultural use six
years ago.
   Crawford said the pesticide was applied to a component of feed
Townsend's received and distributed to chicken producers.
   Townsend's, the ninth-largest poultry producer in the United
States, handles more than 23 million chickens each year for
producers around Batesville, which is about 90 miles northeast of
Little Rock.
   Since the pesticide turned up in January during routine tests of
chicken parts at a Campbell's Soup Co. frozen-foods factory in
Fayetteville, chickens worth $600,000 voluntarily have been
slaughtered, said Townsend's plant manager Tom Vanemburg. Two
million pounds of Townsend's poultry was stored in a warehouse for
testing, the Food Safety and Inspection Service said.
   Crawford said that if the Food and Drug Administration can find
out who first treated seed grain with heptachlor, prosecution is to
follow.
   ``We will always try to make a case, because this is an illegal
activity to add an adulterant to animal feed, whether intentionally
or unintentionally,'' he said.
   Checks during the last month at other feed mills around
Batesville haven't turned up heptachlor, Crawford said, ``but our
first suspicion is always treated seed.''
   The Batesville plant closed voluntarily for 11 days after the
contamination was discoverd.
</TEXT>
