<FIRST>r f PM-McDonnell-Theft     03-17 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McDonnell-Theft,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Executive In England Charged With Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British authorities have charged a former
executive at McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s international computer
subsidiary with embezzling at least $2.5 million from the company,
the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported in a copyright story today.
   The executive, David Stears, was director of operations at
McDonnell Douglas Information Systems Ltd. in Hemel Hempstead,
England. He resigned last month.
   Stears was arrested March 6 and has been charged with theft from
the company, McDonnell Douglas officials told the Post-Dispatch.
   The St. Louis-based defense contractor, meanwhile, has filed a
civil suit against Stears in London's High Court to try to recover
money from him, said David Malaperiman, communications director for
the computer subsidiary.
   ``We are cooperating fully and assisting with the police in their
inquiries,'' Malaperiman said. ``Because the matter is still under
investigation, we cannot make any further comment at this stage.''
   The newspaper quoted a source who said investigators believed
Stears took between $2.5 million and $3 million from the company.
The source said the investigators believed that Stears funneled the
money from England to two interior-design companies in Orlando, Fla.
   Stears also is a subject in a grand-jury investigation in Orlando
of an interior-design firm that he helped found last year.
Authorities believe the firm, Montalbano-Lordan International Inc.,
and a related firm, Laura International Inc., submitted fake bills
to McDonnell Douglas. Stears in turn approved the payment of the
bills, said another source close to the investigation.
</TEXT>
