<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing     03-17 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Anticipates Spending $1.1 Billion on Plants and Equipment
in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. plans to spend $1.1 billion on
plants and equipment in 1989, a 63 percent increase over the past
year, according to the annual report of the aerospace giant.
   The report issued Thursday did not give any breakdown of the
spending plans, but Paul Binder of Boeing said, ``since we have most
activities here (in the Seattle area), the majority of these funds
would be spent here.''
   Boeing's plant and equipment expenses amounted to $690 million in
1988, $738 million in 1987 and $795 million in 1986.
   Earlier this week, Boeing officials announced plans for a $430
million expansion and overhaul over the next five years at the
company's Renton complex, where production of 757 and 737 jetliners
is being boosted from the current 19 a month to 24 a month by the
middle of next year.
   The report said capital spending this year will provide more
space and equipment for current research and development, new and
current programs and measures to improve productivity.
   Record orders have resulted in a backlog of 1,100 commercial
jets, and Boeing is boosting the production rate for the 767 and 747
as well as the 737 and 757. By late next year company officials
expect to be cranking out at least 34 planes a month.
   The annual report also confirmed previous reports of a 28 percent
gain in earnings in 1988 but contained a sour note in the form of a
$95 million loss in Boeing's military aircraft business.
   Analysts, many of whom had predicted lower losses, blamed
troublesome contracts, including one to build new wings for A-6 Navy
fighters.
   ``The A-6 re-wing project continued to be a major challenge,''
and company managers still face ``major technical and schedule
problems,'' the report said.
   ``They've got a real rocky picture there,'' said analyst Paul
Nisbet of Prudential Bache Securities in New York.
   Despite higher production costs and costly, embarrassing delays
in delivering new 747-400 jumbo jets, the company's commercial
airplane division logged $11.3 billion sales, a 15.6 percent
increase.
   Operating profits were $585 million for the division, the highest
in more than five years and an increase of 66 percent from 1987.
   Sales rose 37 percent to $1.45 billion for missiles and space
products, with operating profits rising by 4.2 percent to $124
million for the year.
</TEXT>
