<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Milken     03-17 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milken,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Junk Bond Trader Gets Standing Ovation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire bond trader Michael Milken, who
is expected to be indicted for securities fraud, received two
standing ovations at a speech to the chief executive officers of
some of the nation's biggest companies.
   The address at Financial World magazine's ``CEO of the Decade''
dinner Thursday night was Milken's first public appearance in New
York since Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. agreed to fire him and
withhold his multimillion-dollar 1988 pay as part of a plea deal
with the government.
   Milken, who technically still works for the New York investment
firm, did not address charges that include insider trading in a
Securities and Exchange Commission suit against Drexel that names
him.
   He made one oblique reference to his status when he noted he had
a cold. ``In the past two years I have been learning about rights I
no longer have. I was afraid they were trying to take away my right
to speak, but the doctors of New York have told me I will be all
right.''
   The 42-year-old financier has received a target letter from the
government indicating that he will be indicted on criminal fraud and
other charges.
   In a 30-minute speech, Milken said America's needs for the 1990s
include ``re-educating the last generation'' and motivating
students. He called for the appointment of more women and minorities
as company chief executives.
   Milken also defended a wave of management-led buyouts,
debt-leveraged corporate expansions and employee stock ownership
programs that have ``allowed employees to once again have a stake in
this country.''
   Milken received standing ovations before and after the speech
from an audience of about 700 at the black-tie dinner at the
Waldorf-Astoria hotel.
   Milken has headed Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif., ``junk'' bond
financing department since the mid-1970s and is credited with
turning the high-risk, high-yield securities into a $175 billion a
year market. The bonds often are used to finance takeovers and the
growth of small- to medium-sized companies.
   Milken is challenging Drexel's settlement with the Manhattan U.S.
attorney's office of criminal securities fraud charges, which were
announced in January.
   Financial World named Wal-Mart Stores Inc. founder Samuel M.
Walton its ``CEO of the decade.''
  
</TEXT>
