<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pillsbury-AffirmativeAction     03-17 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pillsbury-Affirmative Action,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Affirmative Action Office Reinstated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employee complaints helped prompt Grand
Metropolitan PLC to reinstate Pillsbury Co.'s director of
affirmative action at least until a company task force completes its
report.
   A group of employees called the Pillsbury Black Network, along
with the leader of the Twin Cities chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, had written to
company officials protesting the transfer of the affirmative action
director's duties to the human resources department.
   Grand Met, which acquired Pillsbury in January for $5.7 billion,
eliminated the affirmative action job along with 550 others at
Pillsbury's Minneapolis headquarters as part of a cost-cutting move.
   ``The thing that convinced management that this position should
be reinstated was really the employees' concern,'' said Mary
Carroll, vice president of external affairs for Grand Met's food
sector.
   ``One of the concerns the employees pointed out was that it was
fine to have a task force, but what would happen until the task
force makes its recommendations ... that was a major reason for
(the) reinstatement,'' Carroll said.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said today there has been no
litigation involving anything affirmative action-related at
Pillsbury, which has 67,000 employees worldwide, including 1,800 at
the corporate offices.
   Carroll said the affirmative action director, Jean Fountain, was
also appointed to the task force that will investigate how the
company should pursue affirmative action goals. Fountain's job will
be reinstated until the task force findings are in, ``and then we'll
have more to say,'' Carroll said.
   The company also will hire an affirmative action consultant to
work with the task force.
   Local NAACP leader Matthew Little said he is pleased with Grand
Met's willingness to reconsider its decision, and said it
demonstrates that the company is concerned about its impact on the
Twin Cities community _ a concern he said the community shares.
</TEXT>
