<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-17 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0282</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened slightly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade, but just as quickly
trended lower in line with the financial markets.
   A 1 percent rise in the producer price index _ a signal that
inflation is rearing its head _ dropped a bomb on the stock market,
but should have been a boon for the commodities markets.
   Instead, after a short climb on the open, grain and soybean
prices quickly slid on a wave of local selling that some traders
attributed to concerns in the financial markets.
   Said one floor trader, ``The more the locals looked up at the
board and saw the stock market collapsing, the more they tended to
follow suit.''
   On the open, wheat was } cent to 3\ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.35{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to } cents higher, with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1 cent higher, with March at $2.09\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 1\ cent lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.67
a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .90 cent lower, with April at 77.42
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .85 cent lower, with
March at 79.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .37 cent lower to .07
cent higher, with April at 42.80 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .45 cent lower to .15 cent higher, with March at 36.70
cents a pound.
