<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AppleSales     03-17 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apple Sales,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Shipments Drop 150,000 Boxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipments of Washington apples dropped by
152,000 boxes in the past week, a sign that some consumers have
stopped buying because of the Alar scare, an industry official said
today.
   The weekly report of out-of-state shipments of the nation's
largest apple crop showed a drop from 1.56 million boxes two weeks
ago to 1.4 million boxes last week.
   For the same week last year shipments were 1.5 million boxes,
said Bill DeWitt of the Wenatchee Valley Traffic Association.
   Based on the top price quoted Thursday for the three main apple
varieties in Washington, the loss to growers from last week's
shipment decline could be as much as $2.4 million.
   ``I'm sure part of this downtrend is the Alar scare,'' said
DeWitt, manager of one of two major apple shipment record-keeping
organizations in the state. ``There is no doubt in my mind.''
   Exports to foreign countries were down 35,000 boxes, from 173,000
boxes to 138,000 boxes last week, DeWitt said.
   ``That downturn is mostly Taiwan,'' he said, of the mass
cancellations of orders by Taiwanese exporters in recent weeks.
   The shipment figures are compiled by the state Department of
Agriculture from scores of warehouses across the state, and they
show the number of 42-pound boxes of apples purchased by retailers,
wholesalers, school districts, institutional customers and other
apple users.
   The shipment figures are considered an accurate barometer of
consumer sales.
   DeWitt said there was no way to tell how much of the drop in
shipments was related to a widespread ban of apple products in
school cafeterias, and how much was a drop in retail sales. Some
schools announced this week that apples would return to cafeterias
next week.
   The Alar scare was ignited in late February, when the non-profit
Natural Resources Defense Council issued a report saying eating
apples treated with the chemical daminozide, marketed as Alar,
increased the cancer risk in children.
   The apple industry has disputed the findings, and also maintained
that only about 5 percent of the crop is treated with the chemical.
   But the concerns raised by the NRDC were enough to cause many of
the nation's largest school districts to ban apples from cafeterias,
and prompted the cancellation of thousands of boxes worth of
Taiwanese orders.
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency, Food and Drug
Administration and Department of Agriculture this week also declared
apples safe for Americans to eat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
