<FIRST>r f BC-Trump-Hotel     03-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Trump-Hotel,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Trump Negotiating To Buy Unfinished Casino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump is negotiating
to buy a long-dormant hotel-casino project that would expand his
holdings in this resort city, a published report said Friday.
   The Press of Atlantic City, quoting unidentified sources, said
Trump's representatives have been talking with owners of the former
Penthouse Boardwalk Hotel Casino project, which is located next to
the Trump Plaza Hotel and Casino.
   Trump could not be reached for comment Friday. His secretary said
Trump was not in his office and likely would not be available for
comment.
   Trump has tried to buy the Penthouse property in the past, but
was turned down by Penthouse. If he is successful, Trump is expected
to convert the project into a non-casino hotel linked to Trump
Plaza, the Press said.
   Last November, Trump sold Resorts International Inc. to
entertainer Merv Griffin and bought back from Resorts its unfinished
Taj Mahal casino complex here.
   A deal to buy the Penthouse project could be complicated by an
agreement between Penthouse and Pratt Hotel Corp., which planned to
convert the property into the Sands Hollywood Hotel Casino, the
Press said.
   The $55 million deal apparently also includes the site of a
proposed parking garage located one block away from the Penthouse
site. It remains uncertain how Trump could buy that property since
Penthouse bought it in partnership with Pratt Hotel Corp.
   William Weidner, president of Pratt Hotel Corp., told the Press
he knew about rumors that Trump and Penthouse officials were
talking. He questioned whether Penthouse would be able to sell the
property.
   ``We have a valid contract in place and I think they (Penthouse
officials) run the danger of some rather expensive litigation if
they try to do something other than sell it to us,'' Weidner told
the newspaper.
</TEXT>
