<FIRST>r f PM-Cattle-Feedlots     03-17 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cattle-Feedlots,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Cattle Inventory Grows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as of
March 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 7.66 million head, up
1 percent from a year ago and 7 percent more than inventories of two
years ago, the Agriculture Department says.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported Thursday at 1.59 million head, up 15 percent from
a year ago and 10 percent more than two years ago. Officials said
the February placements were the most for the month since the
monthly seven-state records began in 1972.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in February totaled 1.51 million
head, down 2 percent from a year ago but up 2 percent from two years
ago.
   As of March 1, feedlot inventories were larger than a year
earlier in California, Colorado, Iowa and Kansas, but were less in
Arizona, Nebraska and Texas. The seven states produce about
three-fourths of the nation's beef.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of March 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
