<FIRST>u f PM-PublicBroadcasting 1stLd-Writethru f0103 03-17 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Public Broadcasting, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0103,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Plead for New Satellite to Avoid Disruptions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: First 2 grafs new to clarify that money is for replacement satellite
in service since 1980. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, CPB President.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public radio and television programming faces
serious disruption unless Congress finds money to replace a
satellite expected to fail in 1991, the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting said today.
   CPB officials, who also are seeking full financing of their
fiscal 1992 budget authorization of $265 million, urged a Senate
panel to provide an additional $143.19 million to replace the
satellite, which since 1980 has handled the public broadcasting
network.
   CPB President Donald Ledwig said failure to receive the satellite
money would ``force the public broadcasting system to divert scarce
resources away from programming and into satellite replacement.''
   He said that would ``seriously disrupt and adversely affect
public broadcasting's programming nationwide.''
   The satellite's useful life will end in 1991 when its
transponders, which relay TV signals to public radio and TV stations
around the country, run out of fuel.
   Congress last year authorized $200 million to replace the
satellite, but thus far it has appropriated only $56.81 million for
fiscal 1991 for the project, CPB said.
   The Bush administration has proposed freezing CPB's fiscal 1992
appropriation at its 1991 level of $242.06 million, with no
additional funds to replace the satellite.
   CPB Board Chairman R. Kenneth Towery, testifying before a Seate
Appropriations subcommittee, said the freeze recommendation
``directly counters the intent of Congress to fund CPB at levels
that reflect reasonable federal support for the nation's public
telecommunications system.''
   ``Dollar for dollar, the funds spent for public broadcasting are
the most efficient means of ensuring that all Americans have access
to outstanding educational, cultural and informational programming
and services,'' Towery said.
   CPB's request of $265 million in general programming support only
``amounts to approximately $1 for each U.S. citizen for the year,''
he said, adding that more than 100 million people watch public TV
each week and more than 10 million listen to public radio.
   ``Today, approximately three-fourths of all families with
children under the age of six watch and learn from public television
regularly,'' Ledwig said.
   He also said long-range funding is essential to public
broadcasting's ability to obtain the non-federal revenue that makes
up the 81 cents of every dollar the system spends.
   CPB is a private, non-profit corporation that was authorized by
the Public Broadcasting Act of 1967 to develop non-commercial radio
and TV programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890317-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv18   03-17 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 18,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Saturday, March 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>The High Cost Of No Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation is a nuisance, to say the least, but
would you really pay the price of getting rid of it altogether?
   If you say yes, you have made a decision that no president or
Federal Reserve chief has ever dared make.
   There is a very high price to eliminating inflation, or even
making the attempt, and whoever steers the economy in that direction
is likely to provoke his or her own good riddance.
   Inflation might have a bad reputation, but to some extent it is a
necessary evil in maintaining a strong economy. In a limited sense,
say some economists, it can even be a measure of economic
enthusiasm, vitality and intensity.
   Roger Brinner, economist at DRI McGraw-Hill, the old Data
Resources organization so highly esteemed by many economists,
recently accused the Federal Reserve of not having the courage to
eliminate the cussed curse.
   Brinner wasn't encouraging the Fed to pursue such a course; he
was merely stating what he believed to be a fact of economic life.
And to demonstrate this, he put some hypothetical numbers in his
computer economic model.
   He asked it:
   ``What unemployment rate would the Fed have to target in the
early 1990s in order to bring inflation to zero by 1995?''
   It answered:
   Unemployment would rise to an average of 8.6 percent over the
next five years. More than three million workers who are now
employed would be unable to find satsifactory jobs. Output would be
depressed an average of 5 percent.
   All this, observes Brinner, in order to cut inflation by four
percentage points relative to current rates and by five percentage
points relative to rates predicted for 1995.
   Such numbers clearly suggest why pursuit of zero inflation at
this time would be foolhardy: The gain would be minor, the damage
inestimable. For a president it would be political suicide, for a
Fed chairman professional ruin.
   The problem with attempting to erase ingrained inflation is that
it is bound to force unemployment higher and almost certain to
reduce output. While this might not be a law of economics, it is a
very powerful thesis.
   Simply put, says Brinner, ``the theory is that inflation will
continually fall as long as slack exists in labor and goods
markets.'' If that sounds innocuous, you may be sure it isn't.
   Right now, there is very little slack in either. Unemployment is
just a bit over 5 percent of the civilian labor force, a low figure
for recent years, while factories are operating at about 85 percent
of capacity, a high figure.
   When you reach those figures you are close to starting the fires
of serious inflation. Stressed, both markets react by pushing up
their price tags, i.e. wage levels and the prices of goods.
   To eliminate inflation, slack is necessary.
   ``The greater the slack, the greater the year-to-year decline in
inflation will be,'' says Brinner.
   The DRI McGraw-Hill model's conclusion explains to some degree
the adage that a lot of inflation is a dangerous thing while a
little inflation can be tolerated.
   Based on the current level of economic understanding, it is all
but impossible to fine tune the economy to zero inflation while
protecting the country from serious recession and political
explosions.
   In short, it's just not worth the effort. The price is too high.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Saturday, March 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
