<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeating for All Needing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market took a sharp drop today as a new
inflation surprise rocked Wall Street.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 47.14 points to
2,293.57 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues overwhelmed advances by nearly 7 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
202 up, 1,375 down and 330 unchanged.
   Before the opening, the government reported that the producer
price index of finished goods rose a full percentage point in
February, matching its increase the month before.
   That news came as a rude surprise to stock traders, who had been
expecting a gain of about half that size, and set off a new wave of
inflation and interest-rate worries.
   In the credit markets, prices of long-term government bonds,
which move in the opposite direction from interest rates, fell about
$20 for each $1,000 in face value.
   Conjecture immediately began to spread in the financial world
that the Federal Reserve would feel compelled to take further steps
soon to tighten credit in its effort to keep inflatin restrained.
   The intensity of activity in the stock market was heightened by
the so-called ``triple witching hour,'' a quarterly occasion when
the last trading occurs in a set of expiring options and futures on
stock indexes.
   This situation prompts heavy trading by professionals engaged in
computer program strategies that involve both the options and
futures and individual stocks.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 2] at 115}; General Motors, down 1\ at 83\; American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down ~ at 31~; Exxon, down 1\ at 44~, and
General Electric, down 1] at 45[.
   W.R. Grace fell 1] to 30{. The company denied rumors that
Chairman Peter Grace was planning to retire, which had led to talk
that the company might become a takeover target.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
3.12 to 164.98. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 3.44 at 329.08.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 174.15 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
