<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower As Rate Worries Flare</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeating for all needing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged Friday in the worst single-day
loss this year on the London Stock Exchange, after the government
reported an unexpectedly strong rise in U.S. producer prices in
February.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, which sank as
much as 49 points at midafternoon, recovered somewhat to finish the
day down 39.5 points, or 1.9 percent, at 2,073.1.
   Volume was 535.2 million shares, little changed from Thursday's
543.2 million shares.
   The report of a 1 percent rise in those prices triggered worries
that interest rates worldwide would head higher.
   The news hit a market already preoccupied by indications of
inflationary pressures and economic slowdown in the British economy.
   ``The first and by far the greatest fear is that international
interest rates have yet to go higher,'' said Paul Walton, an
equities analyst at Warburg Securities.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson ``has made it very clear
that if sterling weakens, and there are signs of inflation, he'll
jack up interest rates,'' in Britain, the analyst added.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended the day down 34.6 points
at 1,705.5. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 22.38 points to
close at 1,182.32.
