<SECOND>PM-Japan-Aircraft Technology, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0018,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Made No Decision on FSX</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Bush quotes; picks up 2nd graf pvs, Press
Secretary ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he has made no
decision on a deal that would enable Japan to build an advanced
version of the F-16 fighter plane.
   ``It's a good one to be sure you listen carefully to all sides
of...and that's what we are doing,'' Bush told reporters aboard Air
Force One as he flew back to Washington from Colorado.
   ``No decision has been made. I have not made any decision at
all,'' Bush said.
   Press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday the administration
wants to go ahead with the controversial technology transfer
agreement involving the FSX warplane, which Japan wants to deploy in
the late 1990s.
   But, he said, ``there are at least three or four basic issues
regarding the agreement'' that still must be resolved.
   Fitzwater, speaking with reporters on Air Force One as Bush flew
to Houston for a speech, said a final presidential decision on the
FSX may not come until next week.
   He said Bush was reviewing documents and reading position papers
while on the plane. Once the president decides on safeguards, ``then
we would be able to announce that we are prepared to go ahead with
an agreement,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``What he's deciding are the terms of the agreement that we would
want to strike for the co-production of the plane,'' the spokesman
said.
   Under the U.S.-Japan agreement initialed late last year, St.
Louis-based General Dynamics would join forces with Japan's
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to co-develop and co-produce the
next-generation fighter.
   Proponents argue the agreement represents the best deal the
United States could negotiate in the face of Japanese opposition to
buying F-16s directly from the United States. They say the deal will
serve to promote beneficial technology transfer in both directions
while generating income and jobs for U.S. industry.
   But critics contend the arrangement amounts to a giveaway of
advanced technology that Japan may use to help propel its civilian
aircraft industry into head-to-head competition with the United
States in the world market. They say Tokyo should purchase
American-made planes to help offset the $50 billion U.S. trade
deficit with Japan.
   Opposition to the aircraft deal within the administration has
been led by Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher, backed by other
Cabinet members including budget director Richard G. Darman, U.S.
Trade Representative Carla Hills and Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins.
   Pushing for approval of the deal as negotiated with Japan have
been officials of the Pentagon and State Department, including
Richard L. Armitage, assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs.
</TEXT>
