<HEAD>Chile Inspects Japanese Trawlers After Japan Bans Chilean Fruit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 4-6, ``In Washington...the agreement.'' with 3 grafs
to UPDATE with agreement in Washington. Pickup 7th graf, ``Since traces...
Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A naval officer today denied a news report
that five Japanese ships were seized in retaliation for Japan's
decision to ban imports of Chilean fruit. He said the ships were
detained for safety inspections.
   On Thursday, Chileans ate grapes, apples and other produce in
defiance of a cyanide poisoning scare that resulted in the Japanese
ban and warnings in the United States and Canada that caused Chilean
produce to be removed from stores.
   Japanese officials said that only two fishing trawlers were
receiving a ``strict'' inspection by Chilean authorities.
   The Bush administration said today it would release Chilean fruit
for public consumption but said any produce already in storage must
be destroyed.
   ``With these and other safeguards in place we believe that this
program will provide the maximum feasible safety for fruit from
Chile,'' FDA Commissioner Frank Young told a news conference in
Washington.
   He outlined the administration's plans for ending the five-day
public health scare after Bush told reporters the quarantine of
Chilean fruit had been justified despite any economic hardship it
imposed.
   Since traces of cyanide were found in two Chilean grapes in
Philadelphia, tens of thousands of Chilean fruit workers have been
laid off and Chile has lost millions of dollars in export revenues,
Chilean officials say. Chile exports about 65 percent of its fruit
to the United States.
   Chile's foreign minister, Hernan Felipe Errazuriz, said in
Washington that 200,000 Chileans and their families face
``unemployment and even destitution.''
   Navy Lt. Jose Araya said in an interview with The Associated
Press today that the five Japanese trawlers were undergoing ``a
mandatory thorough safety inspection'' at three ports in southern
Chile.
   ``This is necessary for the safety of all people on board those
vessels,'' Araya said. ``Once inspectors are satisfied with the
safety standards of the boats, they will let them sail off.''
   He said he did not know how long the inspection would take.
   On Thursday, the official news agency Orbe quoted navy Capt.
Patricio Urbina as saying the five Japanese trawlers were ``seized''
in the ports of Talcahuano, Chacabuco and Punta Arenas in southern
Chile.
   It quoted Adm. Jose Merino, navy commander-in-chief, as saying:
   ``The Japanese have closed their market to Chilean fruits, so I'm
holding their ships.'' Merino, who is also president of the
law-making military junta, also was quoted as saying: ``None of them
is going to fish in our waters until they re-open the market to our
fruits.''
   But Araya said the ships were merely detained for safety
inspections and did not say the action was meant as a retaliation
for the Japanese ban.
   On Thursday, Pinochet made a surprise visit to a fruit-packing
house and said foreign reaction to the cyanide scare was
exaggerated. He ate several seedless white grapes to show they were
safe. ``They are very good,'' said Pinochet, who took power in a
bloody 1973 military coup.
   At rallies in Santiago on Thursday, Chileans waved anti-American
signs and ate the native grapes, peaches, pears, nectarines and
Granny Smith apples the U.S., Japan and Canada have urged consumers
to avoid.
</TEXT>
