<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Soar in February; Financial Markets Sell In Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 new grafs to UPDATE Dow average, bond prices. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, The identical...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices soared 1.0 percent in February for the second
consecutive month, the government reported today, sending stock and
bond prices tumbling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 leading industrial stocks, which
plunged about 50 points right after trading opened, was down 47.14
to 2,293.57 at 2 p.m. on Wall Street. That was off sharply from the
six-week high the popular market indicator had reached just Thursday
amid sentiment that inflation might be slowing.
   Bond prices _ a sensitive barometer of inflation speculation _
also fell sharply before leveling off. The government's bellwether
30-year bond was down nearly 2 points, or $19 per $1,000 of face
amount, at mid-day while its yield jumped to just over 9.3 percent.
   The identical back-to-back increases in wholesale prices, as
measured by the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, were
propelled by rises in energy and food prices.
   The increases mean that inflation at the wholesale level, one
stop short of retail, is running at 12.6 percent annual rate so far
in 1989. That is more than triple the 4.0 percent increase for all
of last year.
   Both large jumps had surprised analysts, who had predicted
moderate rises of about 0.4 percent. After January's numbers were
reported, economists dismissed them as an aberration and said
inflation would return to the 4 percent to 5 percent annual pace of
late last year.
   Wholesale food prices climbed 1.2 percent, the steepest increase
in 13 months. Energy prices jumped 2.4 percent, and analysts
anticipate little relief as the vacation driving season nears and
crude oil prices continue to hover around the $20-a-barrel mark.
   On Thursday, government reports on housing construction and
factory use indicated the economy might be cooling off.
   In its report on housing starts, the Commerce Department said new
homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.5 million units in February, down 11.4 percent from January's
rate of 1.69 million units.
   Part of last month's decline was due to the weather, which turned
cold again after an unseasonably mild January. But analysts said
higher mortgage rates were taking their toll.
   Analysts said a longer-term slowdown in the housing market also
reflects the steady upward climb of interest rates.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the nation's
industrial operating rate _ also known as factory use _ eased last
month for the first time since September.
   U.S. factories, mines and utilities operated at 84.3 percent of
capacity in February, down 0.2 percentage point from January, when
the 84.5 percent rate was the highest in nearly a decade, the Fed
reported.
   At the same time, the pace of industrial production held steady
in February after 12 months of steady advances, the central bank
said in a second report.
   The news was welcomed by those worried that the overheating
economy is pushing up prices. The closer factories get to full
capacity, the greater the fear they will have trouble producing
enough goods to meet demand, leading to shortages and price
increases.
   Federal Reserve Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson told reporters the
figures are ``consistent with the notion of some moderation in the
economy'' although it would be premature to say they signal a trend.
   The reports heartened traders in the stock market. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks rose 20.17 to 2,340.71, its highest
close since it stood at 2,343.21 on Feb. 8. The day before that the
average hit a post-crash high of 2,347.14.
   Traders took the Fed reports as evidence that inflationary
pressures in the economy were easing, but analysts were cautious
about reading too much into one month's figures.
   Bond prices finished little changed in light trading. Analysts
said the government reports met the market's expectations.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 1-32 point, or 31
cents per $1,000 face amount, while its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from price, was about 9.11 percent, roughly even
with late Wednesday.
   Many traders remained on the sidelines, awaiting today's producer
price report.
</TEXT>
