<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel     03-17 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say SEC Wants Milken Fired Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has rejected a
government demand to fire financier Michael Milken immediately,
further delaying settlement of fraud charges against the investment
firm, sources said Friday.
   The refusal by Drexel Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph marks a
possibly significant roadblock in resolving civil charges, and could
complicate resolution of criminal charges stemming from a two-year
federal investigation into one of Wall Street's biggest and most
profitable companies.
   Drexel already has agreed to government demands to axe Milken,
withhold his multimillion-dollar 1988 pay and bar him from ever
speaking with members of the firm about any business matters.
   But the latest request by the Securities and Exchange Commission
would require the 42-year-old financier to immediately leave the
firm, which he helped develop into the leader in the high-yield
``junk'' bond market.
   Milken, who has emerged as a leading figure in a federal campaign
against securities abuses, is expected to be charged with a range of
fraud and racketeering charges. He has denied wrongdoing and has
been working part-time at Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif., office
while preparing his defense.
   Sources who have direct knowledge of the settlement negotiations
said SEC enforcement director Gary Lynch made the new demand during
talks earlier this week. Joseph told Lynch the firm wouldn't do it,
said the sources, who spoke on the condition they not be identified.
   ``Lynch told Fred Joseph they need to fire Michael prior to any
settlement being signed and agreed to by the SEC,'' said one source.
   ``The thinking by the SEC is that if (Drexel) does that then
Milken has less of a case because they're not mandating'' his
firing, the source said.
   Firing Milken would not be a written provision of the settlement
with the SEC, the source said.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder declined to comment on any part
of the negotiations as did a spokesman for Milken. SEC spokeswoman
Mary McCue also refused to comment.
   Drexel already has conceded to terminating Milken as part of a
deal settling criminal charges with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's
office reached in December. Drexel also agreed to plead guilty to
six felony counts and pay a record $650 million in fines and
restitution.
   Milken has asked a federal judge to reject or modify the pact,
which cannot be approved by a federal judge until the SEC deal is
completed. His lawyers say firing him and withholding earned
compensation denies him his legal rights.
   The SEC is said to want Milken ousted immediately regardless of
his legal challenge to the criminal settlement, on grounds that all
employees that the agency believes are responsible for illegal
activities should be purged.
   Sources said the government also wants to insure that Milken is
fired because his legal challenge may take months to resolve and he
could remain at the firm indefinitely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
