<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0274</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed mostly higher, but
wheat and corn ended mixed Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Because inflationary developments are viewed as favorable to
commodity prices, most traders expected the government's report of a
strong 1 percent rise in the producer price index would prove a boon
for the futures markets.
   Instead, after a short climb on the opening, prices in all three
pits quickly slid on a wave of selling that some traders attributed
to concerns in the financial markets where stocks and bonds fell
sharply.
   Wheat stayed in a narrow range all day as the market split on
conflicting forecasts of how much rain will hit the winter wheat
areas of the Plains this weekend.
   Soybeans, however, made a stunning recovery _ 15 cents on some
contracts _ on late buying by professional and commission houses
either covering short positions or squaring up for the weekend.
   ``There was no fresh news, but the same people who were selling
the market early turned out to be the ones who bought it late,''
said Vic Lespinasse, a floor trader for Dean Witter Reynolds.
   On the close, wheat was 3 cents lower to } cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.34 a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to { cent higher, with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to { cent higher, with March at $2.08 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1 cent lower to 6} cents higher, with March at $7.69{
a bushel.
