<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 2249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Patents     03-17 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Patents,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreigners' Share of U.S. Patents Continues to Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The share of U.S. patents issued to foreigners
continued to grow in 1988, the Commerce Department said Friday.
   The department's Patent and Trademark Office said it issued
84,272 patents last year, of which 47.1 percent were granted to
foreigners, up from 46.6 percent in 1987.
   Overall, the number of patents issued last year was down 5.7 from
1987.
   Japanese inventors kept the lead, receiving 16,984 of the patents
issued, down from 17,288 in 1987.
   West Germany remained a distant second, claiming 7,501 patents
last year, down from 8,030 in 1987.
   The percentage of U.S. patents obtained by foreigners has more
the doubled in the past 25 years. It reached the 20 percent level in
1966 and has increased each year since then.
   Patents and Trademarks Commissioner Donald J. Quigg said his
office is trying to counter that trend through an outreach program
``aimed at teaching students to think analytically.''
   ``I only hope our efforts to rekindle the spirit of invention are
not too late,'' Quigg said.
   Under international agreements, foreign residents may obtain U.S.
patents under the same terms as U.S. citizens. Americans are treated
in a similar fashion by foreign patent offices.
   Of the 44,570 patents issued to U.S. residents last year,
Californians claimed the most, at 6,875.
   Here are figures for the top 10 foreign countries in receipts of
patents last year: Japan, 16,984; West Germany, 7,501; France,
2,792; United Kingdom, 2,756; Switzerland, 1,298; Italy, 1,172;
Netherlands, 899; Sweden, 891; Taiwan, 536, and Australia, 486.
   Here are figures for the top 10 states in receipts of patents
last year: California, 6,875; New York, 3,647; New Jersey, 2,777;
Illinois, 2,612; Pennsylvania, 2,560; Texas, 2,540; Ohio, 2,376;
Michigan, 2,312; Massachusetts, 1,786, and Florida, 1,508.
</TEXT>
