<FIRST>r f AM-SouthernMagazine     03-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Southern Magazine,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Progress Announces Agreement to Buy Southern Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Progress Corp. announced Friday
the purchase of controlling interest in the 3-year-old Southern
magazine.
   Financial terms of the agreement were not disclosed.
   The magazine's publisher, Alan Leveritt, said he had been
notified that the Little Rock, Ark., magazine was being purchased by
Birmingham-based Southern Living magazine and that Southern will be
moving to Birmingham.
   Leveritt said he would have preferred not to sell the magazine
``but they made our financiers a very generous offer and they have a
right to sell when they get a good offer.''
   He said Southern was to made its first profit this quarter.
   Leveritt had said earlier this week that negotiations were under
way for the sale of Southern, which has 20 employees and a
circulation of about 275,000, to Southern Progress Corp., a Time
Inc. subsidiary which publishes Southern Living and other regional
magazines.
   Southern Progress said Friday its agreement with Stephens Inc. of
Little Rock, the magazine's principal stockholder, calls for
Southern Progress to have a 70 percent interest in the partnership
and to be the managing general partner.
   ``We will have a minority interest in the magazine but we have no
control,'' Leveritt said. ``They (Southern Living) are making no
commitments on employing anyone at Southern magazine. I think
Southern Progress is an excellent company and that they are going to
do a good job with it and we wish them well.''
   Don Logan, chief executive officer of Southern Progress, said
combined issues of Southern will be published in May-June and
July-August to give more time to formulate an editorial strategy for
the magazine.
   ``We will announce more specific details about our editorial
plans in the next few weeks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
