<DOCNO> AP890317-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet-Limits     03-17 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street-Limits,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Triple Witching Compounds Sell-Off; Circuit Breakers In Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inflation-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp stock market sell-off sparked by renewed
inflation fears Friday triggered futures trading limits aimed at
preventing another market crash.
   The price limits on stock-index futures trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange were used for the first time since being imposed
last year by major financial markets.
   Sparking the trading frenzy was the Labor Department's report of
a larger-than-expected increase in February's producer prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials plummeted about 50 points
on the opening and held at lower levels throughout the day as a new
wave of inflation fears and worries that the Federal Reserve would
boost interest rates rippled through the market.
   The Dow industrials finished down 48.57 points at 2,292.14.
   Last October, the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission approved a series of so-called
``circuit-breaker'' measures designed to calm jittery, volatile
markets and prevent a repeat of the Black Monday crash of Oct. 19,
1987.
   Many critics blamed the effect of computerized strategies
involving simultaneous trading of stocks and stock index futures for
worsening the Black Monday crash, when the Dow Jones average fell
508 points.
   As a result, regulators approved plans to limit trading when it
appeared that sharp price movements in the futures markets _ where
stock index futures are traded _ might spark ensuing plunges in the
stock market.
   Part of the plan stipulates that S&amp;P 500 futures price movements
be limited for 30 minutes once the S&amp;P 500 contract drops 12 points,
to give the markets a cooling-off period. Such a decline is
equivalent to roughly a 100-point drop in the Dow industrials.
   On Friday, a separate five-point price limit on the S&amp;P 500
contract was in effect for the first 10 minutes of trading, when
traders sold off the contract following the inflation report.
   Merc officials and the New York Stock Exchange conferred by phone
during the opening limit, the Merc said in a statement issued after
the market close. The Merc said the S&amp;P 500 limit coordinated ``an
orderly opening'' and noted that the markets continued to trade
normally afterward.
   Although the plunge in the Dow was noteworthy, it came nowhere
near the 250-point drop required to temporarily suspend stock market
trading under the circuit breaker plan. Trading on the major U.S.
exchanges would be halted for an hour on days when the Dow drops 250
points.
   If there is an additional 150-point plunge, for a total of 400
points in a single day, a second circuit breaker would impose an
additional two-hour halt.
   Stock market activity also was intensified somewhat on Friday by
the triple witching hour, the quarterly, simultaneous expiration of
options and futures on stock indexes.
   This situation often prompts abnormally heavy trading by
professionals engaged in complicated strategies involving trading of
both the options and futures and the individual stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
