<FIRST>u f AM-Futures-Moles     03-17 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Futures-Moles,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Merc Would Accept Permanent Moles If Needed To Deter
Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Futures Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Placing undercover regulatory police on
the trading floors of futures exchanges sounds ``invasive'' but they
may be needed to help curb trading fraud, a high-ranking Chicago
Mercantile Exchange official said Friday.
   But the Chicago Merc's planned improvements to its internal
surveillance systems should make it unnecessary to have government
moles patrol the trading pits, added John F. Sandner, a special
adviser to the exchange's board of director's and its immediate past
chairman.
   Sandner made the comments in an interview with the Associated
Press following Rep. Glenn English's statement Thursday that he
would not rule out the possibility that his investigative panel
would consider giving federal regulators the authority to place
undercover watchdogs on the floors of futures exchanges to guard
against the kind of trading abuse being investigated by the Justice
Department in Chicago.
   ``It sounds like a pretty invasive approach but we don't object
to that approach if it is warranted,'' Sandner said.
   ``But once Congressman English sees what the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange is going to do as far as supervising our pits and
increasing surveillance, I think that will be unnecessary.''
   Officials of the Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest
futures market, declined to comment on English's remark.
   The Chicago Merc is the world's second-largest futures exchange.
   English, D-Okla., chairs a House agriculture subcommittee that is
examining the fitness of futures-trading regulation.
   He spoke Thursday at the Futures Industry Association's annual
meeting here.
   The federal undercover probe of suspected trading abuse at the
Chicago exchanges has not yet yielded any charges, but it has
focused attention on the opportunities for cheating and prompted
lawmakers to take a closer look at fraud detection and prosecution.
</TEXT>
