<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Sale, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Pan Am Union Leaders to Discuss Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 8th graf to UPDATE with no comment from Eastern; picks
up 9th graf pvs bg'ng, Financial analysts ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union leader at Pan Am Corp. said he planned to
meet the head of Eastern's striking Machinists union Saturday to
discuss a possible employee-led buyout that would combine the two
troubled airlines.
   William F. Genoese, director of the Teamsters union's Airline
Division, told The Associated Press that he and Charles Bryan
planned to discuss a possible combination of Eastern and Pan Am.
   ``His (Bryan's) fight is our fight,'' Genoese said Friday in a
telephone interview from Miami. ``We'll do everything we can do in
order to make this successful.''
   The employees of the two carriers would be able to secure
financing for a buyout by agreeing to labor concessions, said
Genoese, who also serves as head of the Teamsters local at Pan Am. A
combination of the two airlines would give Pan Am domestic routes to
feed into its international network, he said.
   Bryan confirmed that he planned to meet with Genoese but declined
to say whether they would explore an employee-led, Eastern-Pan Am
combination.
   ``We're going to be discussing a whole range of subjects,'' Bryan
said from his office in Miami.
   Eastern has been crippled since last its Machinists went on
strike March 4 and later were joined by most of the airline's pilots
and flight attendants.
   Spokesmen for other unions at the two airlines weren't available
for comment. Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon in New York and
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell in Miami said their companies had no
comment on the meeting.
   Financial analysts say the leading potential buyer for Eastern
remains financier Carl Icahn, the owner and chairman of Trans World
Airlines Inc., who expressed his interest last fall. The Eastern
Machinists indicated last week they want him to explore a possible
buyout and he expressed a willingness to do so if Eastern did not
object.
   Eastern would provide TWA with the same sort of ``fit'' between
domestic and international routes that a Pan Am-Eastern combination
would create.
   Pan Am, like Eastern, has been racked by financial losses and
labor tensions. Pan Am Chairman Tom Plaskett recently said the
carrier probably would need to merge with another airline to ensure
its survival.
   Last year Pan Am imposed $35 million in pay cuts on its 4,200
Teamsters, who are led by Genoese, after they rejected a new
cost-cutting contract.
   ``Two negatives don't make a positive,'' said Robert Joedicke, an
airline analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., referring to a
possible Pan Am-Eastern combination. ``The cards are stacked against
them.''
   As the labor crisis at Eastern has escalated, Bryan has been the
nemesis of Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo. Genoese has long been a thorn
in the side of Pan Am and other airlines where the Teamsters are
represented.
   The Teamsters at Pan Am and the 8,500 Eastern Machinists both
represent baggage handlers, although there are differences in the
composition of the two unions.
   Bryan and Genoese said the Teamsters plan to contribute $100,000
to the Eastern employees' strike fund.
</TEXT>
