<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FCC-TVAffiliates     03-17 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FCC-TV Affiliates,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repeals Rule on Contract Limits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: retransmitting to restore cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday repealed a rule that had limited contracts between
television networks and their local affiliate stations to two years.
   The FCC said the rule, adopted in 1945 when TV networks were just
forming and lining up local outlets for their programs, was no
longer necessary to assist in the development of new TV networks in
today's television industry of alternative delivery systems such as
satellites and cable.
   ``The current video marketplace provides so many opportunites for
establishing alternative network-type systems for the delivery of
video programming that existing networks will not be able to
foreclose the entry of new networks in the future,'' the commission
said.
   Without the rule, new networks may find it easier to attract
capital and advertisers if they can attract a stable crop of
affiliates, the FCC said.
   ``Elimination of the rule may, in fact, facilitate new entry and
thereby enhance competition and provide even greater program
diversity to the public,'' the agency said.
   Longer contracts may permit a more solid financial base for
networks, and affiliates with longer contracts will have a long-term
guarantee of programming that may make it easier for them to attract
advertisers, the commission said.
</TEXT>
