<FIRST>u f AM-IBMForecast 1stLd-Writethru   03-17 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Forecast, 1st Ld-Writethru,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Says Chip Problem Will Hurt First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of IBM spokesman in 10th graf, Judice sted Thonis.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s stock
plunged and helped pull down the Dow Jones industrial average Friday
after the company said it expected its first-quarter profit to be
below security analysts' estimates.
   IBM attributed the earnings disappointment to a chip problem that
delayed delivery of some computers in its 3090S mainframe line and
said the problem had been fixed.
   IBM's stock sank $5.62{ a share to $112.50 _ a drop of nearly 5
percent _ in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. IBM's
drop added to the decline in the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial
stocks, which had already been hammered by a report of a jump in
wholesale prices.
   A $5.62{ drop in IBM's price translates into an 8-point drop in
the Dow average. Overall, the average fell 48.57 points to 2,292.14.
   The decline in IBM's price occurred even though the company
simultaneously announced plans to increase prices for most of its
products and services by nearly 5 percent, effective immediately.
Higher prices would tend to increase revenue and profitability.
   IBM had acknowledged earlier this month that a chip problem was
delaying delivery of its big mainframe computers but at the time had
said it could not determine what effect, if any, there would be on
its quarterly results.
   It said it now had enough information to predict earnings below
analysts' forecasts. But the statement was ambiguous because it did
not specify which forecasts it would be below, said analyst Wendy
Abramowitz of Argus Research Corp. She noted that quarterly
forecasts range from $1.65 to $2.15 per share.
   Zacks Investment Research Inc. of Chicago said the consensus
earnings forecast of the analysts who report their results to it is
$1.79 a share for the first quarter and $10.98 for 1989 as a whole.
   That compares with IBM's actual earnings of $1.53 in the first
quarter of 1988 and $9.80 a share for 1988.
   IBM spokesman Peter Judice said the production problem involved
chips manufactured by IBM. A shortage of usable chips caused delays
in assembly and shipping of the mainframe computers they go into, he
said. He declined to be more specific.
   ``The chip problem that occurred earlier in the quarter has been
fixed, and the company is working hard to minimize any inconvenience
to customers,'' IBM said in a statement.
   For the year as a whole, IBM said, the delivery delays will make
it more difficult for IBM to achieve the higher end of the range of
analysts' earnings estimates. Those estimates range as high as
$11.80 a share.
   Excluded from the 5 percent price increase announced Friday are
Personal System-2 personal computers and base-layer system software;
maintenance agreement prices on all products; and recently announced
products and price changes, including the new Enterprise System-3090
Model 100S and newly introduced models of the Application System-400.
   Thonis said it was a coincidence that the earnings comment and
the price increase were released on the same day.
</TEXT>
