<FIRST>r f BC-GinnieMae-Heights     03-17 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ginnie Mae-Heights,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Takes Control Of Thrift Portfolio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Government National Mortgage Association has
seized control of a $2.4 billion portfolio of loans from Heights of
Texas FSB, a thrift formed last year from four insolvent
institutions, federal officials said.
   The federal agency, known as Ginnie Mae, took over administration
of the portfolio after Houston-based Heights did not pass through
mortgage payments to investors who own the loans, said agency
spokesman Jack Flynn.
   The takeover ranks as the biggest single default for the agency,
The Dallas Morning News reported Thursday. The agency already has
contributed $15 million to make up for shortfalls in the payments,
Flynn said.
   Ginnie Mae, part of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development, insures securities backed by home mortgages. Lenders
pool their loans for sale to investors in secondary markets,
providing fesh cash to the institutions to make new mortgages.
   However, the thrifts usually retain servicing rights, including
the collection of mortgage payments for disbursement to holders of
the Ginnie Mae securities.
   Ginnie Mae only insures payments on loans already insured by the
Federal Housing Administration or guaranteed by the Veterans
Administration. But those two agencies have increasingly refused to
take back homes, choosing instead to reimburse lenders at a flat
rate.
</TEXT>
