<DOCNO> AP890317-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Burr Bjt   03-17 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Burr, Bjt,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burr: Eastern Crisis Raises Specter of Re-Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of now-defunct People Express
Airlines says the labor crisis gripping Eastern Airlines has raised
the prospect that the government will try to re-regulate the airline
industry that it opened up a decade ago _ a task he says the
government is ill-equipped to handle.
   Donald C. Burr, the founder of People Express and former employee
of Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, says the government
already is failing to oversee the industry adequately and would be
unable to do so if it again re-imposed stiff regulations on fares.
   Eastern has been virtually grounded by a two-week-old strike by
its Machinists union, which has been supported by most of the
airline's pilots and flight attendants. The near shutdown of its
operations forced the carrier to file for bankruptcy protection from
creditors on March 9.
   The possible disappearance of Eastern from the skies and the
temptation for its rivals to hike fares has given rise to public
debate about competition within the industry _ and, Burr said in an
interview Thursday, has raised the prospect of re-regulation.
   The federal government deregulated fare competition in the
airline industry in 1978, giving rise to cut-rate carriers such as
People Express.
   Burr, 47, a graduate of Harvard Business School, has placed
himself in the public eye again after about two years of shunning
the press and the spotlight. That fueled speculation he could be
putting himself forward as a possible participant in an Eastern
buyout.
   Burr said he would ``have to consider it'' if the Eastern unions
approached him about leading a buyout, but he stressed that is not
his primary intention.
   ``I've been president of three companies; I've already done
that,'' he said. ``I'm after the same things I've been after my
whole lifetime ... I would love to see the airline industry evolve
toward high-commitment service organizations.''
   Burr said he has talked about broad concepts with Lorenzo from
time to time before the Eastern strike that started March 4.
   Despite Eastern's travails, deregulation on the whole has been
``a stunning success'' that has opened air travel to more Americans,
Burr said. ``It freed the industry to be marketplace-oriented.''
   Burr quit his job as president of Texas International, Texas
Air's predecessor, in January 1980 to start up no-frills People
Express.
   Spurred by the removal of federal restrictions on fares, the
discount carrier quickly grew, by Burr's reckoning, into the world's
fifth-largest airline with revenue of about $2 billion at its peak
in the summer of 1985.
   People Express eventually was defeated by competitors who were
able to match and undercut its fares _ in addition to offering
full-fare services _ and to offer their own powerful computer
reservations systems, said Burr, who sold People Express to Texas
Air for $300 million in September 1986.
   His faith in deregulation undaunted by the experience, Burr
points to Lorenzo as the current ``low-cost warhound.''
   If Lorenzo's Eastern and sister carrier Continental Airlines
fail, ``we would lose the last major low-cost product,'' Burr warned.
   That event also could open the field to a new low-cost carrier _
which some observers say Burr might be inclined to start up.
   He currently is writing a book on People Express and lectures at
several universities, including Harvard, Stanford, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and the University of North Carolina. He
says he also has looked at possible new airline deals from time to
time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
