<DOCNO> AP890317-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-89 1938EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-17 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening Slide Prompts Use of `Circuit-Breaker' for S &amp; P 500s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock index futures plunged Friday under the weight of a
fast-falling stock market, prompting the first use of a trading
limit designed to halt panic sell-offs that had been put in place
after the October 1987 crash.
   On other markets, crude oil futures posted another strong gain,
but the rest of the complex slipped; precious metal futures advanced
slightly; and livestock and pork futures were mixed.
   The Standard &amp; Poors 500 stock index futures opened limit-down
and prompted the first use of a so-called circuit-breaker that was
designed to halt panic sell-offs.
   ``There was panic-type selling at the opening, and after the
limit, fear to enter the market for nearly five hours,'' said Roy
Postel, analyst with IDE Reports Inc. ``But looking back, I'd call
it an orderly sell-off in all respects.''
   A larger-than-expected 1 percent increase in wholesale prices
slammed the stock market at the opening bell, and the S&amp;P 500
futures contract for June on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange opened
simultaneously down 5 points.
   Merc officials responded by imposing a 10-minute trading limit on
the contract, following the terms of an agreement with the New York
Stock Exchange designed to prevent free-falling prices.
   The agreement, which calls for limits of trading of varying time
depending on how steeply prices fall, is triggered at the Merc
before the NYSE because of the quicker access to the futures
contracts than stock issues.
   After the circuit-breaker was lifted, the S&amp;P 500 contract
tumbled another three points, and moving in lockstep with the stock
market it tracks, stablized until about 1 p.m. EST.
   ``That's when word came out that IBM was going to have trouble
delivering a product line on time and hurt its earning prospects,
and the bargain hunters who were buying left about the same time,''
said Bob Ray, of Dean Witter Reynolds in Chicago. ``We hit the lows
about a half-hour later, and pared back a little from then on out.''
   The S&amp;P 500 futures index settled 8.4 points to 8.5 points lower,
with June contract at 295.45.
   Crude oil, meanwhile, continued its steady climb at the New York
Mercantile Exchange. Unlike earlier in the week, however, heating
oil and unleaded gasoline failed to follow the move higher because
of adequate supplies and slackening demand for the products.
   Crude oil was 1 cent lower to 49 cents higher, with the April
contract crashing what some traders called an important
psychological barrier at $20 and settling at $20.33 a barrel;
heating oil was .03 cent to .26 cent lower, with April at 53.57
cents a barrel; and unleaded gasoline was .27 cent lower to .26 cent
higher, with April at 55.62 cents a gallon.
   Gold, silver and platinum futures all posted moderate gains, but
a number of traders were puzzled why the precious metals didn't
advance further in the wake of the inflationary implications of the
rise in wholesale prices.
   ``I think the problem is the market is still getting mixed
signals on inflation,'' said Peter Cardillo, commodity trading
adviser for Josephthal &amp; Co., New York. ``At the beginning of the
week, most of the (economic) indicators pointed to slowing growth. I
think the $64,000 question in the precious metals is will we see
slower growth in the next two or three months.''
   Gold settled $3.70 to $5.70 higher on the Comex, with the March
contract at $393.60 a troy ounce; silver was 6.5 cents to 10.2 cents
higher, with March at $6.124 a troy ounce. Platinum, traded on the
New York Merc, was $4.60 higher across the board, with April at
$550.10 a troy ounce.
   The livestock market on the Chicago Merc opened under pressure
because of a government cattle-on-feedlot report released after the
markets closed Thursday showed a record number of placements for
Feburary.
   But traders betting that slack demand will pick up after Easter
helped rally the April contract, and that forced those who were
holding contracts for the deferred months back into the market.
   Exactly the opposite situation prevailed in the hog contracts.
With several influential analysts predicting a USDA report on hogs
due March 31 will show some supply tightness later this year or
early 1990, traders flocked to the later month contracts.
   Live cattle settled .23 cent lower to .70 cent higher, with April
at 78.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .93 cent lower to .15
cent higher, with March at 79.67 cents a pound; hogs were .58 cent
lower to .15 cent higher, with April at 42.72 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .70 cent higher, with
March at 36.95 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures prices closed mostly higher, but wheat and corn
mixed Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   On the close, wheat was 3 cents lower to } cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.34 a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to { cent higher, with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to { cent higher, with March at $2.08 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1 cent lower to 6} cents higher, with March at $7.69{
a bushel.
</TEXT>
