<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-17 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Judge Upholds Polaroid's Stock Ownership Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge ruled Friday that Polaroid Corp.
can go ahead with its plan to buy back 22 percent of its shares and
reaffirmed the company's controversial employee stock ownership plan.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc., which is trying to take over Polaroid,
had sought an injunction against the stock buyback plan, which it
said would stack the deck in favor of Polaroid's current management
in a proxy fight.
   Vice Chancellor Carolyn Berger issued the rulings in Delaware
Chancery Court.
   Polaroid has been resisting Shamrock's hostile takeover bid since
July, when the Burbank, Calif., company made a friendly but
unsolicited offer of $40 a share. In January, Shamrock increased the
bid to $45, valued at $3.2 billion.
   Last July, Polaroid put 9.7 million shares into an employee stock
ownership plan. In January, the company announced a recapitalization
plan that included selling $300 million of stock to Corporate
Partners L.P., a private investment group.
   Shamrock, a radio and television concern owned by the Roy E.
Disney family, owns about 4.8 million shares of Polaroid and is
waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the
May 9 annual meeting.
</TEXT>
